es| ]]\n[[Category:Progressive Era in the United States]]\n[[Category:Great Depression in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1918\u20131945)]]\n[[Category:Roaring Twenties]]\n[[Category:1920s in the United States]]\n[[Category:1930 in the United States]]\n[[Category:1931 in the United States]]\n[[Category:1932 in the United States]]\n[[Category:1933 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:1920 introductions]]\n", "name_user": "Radambc", "label": "safe", "comment": "centuy - centuries", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prohibition_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "The Great American Bash (2005)", "text_new": "{{short description|2005 World Wrestling Entertainment pay-per-view event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n| name       = The Great American Bash (2005)\n| image      = GreatAmericanBash2005.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Torrie Wilson]]\n| promotion  = [[World Wrestling Entertainment]]\n| brand      = [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]]\n| date       = July 24, 2005\n| venue      = [[KeyBank Center|HSBC Arena]]\n| city       = [[Buffalo, New York]]\n| attendance = 8,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=3027|title=WWE The Great American Bash 2005 \u00ab Events Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|work=www.cagematch.net|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n| buyrate    = 233,000\n| lastevent  = [[Vengeance (2005)|Vengeance]]\n| nextevent  = [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]]\n| event      = [[WWE The Great American Bash|The Great American Bash]]\n| nextevent2 = [[The Great American Bash (2006)|2006]]\n| lastevent2 = [[The Great American Bash (2004)|2004]]\n}}\n'''The Great American Bash (2005)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of WWE pay-per-view events|event]] produced by [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE). It was the 16th annual event and took place on July 24, 2005, at the [[KeyBank Center|HSBC Arena]] in [[Buffalo, New York]]. The event featured wrestlers and other talent that performed on the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]] program.\n\nThe [[main event]] was [[Dave Batista|Batista]] defending the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] against [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (JBL). JBL won the match after Batista was [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualified]], but did not win the title because a championship can only be won via [[pin (professional wrestling)|pinfall]] or [[Professional wrestling#Submission|submission]]. One of the featured matches on the [[undercard]] was [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] versus [[Eddie Guerrero]], which Mysterio won by pinfall. The other was [[Orlando Jordan]] versus [[Chris Benoit]] for the [[WWE United States Championship]], which Jordan won, also by pinfall.\n\nThe event grossed over US$375,000 in ticket sales from an attendance of 8,000, and received about 233,000&nbsp;pay-per-view buys, the same amount as the [[The Great American Bash (2006)|following year's event]]. This enabled WWE's pay-per-view revenue to increase by $4.7&nbsp;million from the previous year. When the 2005 event was released on [[DVD]], it reached a peak position of second on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s DVD Sales Chart. The event was also available free of charge for [[Military of the United States|Armed Forces]] members and their families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2005/wwe-corporate-wwe-and-american-forces-network-partner-to-provide-the-great-american-bash-pay-per-view-free-to-troops|title=WWE and American Forces Network Partner To Provide The Great American Bash Pay-Per-View Free To Troops.|date=2005-07-19|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2008-08-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310103626/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2005/wwe-corporate-wwe-and-american-forces-network-partner-to-provide-the-great-american-bash-pay-per-view-free-to-troops|archivedate=2016-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Storylines==\nThe Great American Bash event featured a [[card (professional wrestling)|card]], which contained matches that involved different wrestlers from pre-existing [[Teleplay|scripted]] feuds, [[plot (narrative)|plots]] and [[narrative|storylines]]. Wrestlers portrayed either a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] or [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] gimmick as they followed a series of events which generally built tension, leading to a wrestling match. The name of a wrestler's character was not always the person's [[birth name]], as wrestlers often use a [[stage name]] to portray their character.\n\n[[File:Batistalive.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Batista faced JBL for the World Heavyweight Championship]]\nThe [[main event]] at The Great American Bash was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|standard wrestling match]] for the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]], in which [[Dave Batista|Batista]] defended the championship against [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (JBL). The buildup to the match began when [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]] [[John Cena]] was drafted to the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] brand, taking the title with him and leaving SmackDown! without a top-tier championship for the heavyweight division. [[Professional wrestling authority figures#General Managers 2|General Manager]] [[Theodore Long]], a portrayed match maker and rules enforcer, announced a match between six wrestlers for a new top-tier SmackDown! championship. On the June 30 episode of the ''SmackDown!'' television program, the match took place between JBL, [[Chris Benoit]], [[Christian (wrestler)|Christian]], [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]], [[Mark Copani|Muhammad Hassan]], and [[The Undertaker]]. JBL was victorious in the match, but Long announced that he was still not the champion. Instead he had won the right to a match against the World Heavyweight Champion, Batista, who was SmackDown!'s final 2005 draft pick, making the World Heavyweight Championship exclusive to SmackDown!.<ref name=June30>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1120189728.shtml|title=SmackDown Results&nbsp;\u2013 6/30/05&nbsp;\u2013 Anaheim, CA (Final two draft picks)|last=Carrington| first=L. Anne|date=2005-06-30|publisher= WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref><ref name=June30WWE>{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/06302005/mainarticle/|title=JACKPOT!|date=2005-06-30|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]| accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> On the July 14 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Batista defeated [[Orlando Jordan]] in a standard match after performing a [[Batista Bomb]]. After the match, JBL successfully attacked Batista by executing a [[A double clothesline|clothesline]].<ref name=July14>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/07/15/1132138.html| title=Smackdown: A legend returns, Bash takes shape|date=2005-07-14|last=Plummer|first=Dale|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]| accessdate=2008-08-02}}</ref><ref name=July14WWE>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07142005/mainarticle/|title=JBL's stand|date=2005-07-14|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The following week on ''SmackDown!'', JBL, who was accompanied by Jordan, threw himself a celebration party with the belief that he had already won the World Heavyweight Championship. Batista appeared, and as JBL fled the scene, performed a [[spinebuster]] on Jordan.<ref name=July21>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/07/22/pf-1142829.html|title=Smackdown: JBL's bash ruined by Batista|date=2005-07-21|last=Sokol|first=Chris|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=2008-08-02}}</ref><ref name=July21WWE>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07212005/mainarticle/|title=JBL guarantees victory|date= 2005-07-21|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThe event also featured a feud between [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] and [[Eddie Guerrero]]. At the [[No Way Out (2005)|No Way Out]] event, Guerrero and Mysterio won the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championships]] from the [[Basham Brothers]]. After Guerrero and Mysterio lost the championships, Guerrero then began to portray a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] character, [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Turn|turning]] on Mysterio in the process. At [[WrestleMania 21|WrestleMania]], Mysterio defeated Guerrero in a standard match.<ref name=\"WrestleMania21\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm21/results/ |title=WrestleMania 21 Results |date=2005-04-03 |accessdate=2008-07-19 |publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080327053358/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm21/results/ |archivedate=March 27, 2008 }}</ref> On the April 21 episode of ''SmackDown!'', [[MNM (wrestling)|MNM]] ([[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]] and [[Adam Birch|Joey Mercury]]) defeated Mysterio and Guerrero to win the tag team championship.<ref name=\"April 21, 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1145769231.shtml|title=WWE SmackDown! results|accessdate=2008-08-03|date=2005-04-22|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref><ref name=\"April21WWE\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/04212005/mainarticle/|title=His Time Is Now|accessdate =2008-07-19|date=2005-04-21|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> On the April 28 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Guerrero and Mysterio faced MNM in a rematch for the title, but MNM retained them after pinning Mysterio for the win.<ref name=\"April 28, 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1146279418.shtml|title=The Dream stays alive|last=Dee|first=Louie|accessdate=2008-08-03|publisher= WrestleView}}</ref><ref name=\"April28WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/04282005/mainarticle/|title=Second Chance| accessdate=2008-07-19|date=2005-04-28|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At the [[Judgment Day (2005)|Judgment Day]] event, Mysterio defeated Guerrero by disqualification, and on the June 30 episode of ''SmackDown!'', the rivalry between Guerrero and Mysterio continued when Guerrero threatened to reveal a secret concerning Mysterio's son Dominick.<ref name=June30 /><ref name=June30WWE /> Both the Mysterio and Guerrero families continued to beg Guerrero to not reveal the secret.<ref name=Secret>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07142005/mainarticle/|title=JBL'S Stand|date=2005-07-14|accessdate= 2008-08-02|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> A match was made between Mysterio and Guerrero for The Great American Bash, where if Mysterio won, Guerrero could not reveal the secret, but if Guerrero won, he would be able to reveal the secret on live television.<ref name=Secret />\n\nThe third predominant feud prior to the event was between Chris Benoit and Orlando Jordan for the [[WWE United States Championship]]. On the July 7 edition of ''SmackDown!'', Benoit defeated Booker T in a match to become the #1 contender for the title.<ref name=July7>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07072005/mainarticle/|title=Showdown Looming|date= 2005-07-07|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=July7Canoe>{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/07/08/1122701.html|title=Smackdown: BWO triumphs; terrorist angle airs|date=2005-07-07| last=Sokol|first=Chris|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=2008-08-02}}</ref> Long granted Benoit a match against Jordan for The Great American Bash.<ref name=July7/>\n\n==Event==\nBefore the pay-per-view went live, a match took place on the ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' pre-show between [[Paul London]] and [[James Maritato|Nunzio]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]], which London won to retain the title.<ref name=WrestleViewresults>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1122259923.shtml|title=WWE's The Great American Bash (SmackDown) PPV Results&nbsp;\u2013 7/24/05|publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=2005-07-24|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+Other on-screen personnel\n|-\n!Role:\n!Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=2|English [[Sports commentator|commentators]]\n|[[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]] \n|-\n|[[Tazz]] \n|-\n|rowspan=2|Spanish commentators\n|[[Carlos Cabrera]]\n|-\n|[[Hugo Savinovich]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Interview]]ers\n|[[Josh Mathews]] \n|-\n|Steve Romero\n|-\n|[[Ring announcer]]\n|[[Tony Chimel]] \n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Referee (professional wrestling)|Referees]]\n|[[Nick Hamilton|Nick Patrick]] \n|-\n|[[Charles Robinson (referee)|Charles Robinson]] \n|-\n|[[Earl Hebner|Brian Hebner]] \n|-\n|[[Jim Korderas]] \n|}\n\n===Preliminary matches===\n[[File:Christian20061020.jpg|right|upright|thumb|Christian faced Booker T at The Great American Bash]]\nThe first match on the card was between MNM (Johnny Nitro and Joey Mercury, managed by [[Melina Perez|Melina]]) and [[The Road Warriors#L.O.D. 2005 (2005\u20132006)|The Legion of Doom]] ([[Jon Heidenreich|Heidenreich]] and [[Road Warrior Animal]]) for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]]. During the match, Nitro hit Animal with one of the championship belts, but Animal retaliated by [[powerslam]]ming him. Animal and Heidenreich then performed the [[Doomsday Device (wrestling)|doomsday device]] on Nitro and scored the [[pin (professional wrestling)|pin]] to win the match and the titles.<ref name=WWEresults>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/results/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331125323/http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/results/|archivedate=2008-03-31|title=WWE Great American Bash 2005 results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=2005-07-24|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwetag/|title=WWE Tag Team Championship|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThe next match was between [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (managed by [[Sharmell Sullivan|Sharmell]]) and [[Christian (wrestler)|Christian]]. Booker T won the match after performing a [[scissor kick (strike)|scissors kick]].<ref name=WWEresults />\n\nIn the next match, [[Orlando Jordan]] faced [[Chris Benoit]] for the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]]. During the match, Jordan removed the top turnbuckle pad. Benoit attempted to slam Jordan but Jordan avoided the attack and instead forced Benoit to run into the exposed turnbuckle. Jordan scored the pin to win the match and retain the title.<ref name=WWEresults />\n\nThe fourth match was between [[The Undertaker]] and [[Muhammad Hassan (wrestler)|Muhammad Hassan]] (managed by [[Shawn Daivari|Daivari]]) to determine the #1 contender for the World Heavyweight Championship. During Hassan's entrance, men in masks accompanied him to the ring to represent his Arabic culture. The masked men proceeded to interfered in the match, but Undertaker retaliated and removed all of the masked men from the ring. Midway through the match, Undertaker attempted to use a [[Tombstone piledriver]] on Hassan, but Hassan escaped the move and attempted a Clothesline. The Undertaker countered by [[chokeslam]]ming Hassan and scored the pinfall on Hassan to win the match and become the #1 contender. Following this, Undertaker executed a Last Ride through the stage floor on Hassan, writing him out of storylines.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results>{{cite web|url=http://pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/july/2005.htm|title=WWE Great American Bash 2005|publisher=PWWEW.net|date=2005-07-24|accessdate=2008-07-18}}</ref>\n\nThe next match was between [[The Mexicools]] and [[The Blue World Order]] in a six-man [[tag team]] match. At the match's end, [[Super Crazy]] executed a [[moonsault]] onto [[Stevie Richards|Big Stevie Cool]] from the top ring rope, and [[Psicosis]] performed a [[leg drop]]. Psicosis proceeded to pin Big Stevie and win the match for his team.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results />\n\n===Main event matches===\n[[File:Eddie Guerrero on SmackDown cropped.jpg|upright|thumb|right|Eddie Guerrero faced Rey Mysterio at The Great American Bash]]\nThe following match was between [[Rey Mysterio]] and [[Eddie Guerrero]], where the stipulation was that if Guerrero won the match, he would reveal the secret he has been hiding from the public that neither Mysterio's nor Guerrero's families wanted revealed. If Mysterio won, however, Guerrero would not reveal the secret. Guerrero executed the Three Amigos on Mysterio and performed a [[frog splash]]. Guerrero then tried to score the pinfall, but Mysterio countered by pinning Guerrero to win the match. As a result, Guerrero was not able to reveal the secret.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results />\n\nThe seventh match was between [[Melina Perez|Melina]] and [[Torrie Wilson]] with [[Candice Michelle]], as the [[professional wrestling match types#Special referee|guest referee]], in a [[Bra and Panties Match|Bra and Panties match]]. The only way to win a \"Bra and Panties\" match is for a wrestler to strip her opponent down to her underwear. At the start of the match, Wilson pulled off Melina's shirt to reveal her bra, but Melina retaliated and pulled off Wilson's shirt. Wilson then lifted Melina to her shoulders and dropped her to the mat, while she attempted to pull off her pants, but Melina countered the attack by pulling Wilson's pants off to win the match. Afterward, Michelle stripped Melina and then removed her own clothes, as well.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results />\n\nThe [[main event]] was between [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[John Layfield|JBL]] (managed by Orlando Jordan) for the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]]. Jordan interfered by attempting to hit Batista with a [[folding chair]], but Batista grabbed the chair from him. Batista then used the chair to hit Jordan and JBL, and JBL was declared the winner, via disqualification. In WWE, a title cannot be won by disqualification, but only by pinfall or submission (the normal scoring conditions in professional wrestling matches). As a result, Batista retained the title.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results /><ref name=mainevent>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/mainevent/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331125318/http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/mainevent/|archivedate=2008-03-31|title=Batista vs. JBL for the World Heavyweight Championship|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=2005-07-22|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> After the match Batista gave JBL and Jordan a Batista Bomb.\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe feud between Batista and JBL continued after the Bash. On the July 28 episode of ''SmackDown!'', JBL defeated The Undertaker after interference from Randy Orton to become the number-one contender for the World Heavyweight Championship at [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]].<ref name=July28>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1122611986.shtml|title=JBL going to SummerSlam|date=2005-07-29| publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> The following week on ''SmackDown!'', Batista and JBL held a scripted official contract signing, where it was announced that their match at SummerSlam would be a [[Professional wrestling match types#No Disqualification match|No Holds Barred match]] that allowed for no disqualification.<ref name=August4>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1123209690.shtml|title=SmackDown Results&nbsp;\u2013 8/04/05&nbsp;\u2013 Bridgeport, CT (Tag Titles and more)|date=2005-08-04|publisher=WrestleView|last=Allen|first=Ryan|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> At SummerSlam, Batista defeated JBL to retain the World Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=SummerSlam>{{cite web|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1124679610.shtml|title=WWE SummerSlam (RAW/SmackDown) PPV Results&nbsp;\u2013 8/21/05|date=2005-08-21| last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> The feud between the two ended when Batista defeated JBL in a [[Texas Bullrope Match|Texas Bullrope match]] on the September 9 edition of ''SmackDown!'', a match where the objective is to touch all four ring corners while tied to one's opponent with a bullrope.<ref name=September9>{{cite web| url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1126326583.shtml|title=Changing Friday nights|last=Martin|first= Adam|date=2005-09-09|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref>\n\nOn the edition of ''SmackDown!'' following The Great American Bash, Eddie Guerrero revealed the secret he had been keeping; he was Dominick's real father, not Rey Mysterio (was thought to be).<ref name=July28 /> At SummerSlam, Mysterio defeated Guerrero in a ladder match, where the goal is to climb a ladder to retrieve an object that is suspended in the air. As per pre-match stipulations, Mysterio gained complete [[Child custody|custody]] of Dominick.<ref name=SummerSlam /> On the September 9 edition of ''SmackDown!'', Guerrero defeated Mysterio in a [[steel cage]] match to end the feud.<ref name=September9 /> Guerrero then began a feud with Batista when Guerrero was given a title match at [[No Mercy (2005)|No Mercy]].<ref name=NoMercy>{{cite web|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1128912495.shtml|title=WWE No Mercy (SmackDown) PPV Results&nbsp;\u2013 10/9/05|last=Martin|first=Adam| date=2005-10-09|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> Guerrero, however, died unexpectedly of [[heart failure]] on November 13, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1131910843.shtml|title=Another update on the passing of Eddie Guerrero; heart failure possible|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|date=2005-11-13}}</ref> In 2006 Guerrero was inducted into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] by Mysterio, his nephew [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]], and Chris Benoit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/halloffame/eddieguerrero/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331130442/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/halloffame/eddieguerrero/|archivedate=2008-03-31|title=Eddie Guerrero|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-09-10}}</ref>\n\nThe feud between Chris Benoit and Orlando Jordan continued. At SummerSlam, Benoit defeated Jordan for the WWE United States Championship in a match that lasted 25.5 seconds.<ref name=SummerSlam /> On the September 1 edition of ''SmackDown!'', Benoit once again defeated Jordan for the title, but this time the match lasted 23.4 seconds.<ref name=September1>{{cite web|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1125630281.shtml|title=Another Assist From Dad|last=Martin|first= Adam|date=2005-09-09|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> The following week on ''SmackDown!'', Benoit defeated Jordan in another title match, where the match lasted 22.5 seconds.<ref name=September9 />\n\n==Reception==\nThe HSBC Arena has a maximum capacity of 18,690,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsbcarena.com/quickfacts.cfm|title=Quick Facts|publisher=HSBC Arena|accessdate=2008-08-25| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080224064908/http://www.hsbcarena.com/quickfacts.cfm| archivedate = February 24, 2008}}</ref> but it was reduced for The Great American Bash. The event grossed over $375,000 in ticket sales from an attendance of 8,000, the maximum allowed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/wwe-pay-per-view/the-great-american-bash-2005/episode/387116/summary.html|title=Great American Bash 2005|publisher=TV.com|accessdate=2008-08-02}}</ref> The event resulted in 233,000 pay-per-view buys, which was the same amount as the [[The Great American Bash (2006)|following year's Great American Bash]]. The promotion's pay-per-view revenue was $21.6&nbsp;million, greater than the previous year's revenue of $16.9&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/documents/1QFY2006EarningsRelease-FINAL.pdf |title=WWE Reports Fiscal 2006 First Quarter Results |publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] Corporate |accessdate=2008-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202042056/http://corporate.wwe.com./news/documents/1QFY2006EarningsRelease-FINAL.pdf |archivedate=December 2, 2008 }}</ref> The event was widely criticized by fans and critics alike. ''[[Canadian Online Explorer]]'''s professional wrestling section rated the event a five out of ten.<ref name=Slam>{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2005/07/25/1146844.html|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|title=JBL reigns at a dull Bash|last=Kapur|first=Bob|accessdate=2008-08-01}}</ref> The World Heavyweight Championship main event match was rated three out of ten, and the match between Rey Mysterio and Eddie Guerrero received the highest match rating of eight out of ten.<ref name=Slam />\n\nThe event was released on [[DVD]] on August 23, 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fye.com/WWE--The-Great-American-Bash-Front-Page_stcVVproductId3417525VVcatId455366VVviewprod.htm |title=WWE: The Great American Bash |publisher=[[Trans World Entertainment|For Your Entertainment]] |accessdate=2008-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924002559/http://www.fye.com/WWE--The-Great-American-Bash-Front-Page_stcVVproductId3417525VVcatId455366VVviewprod.htm |archivedate=September 24, 2008 }}</ref> by [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. The DVD reached seventh on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s DVD Sales Chart for recreational sports during the week of October 8, 2005, and it rose to the fourth spot the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3061521&cdi=8443398&cid=10%2F08%2F2005 |title=Video Sales\u2014Recreational Sports DVD |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].com |accessdate=2008-08-01 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> It remained on the chart's \"top ten\" for four consecutive weeks, until the week of December 15, 2005, when it ranked thirteenth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3061696&cdi=8450166&cid=10%2F15%2F2005 |title=Video Sales\u2014Recreational Sports DVD |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].com |accessdate=2008-08-01 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|heat1  = yes\n|match1 = [[Paul London]] (c) defeated [[James Maritato|Nunzio]]\n|stip1  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|time1  = 02:33\n|match2 = [[The Road Warriors#L.O.D. 2005 (2005\u20132006)|The Legion of Doom]] ([[Road Warrior Animal|Animal]] and [[Jon Heidenreich|Heidenreich]]) defeated [[MNM (professional wrestling)|MNM]] ([[Joey Mercury]] and [[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]) (c) (with [[Melina Perez|Melina]]) \n|stip2  = [[Tag team match]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]]\n|time2  = 06:45\n|match3 = [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (with [[Sharmell]]) defeated [[Christian Cage|Christian]]\n|stip3  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time3  = 11:52\n|match4 = [[Orlando Jordan]] (c) defeated [[Chris Benoit]]\n|stip4  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE United States Championship]]\n|time4  = 14:23\n|match5 = [[The Undertaker]] defeated [[Muhammad Hassan (wrestler)|Muhammad Hassan]] (with [[Shawn Daivari|Daivari]])\n|stip5  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] to determine the #1 contender for the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] at [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]]\n|time5  = 08:04\n|match6 = [[The Mexicools]] ([[Juventud Guerrera|Juventud]], [[Psicosis]] and [[Super Crazy]]) defeated [[The bWo]] ([[Big Stevie Cool]], [[The Blue Meanie]] and [[Hollywood Nova]])\n|stip6  = [[Six-man tag team match]]\n|time6  = 04:53\n|match7 = [[Rey Mysterio]] defeated [[Eddie Guerrero]]\n|stip7  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]; had Mysterio lost, Guerrero would\u2019ve revealed his secret on live television \n|time7  = 15:39\n|match8 = [[Melina Perez|Melina]] defeated [[Torrie Wilson]]\n|stip8  = [[Bra and Panties match]] with [[Candice Michelle]] as [[special guest referee]]\n|time8  = 03:53\n|match9 = [[John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (with [[Orlando Jordan]]) defeated [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] (c) by [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]]\n|stip9  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the World Heavyweight Championship\n|time9  = 19:47\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080319091728/http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/ Official Great American Bash 2005 website]\n* {{imdb episode|0457194}}\n\n{{2005 WWE pay-per-view events}}\n{{WWEPPV|The Great American Bash}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great American Bash (2005), The}}\n[[Category:2005 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Events in Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:The Great American Bash|2005]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:2005 WWE pay-per-view events]]\n[[Category:July 2005 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2005 World Wrestling Entertainment pay-per-view event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n| name       = The Great American Bash (2005)\n| image      = GreatAmericanBash2005.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Torrie Wilson]]\n| promotion  = [[World Wrestling Entertainment]]\n| brand      = [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]]\n| date       = July 24, 2005\n| venue      = [[KeyBank Center|HSBC Arena]]\n| city       = [[Buffalo, New York]]\n| attendance = 8,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=3027|title=WWE The Great American Bash 2005 \u00ab Events Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|work=www.cagematch.net|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n| buyrate    = 233,000\n| lastevent  = [[Vengeance (2005)|Vengeance]]\n| nextevent  = [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]]\n| event      = [[WWE The Great American Bash|The Great American Bash]]\n| nextevent2 = [[The Great American Bash (2006)|2006]]\n| lastevent2 = [[The Great American Bash (2004)|2004]]\n}}\n'''The Great American Bash (2005)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of WWE pay-per-view events|event]] produced by [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE). It was the 16th annual event and took place on July 24, 2005, at the [[KeyBank Center|HSBC Arena]] in [[Buffalo, New York]]. The event featured wrestlers and other talent that performed on the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]] program.\n\nThe [[main event]] was [[Dave Batista|Batista]] defending the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] against [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (JBL). JBL won the match after Batista was [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualified]], but did not win the title because a championship can only be won via [[pin (professional wrestling)|pinfall]] or [[Professional wrestling#Submission|submission]]. One of the featured matches on the [[undercard]] was [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] versus [[Eddie Guerrero]], which Mysterio won by pinfall. The other was [[Orlando Jordan]] versus [[Chris Benoit]] for the [[WWE United States Championship]], which Jordan won, also by pinfall.\n\nThe event grossed over US$375,000 in ticket sales from an attendance of 8,000, and received about 233,000&nbsp;pay-per-view buys, the same amount as the [[The Great American Bash (2006)|following year's event]]. This enabled WWE's pay-per-view revenue to increase by $4.7&nbsp;million from the previous year. When the 2005 event was released on [[DVD]], it reached a peak position of second on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s DVD Sales Chart. The event was also available free of charge for [[Military of the United States|Armed Forces]] members and their families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2005/wwe-corporate-wwe-and-american-forces-network-partner-to-provide-the-great-american-bash-pay-per-view-free-to-troops|title=WWE and American Forces Network Partner To Provide The Great American Bash Pay-Per-View Free To Troops.|date=2005-07-19|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2008-08-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310103626/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2005/wwe-corporate-wwe-and-american-forces-network-partner-to-provide-the-great-american-bash-pay-per-view-free-to-troops|archivedate=2016-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Storylines==\nThe Great American Bash event featured a [[card (professional wrestling)|card]], which contained matches that involved different wrestlers from pre-existing [[Teleplay|scripted]] feuds, [[plot (narrative)|plots]] and [[narrative|storylines]]. Wrestlers portrayed either a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] or [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] gimmick as they followed a series of events which generally built tension, leading to a wrestling match. The name of a wrestler's character was not always the person's [[birth name]], as wrestlers often use a [[stage name]] to portray their character.\n\n[[File:Batistalive.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Batista faced JBL for the World Heavyweight Championship]]\nThe [[main event]] at The Great American Bash was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|standard wrestling match]] for the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]], in which [[Dave Batista|Batista]] defended the championship against [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (JBL). The buildup to the match began when [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]] [[John Cena]] was drafted to the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] brand, taking the title with him and leaving SmackDown! without a top-tier championship for the heavyweight division. [[Professional wrestling authority figures#General Managers 2|General Manager]] [[Theodore Long]], a portrayed match maker and rules enforcer, announced a match between six wrestlers for a new top-tier SmackDown! championship. On the June 30 episode of the ''SmackDown!'' television program, the match took place between JBL, [[Chris Benoit]], [[Christian (wrestler)|Christian]], [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]], [[Mark Copani|Muhammad Hassan]], and [[The Undertaker]]. JBL was victorious in the match, but Long announced that he was still not the champion. Instead he had won the right to a match against the World Heavyweight Champion, Batista, who was SmackDown!'s final 2005 draft pick, making the World Heavyweight Championship exclusive to SmackDown!.<ref name=June30>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1120189728.shtml|title=SmackDown Results&nbsp;\u2013 6/30/05&nbsp;\u2013 Anaheim, CA (Final two draft picks)|last=Carrington| first=L. Anne|date=2005-06-30|publisher= WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref><ref name=June30WWE>{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/06302005/mainarticle/|title=JACKPOT!|date=2005-06-30|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]| accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> On the July 14 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Batista defeated [[Orlando Jordan]] in a standard match after performing a [[Batista Bomb]]. After the match, JBL successfully attacked Batista by executing a [[A double clothesline|clothesline]].<ref name=July14>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/07/15/1132138.html| title=Smackdown: A legend returns, Bash takes shape|date=2005-07-14|last=Plummer|first=Dale|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]| accessdate=2008-08-02}}</ref><ref name=July14WWE>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07142005/mainarticle/|title=JBL's stand|date=2005-07-14|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The following week on ''SmackDown!'', JBL, who was accompanied by Jordan, threw himself a celebration party with the belief that he had already won the World Heavyweight Championship. Batista appeared, and as JBL fled the scene, performed a [[spinebuster]] on Jordan.<ref name=July21>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/07/22/pf-1142829.html|title=Smackdown: JBL's bash ruined by Batista|date=2005-07-21|last=Sokol|first=Chris|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=2008-08-02}}</ref><ref name=July21WWE>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07212005/mainarticle/|title=JBL guarantees victory|date= 2005-07-21|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThe event also featured a feud between [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] and [[Eddie Guerrero]]. At the [[No Way Out (2005)|No Way Out]] event, Guerrero and Mysterio won the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championships]] from the [[Basham Brothers]]. After Guerrero and Mysterio lost the championships, Guerrero then began to portray a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] character, [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Turn|turning]] on Mysterio in the process. At [[WrestleMania 21|WrestleMania]], Mysterio defeated Guerrero in a standard match.<ref name=\"WrestleMania21\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm21/results/ |title=WrestleMania 21 Results |date=2005-04-03 |accessdate=2008-07-19 |publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080327053358/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm21/results/ |archivedate=March 27, 2008 }}</ref> On the April 21 episode of ''SmackDown!'', [[MNM (wrestling)|MNM]] ([[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]] and [[Adam Birch|Joey Mercury]]) defeated Mysterio and Guerrero to win the tag team championship.<ref name=\"April 21, 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1145769231.shtml|title=WWE SmackDown! results|accessdate=2008-08-03|date=2005-04-22|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref><ref name=\"April21WWE\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/04212005/mainarticle/|title=His Time Is Now|accessdate =2008-07-19|date=2005-04-21|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> On the April 28 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Guerrero and Mysterio faced MNM in a rematch for the title, but MNM retained them after pinning Mysterio for the win.<ref name=\"April 28, 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1146279418.shtml|title=The Dream stays alive|last=Dee|first=Louie|accessdate=2008-08-03|publisher= WrestleView}}</ref><ref name=\"April28WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/04282005/mainarticle/|title=Second Chance| accessdate=2008-07-19|date=2005-04-28|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At the [[Judgment Day (2005)|Judgment Day]] event, Mysterio defeated Guerrero by disqualification, and on the June 30 episode of ''SmackDown!'', the rivalry between Guerrero and Mysterio continued when Guerrero threatened to reveal a secret concerning Mysterio's son Dominick.<ref name=June30 /><ref name=June30WWE /> Both the Mysterio and Guerrero families continued to beg Guerrero to not reveal the secret.<ref name=Secret>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07142005/mainarticle/|title=JBL'S Stand|date=2005-07-14|accessdate= 2008-08-02|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> A match was made between Mysterio and Guerrero for The Great American Bash, where if Mysterio won, Guerrero could not reveal the secret, but if Guerrero won, he would be able to reveal the secret on live television.<ref name=Secret />\n\nThe third predominant feud prior to the event was between Chris Benoit and Orlando Jordan for the [[WWE United States Championship]]. On the July 7 edition of ''SmackDown!'', Benoit defeated Booker T in a match to become the #1 contender for the title.<ref name=July7>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07072005/mainarticle/|title=Showdown Looming|date= 2005-07-07|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=July7Canoe>{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/07/08/1122701.html|title=Smackdown: BWO triumphs; terrorist angle airs|date=2005-07-07| last=Sokol|first=Chris|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=2008-08-02}}</ref> Long granted Benoit a match against Jordan for The Great American Bash.<ref name=July7/>\n\n==Event==\nBefore the pay-per-view went live, a match took place on the ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' pre-show between [[Paul London]] and [[James Maritato|Nunzio]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]], which London won to retain the title.<ref name=WrestleViewresults>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1122259923.shtml|title=WWE's The Great American Bash (SmackDown) PPV Results&nbsp;\u2013 7/24/05|publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=2005-07-24|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+Other on-screen personnel\n|-\n!Role:\n!Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=2|English [[Sports commentator|commentators]]\n|[[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]] \n|-\n|[[Tazz]] \n|-\n|rowspan=2|Spanish commentators\n|[[Carlos Cabrera]]\n|-\n|[[Hugo Savinovich]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Interview]]ers\n|[[Josh Mathews]] \n|-\n|Steve Romero\n|-\n|[[Ring announcer]]\n|[[Tony Chimel]] \n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Referee (professional wrestling)|Referees]]\n|[[Nick Hamilton|Nick Patrick]] \n|-\n|[[Charles Robinson (referee)|Charles Robinson]] \n|-\n|[[Earl Hebner|Brian Hebner]] \n|-\n|[[Jim Korderas]] \n|}\n\n===Preliminary matches===\n[[File:Christian20061020.jpg|right|upright|thumb|Christian faced Booker T at The Great American Bash]]\nThe first match on the card was between MNM (Johnny Nitro and Joey Mercury, managed by [[Melina Perez|Melina]]) and [[The Road Warriors#L.O.D. 2005 (2005\u20132006)|The Legion of Doom]] ([[Jon Heidenreich|Heidenreich]] and [[Road Warrior Animal]]) for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]]. During the match, Nitro hit Animal with one of the championship belts, but Animal retaliated by [[powerslam]]ming him. Animal and Heidenreich then performed the [[Doomsday Device (wrestling)|doomsday device]] on Nitro and scored the [[pin (professional wrestling)|pin]] to win the match and the titles.<ref name=WWEresults>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/results/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331125323/http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/results/|archivedate=2008-03-31|title=WWE Great American Bash 2005 results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=2005-07-24|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwetag/|title=WWE Tag Team Championship|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThe next match was between [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (managed by [[Sharmell Sullivan|Sharmell]]) and [[Christian (wrestler)|Christian]]. Booker T won the match after performing a [[scissor kick (strike)|scissors kick]].<ref name=WWEresults />\n\nIn the next match, [[Orlando Jordan]] faced [[Chris Benoit]] for the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]]. During the match, Jordan removed the top turnbuckle pad. Benoit attempted to slam Jordan but Jordan avoided the attack and instead forced Benoit to run into the exposed turnbuckle. Jordan scored the pin to win the match and retain the title.<ref name=WWEresults />\n\nThe fourth match was between [[The Undertaker]] and [[Muhammad Hassan (wrestler)|Muhammad Hassan]] (managed by [[Shawn Daivari|Daivari]]) to determine the #1 contender for the World Heavyweight Championship. During Hassan's entrance, men in masks accompanied him to the ring to represent his Arabic culture. The masked men proceeded to interfered in the match, but Undertaker retaliated and removed all of the masked men from the ring. Midway through the match, Undertaker attempted to use a [[Tombstone piledriver]] on Hassan, but Hassan escaped the move and attempted a Clothesline. The Undertaker countered by [[chokeslam]]ming Hassan and scored the pinfall on Hassan to win the match and become the #1 contender. Following this, Undertaker executed a Last Ride through the stage floor on Hassan, writing him out of storylines.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results>{{cite web|url=http://pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/july/2005.htm|title=WWE Great American Bash 2005|publisher=PWWEW.net|date=2005-07-24|accessdate=2008-07-18}}</ref>\n\nThe next match was between [[The Mexicools]] and [[The Blue World Order]] in a six-man [[tag team]] match. At the match's end, [[Super Crazy]] executed a [[moonsault]] onto [[Stevie Richards|Big Stevie Cool]] from the top ring rope, and [[Psicosis]] performed a [[leg drop]]. Psicosis proceeded to pin Big Stevie and win the match for his team.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results />\n\n===Main event matches===\n[[File:Eddie Guerrero on SmackDown cropped.jpg|upright|thumb|right|Eddie Guerrero faced Rey Mysterio at The Great American Bash]]\nThe following match was between [[Rey Mysterio]] and [[Eddie Guerrero]], where the stipulation was that if Guerrero won the match, he would reveal the secret he has been hiding from the public that neither Mysterio's nor Guerrero's families wanted revealed. If Mysterio won, however, Guerrero would not reveal the secret. Guerrero executed the Three Amigos on Mysterio and performed a [[frog splash]]. Guerrero then tried to score the pinfall, but Mysterio countered by pinning Guerrero to win the match. As a result, Guerrero was not able to reveal the secret.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results />\n\nThe seventh match was between [[Melina Perez|Melina]] and [[Torrie Wilson]] with [[Candice Michelle]], as the [[professional wrestling match types#Special referee|guest referee]], in a [[Bra and Panties Match|Bra and Panties match]]. The only way to win a \"Bra and Panties\" match is for a wrestler to strip her opponent down to her underwear. At the start of the match, Wilson pulled off Melina's shirt to reveal her bra, but Melina retaliated and pulled off Wilson's shirt. Wilson then lifted Melina to her shoulders and dropped her to the mat, while she attempted to pull off her pants, but Melina countered the attack by pulling Wilson's pants off to win the match. Afterward, Michelle stripped Melina and then removed her own clothes, as well.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results />\n\nThe [[main event]] was between [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[John Layfield|JBL]] (managed by Orlando Jordan) for the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]]. Jordan interfered by attempting to hit Batista with a [[folding chair]], but Batista grabbed the chair from him. Batista then used the chair to hit Jordan and JBL, and JBL was declared the winner, via disqualification. In WWE, a title cannot be won by disqualification, but only by pinfall or submission (the normal scoring conditions in professional wrestling matches). As a result, Batista retained the title.<ref name=WWEresults /><ref name=results /><ref name=mainevent>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/mainevent/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331125318/http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/mainevent/|archivedate=2008-03-31|title=Batista vs. JBL for the World Heavyweight Championship|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=2005-07-22|accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> After the match Batista gave JBL and Jordan a Batista Bomb.\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe feud between Batista and JBL continued after the Bash. On the July 28 episode of ''SmackDown!'', JBL defeated The Undertaker after interference from Randy Orton to become the number-one contender for the World Heavyweight Championship at [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]].<ref name=July28>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1122611986.shtml|title=JBL going to SummerSlam|date=2005-07-29| publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> The following week on ''SmackDown!'', Batista and JBL held a scripted official contract signing, where it was announced that their match at SummerSlam would be a [[Professional wrestling match types#No Disqualification match|No Holds Barred match]] that allowed for no disqualification.<ref name=August4>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1123209690.shtml|title=SmackDown Results&nbsp;\u2013 8/04/05&nbsp;\u2013 Bridgeport, CT (Tag Titles and more)|date=2005-08-04|publisher=WrestleView|last=Allen|first=Ryan|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> At SummerSlam, Batista defeated JBL to retain the World Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=SummerSlam>{{cite web|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1124679610.shtml|title=WWE SummerSlam (RAW/SmackDown) PPV Results&nbsp;\u2013 8/21/05|date=2005-08-21| last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> The feud between the two ended when Batista defeated JBL in a [[Texas Bullrope Match|Texas Bullrope match]] on the September 9 edition of ''SmackDown!'', a match where the objective is to touch all four ring corners while tied to one's opponent with a bullrope.<ref name=September9>{{cite web| url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1126326583.shtml|title=Changing Friday nights|last=Martin|first= Adam|date=2005-09-09|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref>\n\nOn the edition of ''SmackDown!'' following The Great American Bash, Eddie Guerrero revealed the secret he had been keeping; he was Dominick's real father, not Rey Mysterio (was thought to be).<ref name=July28 /> At SummerSlam, Mysterio defeated Guerrero in a ladder match, where the goal is to climb a ladder to retrieve an object that is suspended in the air. As per pre-match stipulations, Mysterio gained complete [[Child custody|custody]] of Dominick.<ref name=SummerSlam /> On the September 9 edition of ''SmackDown!'', Guerrero defeated Mysterio in a [[steel cage]] match to end the feud.<ref name=September9 /> Guerrero then began a feud with Batista when Guerrero was given a title match at [[No Mercy (2005)|No Mercy]].<ref name=NoMercy>{{cite web|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1128912495.shtml|title=WWE No Mercy (SmackDown) PPV Results&nbsp;\u2013 10/9/05|last=Martin|first=Adam| date=2005-10-09|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> Guerrero, however, died unexpectedly of [[heart failure]] on November 13, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1131910843.shtml|title=Another update on the passing of Eddie Guerrero; heart failure possible|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|date=2005-11-13}}</ref> In 2006 Guerrero was inducted into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] by Mysterio, his nephew [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]], and Chris Benoit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/halloffame/eddieguerrero/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331130442/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/halloffame/eddieguerrero/|archivedate=2008-03-31|title=Eddie Guerrero|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-09-10}}</ref>\n\nThe feud between Chris Benoit and Orlando Jordan continued. At SummerSlam, Benoit defeated Jordan for the WWE United States Championship in a match that lasted 25.5 seconds.<ref name=SummerSlam /> On the September 1 edition of ''SmackDown!'', Benoit once again defeated Jordan for the title, but this time the match lasted 23.4 seconds.<ref name=September1>{{cite web|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2005/1125630281.shtml|title=Another Assist From Dad|last=Martin|first= Adam|date=2005-09-09|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-08-03}}</ref> The following week on ''SmackDown!'', Benoit defeated Jordan in another title match, where the match lasted 22.5 seconds.<ref name=September9 />\n\n==Reception==\nThe HSBC Arena has a maximum capacity of 18,690,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsbcarena.com/quickfacts.cfm|title=Quick Facts|publisher=HSBC Arena|accessdate=2008-08-25| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080224064908/http://www.hsbcarena.com/quickfacts.cfm| archivedate = February 24, 2008}}</ref> but it was reduced for The Great American Bash. The event grossed over $375,000 in ticket sales from an attendance of 8,000, the maximum allowed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/wwe-pay-per-view/the-great-american-bash-2005/episode/387116/summary.html|title=Great American Bash 2005|publisher=TV.com|accessdate=2008-08-02}}</ref> The event resulted in 233,000 pay-per-view buys, which was the same amount as the [[The Great American Bash (2006)|following year's Great American Bash]]. The promotion's pay-per-view revenue was $21.6&nbsp;million, greater than the previous year's revenue of $16.9&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/documents/1QFY2006EarningsRelease-FINAL.pdf |title=WWE Reports Fiscal 2006 First Quarter Results |publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] Corporate |accessdate=2008-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202042056/http://corporate.wwe.com./news/documents/1QFY2006EarningsRelease-FINAL.pdf |archivedate=December 2, 2008 }}</ref> The event was widely criticized by fans and critics alike. ''[[Canadian Online Explorer]]'''s professional wrestling section rated the event a five out of ten.<ref name=Slam>{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2005/07/25/1146844.html|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|title=JBL reigns at a dull Bash|last=Kapur|first=Bob|accessdate=2008-08-01}}</ref> The World Heavyweight Championship main event match was rated three out of ten, and the match between Rey Mysterio and Eddie Guerrero received the highest match rating of eight out of ten.<ref name=Slam />\n\nThe event was released on [[DVD]] on August 23, 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fye.com/WWE--The-Great-American-Bash-Front-Page_stcVVproductId3417525VVcatId455366VVviewprod.htm |title=WWE: The Great American Bash |publisher=[[Trans World Entertainment|For Your Entertainment]] |accessdate=2008-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924002559/http://www.fye.com/WWE--The-Great-American-Bash-Front-Page_stcVVproductId3417525VVcatId455366VVviewprod.htm |archivedate=September 24, 2008 }}</ref> by [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. The DVD reached seventh on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s DVD Sales Chart for recreational sports during the week of October 8, 2005, and it rose to the fourth spot the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3061521&cdi=8443398&cid=10%2F08%2F2005 |title=Video Sales\u2014Recreational Sports DVD |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].com |accessdate=2008-08-01 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> It remained on the chart's \"top ten\" for four consecutive weeks, until the week of December 15, 2005, when it ranked thirteenth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3061696&cdi=8450166&cid=10%2F15%2F2005 |title=Video Sales\u2014Recreational Sports DVD |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].com |accessdate=2008-08-01 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|heat1  = yes\n|match1 = [[Paul London]] (c) defeated [[James Maritato|Nunzio]]\n|stip1  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|time1  = 02:33\n|match2 = [[The Road Warriors#L.O.D. 2005 (2005\u20132006)|The Legion of Doom]] ([[Road Warrior Animal|Animal]] and [[Jon Heidenreich|Heidenreich]]) defeated [[MNM (professional wrestling)|MNM]] ([[Joey Mercury]] and [[Johnny Nitro]]) (c) (with [[Melina Perez|Melina]]) \n|stip2  = [[Tag team match]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]]\n|time2  = 06:45\n|match3 = [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (with [[Sharmell]]) defeated [[Christian Cage|Christian]]\n|stip3  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time3  = 11:52\n|match4 = [[Orlando Jordan]] (c) defeated [[Chris Benoit]]\n|stip4  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE United States Championship]]\n|time4  = 14:23\n|match5 = [[The Undertaker]] defeated [[Muhammad Hassan (wrestler)|Muhammad Hassan]] (with [[Shawn Daivari|Daivari]])\n|stip5  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] to determine the #1 contender for the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] at [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]]\n|time5  = 08:04\n|match6 = [[The Mexicools]] ([[Juventud Guerrera|Juventud]], [[Psicosis]] and [[Super Crazy]]) defeated [[The bWo]] ([[Big Stevie Cool]], [[The Blue Meanie]] and [[Hollywood Nova]])\n|stip6  = [[Six-man tag team match]]\n|time6  = 04:53\n|match7 = [[Rey Mysterio]] defeated [[Eddie Guerrero]]\n|stip7  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]; had Mysterio lost, Guerrero would\u2019ve revealed his secret on live television \n|time7  = 15:39\n|match8 = [[Melina Perez|Melina]] defeated [[Torrie Wilson]]\n|stip8  = [[Bra and Panties match]] with [[Candice Michelle]] as [[special guest referee]]\n|time8  = 03:53\n|match9 = [[John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (with [[Orlando Jordan]]) defeated [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] (c) by [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]]\n|stip9  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the World Heavyweight Championship\n|time9  = 19:47\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080319091728/http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/history/2005/ Official Great American Bash 2005 website]\n* {{imdb episode|0457194}}\n\n{{2005 WWE pay-per-view events}}\n{{WWEPPV|The Great American Bash}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great American Bash (2005), The}}\n[[Category:2005 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Events in Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:The Great American Bash|2005]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:2005 WWE pay-per-view events]]\n[[Category:July 2005 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohnny Nitro(link changed toJohn Morrison (wrestler)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Great_American_Bash_(2005)"}
{"title_page": "Pete Postlethwaite", "text_new": "{{use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Pete Postlethwaite<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|OBE]]</small>\n|image         = Pete Postlethwaite.JPG\n|caption       = Postlethwaite at the [[Make Poverty History| Make Poverty History March]] in 2005\n|birth_name    = Peter William Postlethwaite\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1946|2|7|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Warrington]], [[Lancashire]]<!--Lancashire is correct as Warrington was in that county until 1974-->, England\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|2011|1|2|1946|2|7|df=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]], England\n|nationality   = British\n|occupation    = Actor\n|years_active  = 1975\u20132011\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Jacqueline Morrish|2003|2011|reason=his death}}\n|children      = 2\n}}\n'''Peter William Postlethwaite''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u0252|s|\u0259l|\u03b8|w|e\u026a|t}}; 7 February 1946 \u2013 2 January 2011)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/04/arts/04postlethwaite.html|work=The New York Times|first=Bruce|last=Weber|title=Pete Postlethwaite, British Actor, Dies at 64|date=3 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenrush.co.uk/stars/star-9155|title=Pete Postlethwaite Biography}}</ref> was an English [[character actor]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/03/AR2011010304974.html|title=Pete Postlethwaite, brilliant character actor of 'Usual Suspects,' 'Name of the Father'|first=T. Rees|last=Shapiro|date=4 January 2011|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> who appeared in ''[[In the Name of the Father (film)|In the Name of the Father]]'' (1993), ''[[Dragonheart]]'' (1996), ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]'' (1996), ''[[Brassed Off]]'' (1996), ''[[Sharpe (TV series)|Sharpe]]'' (1997), ''[[Amistad (film)|Amistad]]'' (1997), ''[[The Constant Gardener (film)|The Constant Gardener]]'' (2005), ''[[Clash of the Titans (2010 film)|Clash of the Titans]]'' (2010), ''[[Inception]]'' (2010), and ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' (2010).\n\nAfter minor television appearances, including in ''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]'', his first major success arose through the [[Great Britain|British]] [[autobiographical]] film ''[[Distant Voices, Still Lives]]'' (1988). He had a transatlantic breakthrough when he portrayed David in ''[[Alien 3]]'' (1992), and his international reputation was further solidified when he was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for ''[[In the Name of the Father (film)|In the Name of the Father]]'' (1993). Following this role, he portrayed the mysterious lawyer Mr Kobayashi in ''[[The Usual Suspects]]'' (1995) and went on to appear in a wide variety of films.\n\nIn television, Postlethwaite played [[Obadiah Hakeswill|Sergeant Obadiah Hakeswill]] on ''[[Sharpe (TV series)|Sharpe]]''. He trained as a teacher and taught drama before training as an actor. Director [[Steven Spielberg]] called him \"the best actor in the world\" after working with him on ''[[The Lost World: Jurassic Park]]'' (1997).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/jan/04/pete-postlethwaite-film-actor|title=Pete Postlethwaite: A face we won't forget|first=Peter|last=Bradshaw|date=4 January 2011}}</ref> He was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in the [[2004 New Year Honours]] list. Less than one month after his death, he was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]] for his performance in [[Ben Affleck]]'s ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' (2010).\n\n==Early life==\nPostlethwaite was born in [[Warrington]], at that time in [[Lancashire]], the fourth and youngest child of William Postlethwaite (1913\u20131988), a [[cooper (profession)|cooper]], wood machinist, and school caretaker, and Mary Geraldine (n\u00e9e Lawless; 1913\u20132000), working-class Roman Catholics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/film-obituaries/8237344/Pete-Postlethwaite.html|title=Pete Postlethwaite|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London, UK|date=3 January 2011|accessdate=4 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite ODNB|author=Tim O'Sullivan|title=Postlethwaite, Peter William [Pete] (1946\u20132011)|date= Jan 2015 |id=103537|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/public/dnb/103537.html}}</ref> He had two sisters, Anne and Patricia, and a brother, Michael (1944\u20132006). Despite portraying Irish characters on multiple occasions, Postlethwaite was not of Irish descent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/books-arts/review-autobiography-pete-postlethwaite-a-spectacle-of-dust-26754459.html|title=Review: Autobiography Pete Postlethwaite: A Spectacle of Dust|date=1 December 2012|newspaper=Irish Independent}}</ref>\n\nPostlethwaite attended St Benedict's RC Junior School and a [[seminary]]. He then joined the 4th form at [[De La Salle School, St Helens#Grammar schools|West Park Grammar School]], [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]] where he enjoyed sport including rugby league. He spent an extra year re-sitting some [[GCE Ordinary Level|O-levels]] and then took four [[GCE Advanced Level|A-levels]] in English, history, geography and French.<ref name=autobiography>{{cite book|last1=Postlethwaite|first1=Pete|last2=Richardson|first2=Andy|authorlink2=Andy Richardson (writer)|title=A Spectacle of Dust: The Autobiography|edition=Hardcover|date=1 June 2011|publisher=[[Orion Publishing]]|isbn=0297864939|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/spectacleofdusta0000post}}</ref> He trained as a teacher at [[St Mary's University, Twickenham|St Mary's College, Strawberry Hill]] where his chosen subjects were physical education and drama and then taught drama at [[Loreto College, Manchester]], before training as an actor at the [[Bristol Old Vic Theatre School]].\n\n==Career==\nEarly in his career, Postlethwaite was advised to adopt a new surname for his acting work by his first agent and by peers who quipped that his name \"would never be put up in lights outside theatres because they couldn't afford the electricity\". Postlethwaite rejected the advice.<ref name=\"Postlethwaitename\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/04/local/la-me-pete-postlethwaite-20110104|title=Pete Postlethwaite dies at 64; actor was nominated for an Oscar for 'In the Name of the Father'|author=McLellan, Dennis|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=4 January 2011|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe initially trained to be a Catholic priest<ref>{{cite news|title=Australia's soul singer|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/jun/20/filmandmusic1.filmandmusic16|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 June 2008}}</ref> but opted for a career in theatre and started his career at the [[Everyman Theatre, Liverpool|Everyman Theatre]] in [[Liverpool]], where his colleagues included [[Bill Nighy]], [[Jonathan Pryce]], [[Antony Sher]], [[Matthew Kelly]] and [[Julie Walters]]. Postlethwaite and Walters had an intimate relationship during the latter half of the 1970s.<ref name=\"wheatley1\"/> He was a veteran of the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] and other acting companies. On 13 January 1981, he took the leading role in a [[BBC]] TV [[black comedy]] by [[Alan Bleasdale]], ''The Muscle Market'', which was a spin-off from ''[[Boys from the Blackstuff]]''; it was part of the ''Play for Today'' series.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nAfter other early appearances in small parts for television programmes such as ''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]'', Postlethwaite's first film success came with the film ''[[Distant Voices, Still Lives]]'' in 1988. He received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for his role in ''[[In the Name of the Father (film)|In the Name of the Father]]'' in 1993. He is well known for his role as mysterious lawyer Mr. Kobayashi in ''[[The Usual Suspects]]''. He made appearances in several other successful films, including ''[[Alien 3]]'', ''[[Amistad (film)|Amistad]]'', ''[[Brassed Off]]'', ''[[The Shipping News (film)|The Shipping News]]'', ''[[The Constant Gardener (film)|The Constant Gardener]]'', ''[[Inception]]'', ''[[James and the Giant Peach (film)|James and the Giant Peach]]'' and as Friar Lawrence in Baz Luhrmann's ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''. {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nIn 2003, he was both the physical and vocal actor for the villain Deeth in ''[[Zixx]]: Level One'', a Canadian TV series created by [[Starz Media|IDT Entertainment]]. Later that same year, he toured [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] in a 90-minute one-man play, ''Scaramouche Jones'', in which he played a clown trying to find out why he is who he is before he dies at midnight, receiving a nomination for the [[TMA Award]] for Best Actor and winning the [[Theatregoers' Choice Award]] for Best Solo Performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/enoughrope/transcripts/s879121.htm|title=ENOUGH ROPE with Andrew Denton \u2013 episode 12: Pete Postlethwaite|publisher=ABC|location=Australia|date=2 June 2003|accessdate=3 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107073513/http://www.abc.net.au/tv/enoughrope/transcripts/s879121.htm|archive-date=7 January 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> This was directed by Rupert Goold, who would also direct his [[King Lear|Lear]] in 2008, in which Postlethwaite played every character. As well as Australia, the play toured Canada, New Zealand and the UK to great acclaim.<ref name=\"wheatley1\">{{cite news |last1=Wheatley |first1=Jane |title=The Coronation of Pete Postlethwaite |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-coronation-of-pete-postlethwaite-wvtkrjgdxlh |accessdate=28 August 2019 |work=[[The Times]] |date=27 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Art of Discworld]]'' (2004), [[Terry Pratchett]] wrote that he had always imagined [[Sam Vimes]] as 'a younger, slightly bulkier version of Pete Postlethwaite'.<ref>Pratchett, Terry and [[Paul Kidby|Kidby, Paul]]. ''The Art of Discworld'', Victor Gollancz Ltd, 2004; {{ISBN|0-575-07511-2}}</ref>\n\n[[Steven Spielberg]] called Postlethwaite \"the best actor in the world\" after working with him on ''[[The Lost World: Jurassic Park]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Pete's progress|date=1 October 2000|url=http://film.guardian.co.uk/interview/interviewpages/0,,375560,00.html|work=The Observer|accessdate=25 April 2007|location=London}}</ref> to which Postlethwaite quipped: \"I'm sure what Spielberg actually said was, 'The thing about Pete is that he thinks he's the best actor in the world.'\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Dominic|last=Cavendish|title=The poet in Pete's soul|date=25 April 2007|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2007/04/25/btpete125.xml|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=25 April 2007|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\nOne of his more notable roles was [[Obadiah Hakeswill|Sergeant Obadiah Hakeswill]] in ITV's ''[[Sharpe (TV series)|Sharpe]]'' series. The actor said this was one of his favourite roles and that he and fellow actor [[Sean Bean]] played well off each other because of their mutual love and respect. [[Bernard Cornwell]], the author and creator of the ''Sharpe'' series, specifically wrote Hakeswill's character in later novels to reflect Postlethwaite's performance as the character in the TV series. Postlethwaite co-starred with Bean in ''[[When Saturday Comes (film)|When Saturday Comes]]''. {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nPostlethwaite next starred in a Liverpool stage production of ''King Lear'' in 2008 at the Everyman Theatre, Liverpool, and at the Young Vic, London. He appeared in the [[climate change]]-themed film ''[[The Age of Stupid]]'', which premiered in March 2009. Having recently installed a [[wind turbine]] in his garden, he said was impressed by the film and wrote in ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper that, \"The stakes [of climate change] are very, very high. They're through the roof. How could we willingly know that we're going into extinction ... and let it happen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofstupid.net/video/making_of_petes_reaction|title=Reactions: Spanner Films|publisher=Ageofstupid.net|accessdate=3 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofstupid.net/video/channel_4_news_16th_feb_2008|title=Press: Stupid on Channel 4 News|publisher=Ageofstupid.net|date=16 February 2008|accessdate=3 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nTerminally ill, Postlethwaite made a conspicuous return to [[Hollywood]] in three 2010 films, first as Spyros in ''[[Clash of the Titans (2010 film)|Clash of the Titans]]''. He next appeared in the blockbuster hit ''[[Inception]]'' as Maurice Fischer, an industrialist who is slowly dying. Lastly, his performance in ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' as florist/crime boss Fergus \"Fergie\" Colm was well received by critics, making several publications' lists of Oscar predictions for Best Supporting Actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/for_your|title=For Your Consideration: Final 2011 Oscar Predictions|first=Peter|last=Knegt|date=24 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2011/01/18/oscar-predictions-final-pre-nomination-rankings|title=Oscar predictions: Final pre-nomination rankings}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.craveonline.com/culture/130154-crave-online-predicts-the-2011-oscar-nominations|title=CRAVE Online Predicts the 2011 Oscar Nominations! \u2013 CraveOnline|date=24 January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923211122/http://www.craveonline.com/culture/130154-crave-online-predicts-the-2011-oscar-nominations|archivedate=23 September 2015}}</ref> Postlethwaite's last appearance on screen was in [[Nick Hamm]]'s film ''[[Killing Bono]]'', based on the memoir of Neil McCormick. The role was written specially for Postlethwaite to accommodate his illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meg.ie/killing-bono-premier/|title=Killing Bono premier \u2013 meg}}</ref> The film was released on 1 April 2011. His final role was due to be in the BBC series ''[[Exile (TV series)|Exile]]'', written by [[Danny Brocklehurst]] and [[Paul Abbott]], but he had to pull out because of ill health. [[Jim Broadbent]] replaced him in the role.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-12890291 \"Jim Broadbent takes Pete Postlethwaite part in drama\"], BBC.co.uk; accessed 24 January 2014.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\nPostlethwaite was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in the 2004 New Year Honours list and received an Honorary Fellowship in recognition of outstanding contribution to the dramatic arts by [[Liverpool John Moores University]] in 2005 and an honorary degree from the [[University of Liverpool]] in 2006. He received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for his role ''[[In the Name of the Father (film)|In the Name of the Father]]'' and was posthumously nominated for a [[BAFTA Award]] for his performance in ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nPostlethwaite lived in [[West Itchenor]], [[West Sussex]] before moving near [[Bishop's Castle]], [[Shropshire]]. He began a relationship with Jacqueline \"Jacqui\" Morrish, a former [[BBC]] producer, in 1987; the couple married in 2003 at [[St Nicholas' Church, West Itchenor|St Nicholas' Church, Itchenor]]. They had two children, William John \"Billy\" (born 1989), and Lily Kathleen (born 1996). Billy Postlethwaite is an actor who trained at the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]], and has most notably appeared in the TV series ''[[Holby City]]'', ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' and ''[[Chernobyl (TV series)|Chernobyl]]''.<ref name=\"wheatley1\"/>\n\nPostlethwaite was a lifelong supporter of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool Football Club]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/jan/03/pete-postlethwaite-remembered-colleagues|title=Pete Postlethwaite remembered|first=Tim|last=Lusher|date=3 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nPostlethwaite was diagnosed with [[testicular cancer]] in 1990, and [[Inguinal orchiectomy|had his right testicle removed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seanmartella.blogspot.com/2008/01/cancer-survivors-part-1-pete.html|title=Sean Martella's Testicular Cancer Update Blog: Cancer Survivors Part 1 \u2013 Pete Postlethwaite |publisher=Seanmartella.blogspot.com|date=17 January 2008|accessdate=3 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Observer\">{{cite news|url=http://film.guardian.co.uk/interview/interviewpages/0,,375560,00.html#article_continue|work=The Observer|location=London|title=Pete's progress|accessdate=22 May 2010|date=1 October 2000}}</ref> He was a [[tobacco smoking|smoker]] from the age of ten until his death.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/film-obituaries/8237344/Pete-Postlethwaite.html|title=Pete Postlethwaite |work=The Telegraph|date=16 February 1945 |accessdate=4 January 2011|location=London}}</ref> In a March 2009 interview with ''[[Scotland on Sunday]]'', the actor referred to his smoking habit, stating: \"We've got to hope the next generation will do things differently. I'm sure that in 20 years' time the kids will say: 'Can you believe that people actually used to smoke \u2013 put these funny little things in their mouths, lit them and sucked all that crap into their lungs?\"<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite news|title=Pete Postlethwaite interview: For the love of Pete|author=Smith, Aidan|url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/sos-review/Pete-Postlethwaite-interview-For-the.5048415.jp|newspaper=Scotland on Sunday|date=8 March 2009|accessdate=26 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nPostlethwaite appeared as a taxi driver in one of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]'s [[Party political broadcast|political broadcasts]] during the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker|first=Michael|url=http://country-standard.blogspot.com/2011/01/pete-postlethwaite-1997-ppb-taxicab.html|title=Country Standard: Pete Postlethwaite \u2013 1997 PPB Taxicab Angel|publisher=Country-standard.blogspot.com|date=3 January 2011|accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref> He marched in London against the [[Iraq War]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weaver|first=Matthew|title=Actor Pete Postlethwaite dies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/jan/03/actor-pete-postlethwaite-dies|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 January 2011|location=London}}</ref> He was an activist calling for action to prevent [[climate change]]. At the UK premiere of ''The Age of Stupid'' on 16 November 2009, he told then-[[Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]] [[Ed Miliband]] that he would return his [[OBE]] and vote for any party other than Labour if the [[Kingsnorth power station#Proposed replacement|Kingsnorth coal-fired power station]] was given the go-ahead by the government.<ref>{{cite news|last=Siegle|first=Lucy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/ethicallivingblog/2009/mar/16/the-age-of-stupid-renewableenergy|title=The night Miliband said 'I'm with Stupid, but...'|work=The Guardian|location=UK|date=16 March 2009|accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref> The proposal to build a new power station at Kingsnorth was shelved by the coalition government in October 2010.\n\n==Illness and death==\nPostlethwaite died of [[pancreatic cancer]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/postlethwaites-last-take-director-recalls-dying-stars-final-film-2254170.html|title=Five years on: Celebrating Pete Postlethwaite's legacy|date=7 January 2017|accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref> at the [[Royal Shrewsbury Hospital]] on 2 January 2011, and was survived by his wife and children.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.inthenews.co.uk/news/entertainment/film/daniel-day-lewis-pays-tribute-to-pete-postlethwaite-$21385579.htm|author=Lesnik, Tim|title=Daniel Day Lewis Pays Tribute to Pete Postlethwaite|date=17 February 2011|accessdate=17 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304124603/http://www.inthenews.co.uk/news/entertainment/film/daniel-day-lewis-pays-tribute-to-pete-postlethwaite-$21385579.htm|archivedate=4 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-12106753 |title=Oscar-nominated actor Pete Postlethwaite dies aged 64 |publisher=[[BBC]]  |date= 3 January 2011|accessdate=4 January 2011}}</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/actor-pete-postlethwaite-dies-age-64-2174887.html Actor Pete Postlethwaite dies age 64] ''[[The Independent]]'' (London) 3 January 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/jan/04/pete-postlethwaite-film-actor|title=Pete Postlethwaite: A face we won't forget|date=1 January 2011|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|location=London|first=Peter|last=Bradshaw|authorlink=Peter Bradshaw}}</ref> The cancer had been diagnosed in March 2009.<ref>https://www.moviesteve.com/film-of-the-day-02-january-the-usual-suspects-1995/</ref> Postlethwaite continued acting almost to the end of 2010, showing clear signs of weight loss during his last performances. In his last two years, he worked on his memoir ''A Spectacle of Dust'' with [[Andy Richardson (writer)|Andy Richardson]]. It was published on 1 June 2011.<ref name=autobiography /><ref name=\"book\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shropshirestar.com/news/2011/06/20/pete-postlethwaites-book-serialised-in-the-shropshire-star/|title=Pete Postlethwaite's book serialised in the Shropshire Star|date=20 June 2011|work=[[Shropshire Star]]|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''The Racer''\n| Ecco\n| Short film\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[The Duellists]]''\n| Man Shaving General Treillard\n| Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''Doris and Doreen''\n| Mr. Lomax\n| 