ond City Firsts''\n|\n| Episode: \"Thwum\"<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''Plays for Britain''\n| Soldier\n| Episode: \"The Paradise Run\"<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Last of the Summer Wine]]''\n| Customer in Sid's Cafe\n| Episode: \"A Merry Heatwave\"<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Going Straight]]''\n| Thomas Clifford Crowther\n| Episode: \"Going Going Gone\"<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Afternoon Off]]''\n| Gallery Attendant\n| \n|-\n| 1979\n| ''Horse in the House''\n| Uncle Doug\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Play for Today]]''\n| Danny Duggan\n| Episode: \"The Muscle Market\"<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n| Detective Sergeant Cross\n| Episode 2061\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Crown Court (TV series)|Crown Court]]''\n|\n| Episode: \"The Merry Widow: Part 1\"\n|-\n| 1982{{ndash}}1993\n| ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]''\n| Jack \"Oily\" Wragg<br />Eric \"Logie\" Lawson\n| 2 episodes<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''Mitch''\n| Jack Frost\n| Episode: \"Squealer\"<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Victoria Wood As Seen on TV]]''\n| Barry\n| Episode 1.6<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''Summer Season''\n|\n| Episode: \"A Crack in the Ice\"<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Tales of Sherwood Forest''\n| Eric\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''Screenplay''\n| Paula's Father\n| Episode: \"Needle\"\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''Debut on Two''\n| Tony<br>Keef\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Boon (TV series)|Boon]]''\n| Steve McLaughlin\n| Episode: \"Undercover\"\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]''\n|\n| Episode: \"The Marked Man\"\n|-\n| 1990{{ndash}}1993\n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| Ralph Peters<br />Hank\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[El C.I.D.]]''\n| Vince\n| Episode 3.1: \"Making Amends\"\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Between the Lines (TV series)|Between the Lines]]''\n| Chief Superintendent Jameson\n| Episode: \"Out of the Game\"\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Shakespeare: The Animated Tales]]''\n| Quince\n| Episode: \"[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]\"<br />Credited as Peter Postlethwaite\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[The Bill]]''\n| Ray Goller\n| Episode: \"Principled Negotiation\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Lovejoy]]''\n| Terence Sullivan\n| Episode: \"Goose Bumps\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Pie in the Sky (TV series)|Pie in the Sky]]''\n| Kevin Tasker\n| Episode 1.8: \"A Matter of Taste\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Martin Chuzzlewit (TV series)|Martin Chuzzlewit]]''\n| [[Martin Chuzzlewit#Other characters|Montague Tigg/Tigg Montague]]\n| 5 episodes<br>Nominated \u2013 [[British Academy Television Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Sins]]''\n| Len Green\n| Miniseries<br>Nominated \u2013 [[British Academy Television Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Shattered City: The Halifax Explosion]]''\n| Charles Burchell\n| Miniseries\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Criminal Justice (TV series)|Criminal Justice]]''\n| Hooch\n| Miniseries\n|-\n|}\n\n==Selected theatre performances==\n* Antonio Bologna in ''[[The Duchess of Malfi]]''. Directed by [[Adrian Noble]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]].  (1980)\n* Brutus Jones in ''[[The Emperor Jones]]'' by [[Eugene O\u2019Neill]]. Directed by [[Richard Negri]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]].  (1980)\n* Max in ''[[The Homecoming]]'' by [[Harold Pinter]]. Directed by [[Greg Hersov]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]].  Postlethwaite won a ([[Manchester Evening News Theatre Awards|MEN Award]]) for best actor.(2002)\n* ''[[Scaramouche Jones]]'' toured New Zealand (2003)\n* Prospero in ''[[The Tempest]]''. Directed by [[Greg Hersov]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]].  (2007)\n* King Leah in \u2018\u2019[King Leah]]\u2019\u2019. Directed by [[Rupert Goold]] at the Everyman Theatre, Liverpool.\n(2008)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n\n* {{IMDb name|0000592|Pete Postlethwaite}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{amg name|57436|Pete Postlethwaite}}\n* {{Screenonline name|510419|Pete Postlethwaite}}\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/film-obituaries/8237344/Pete-Postlethwaite.html Daily Telegraph Obituary]\n* {{Find a Grave|63670767}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Postlethwaite, Pete}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bristol Old Vic Theatre School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Mary's University, Twickenham]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Actors at the Royal Exchange, Manchester]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Warrington]]\n[[Category:Testicular cancer survivors]]\n", "name_user": "Acahopkins", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Correct typo \"Postletwaite\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_Postlethwaite"}
{"title_page": "Armageddon (2006)", "text_new": "{{short description|2006 World Wrestling Entertainment pay-per-view event}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = Armageddon (2006)\n|image      = WWEarmageddon06.jpg\n|alt        =\n|caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Dave Batista|Batista]]\n|tagline    = The End...Is Only the Beginning\n|theme      =\n|promotion  = [[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]]\n|brand      = [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]]\n|date       = December 17, 2006\n|venue      = [[Richmond Coliseum]]\n|city       = [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n|attendance = 8,200\n|lastevent  = [[December to Dismember (2006)|December to Dismember]]\n|nextevent  = [[New Year's Revolution (2007)|New Year's Revolution]]\n|event      = [[WWE Armageddon|Armageddon]]\n|lastevent2 = [[Armageddon (2005)|2005]]\n|nextevent2 = [[Armageddon (2007)|2007]]\n}}\n'''Armageddon (2006)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of WWE pay-per-view events|event]] produced by [[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE). It took place on December 17, 2006, at the [[Richmond Coliseum]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]]. The event starred [[List of World Wrestling Entertainment employees|wrestlers]] from the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]] [[WWE Brand Extension|brand]].<ref name=\"SLAM!\">{{cite web|first=Brian|last=Elliott|date=December 17, 2006|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2006/12/18/2859158.html|title=Unexpected ladder contest steals Armageddon|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|work=Slam! Sports|accessdate=March 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team match]], in which the team of [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[John Cena]] defeated the team of [[Booker Huffman|King Booker]] and [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]].<ref name=\"Cena & Batista vs Booker & Finlay\">{{cite web|first=Brett|last=Hoffman|date=December 17, 2006|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/347294412/results/|title=Champs prevail|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=March 29, 2008}}</ref> Two featured bouts were scheduled on the undercard, including [[The Undertaker]] versus [[Mr. Kennedy]], in a match where the objective was to [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|place an opponent in a hearse located on the entrance stage and drive them out of the arena]], which Undertaker won.<ref name=\"Last Ride match\">{{cite web|first=Craig|last=Tello|date=December 17, 2006|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729442/results/|title=Ride to Hell|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=March 29, 2006}}</ref> The other match was an [[Professional wrestling match types#Inferno match|Inferno match]] featuring wrestlers attempting to set the opponent on fire with flames surrounding the [[wrestling ring|ring]]. [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] defeated [[Montel Vontavious Porter]].<ref name=\"Inferno match\">{{cite web|first=Mike|last=McAvennie|date=December 17, 2006|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729443/results/|title=Back-burner|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=March 18, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331201448/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729443/results/|archivedate=March 31, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe event grossed over $423,500 in ticket sales from an attendance of 8,200. [[Canadian Online Explorer]]'s professional wrestling section rated the WWE Tag Team Championship match a nine out of ten stars, the highest match rating. The event was released on [[DVD]] on January 16, 2007 by [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. The DVD reached second on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s'' DVD Sales Chart for recreational sports during the week of February 18, 2007, and it dropped to the tenth spot the following week.\n\n==Storylines==\nArmageddon (2006) was the seventh annual [[WWE Armageddon|Armageddon]] event. Eight professional wrestling matches, were featured on the event's [[Card (sports)|card]].\n\n[[Image:Cena With Spinner Belt.jpg|thumb|left|upright|John Cena teamed up with Batista against King Booker and Finlay]]\nThe leading [[Feud (professional wrestling)|staged rivalry]] written into the event was between [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[Booker Huffman|King Booker]]. At [[Survivor Series (2006)|Survivor Series]], WWE's November pay-per-view event, Batista defeated Booker to win the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=\"SurvivorSeries\"/><ref name=\"SurvivorSeries2\"/> On the December 1, 2006 episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'', one of WWE's primary television programs, King Booker and [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]] both demanded a match against Batista for the World Heavyweight Championship. [[Professional wrestling authority figures#General Managers 2|General Manager]] [[Theodore Long]], a portrayed match maker and rules enforcer, announced that Booker and Finlay would instead form a [[tag team]] to compete against Batista and a partner of his choice at Armageddon. Later that night, Batista announced that his partner would be [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]] [[John Cena]], a member of the ''[[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]]'' brand.<ref name=\"December1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1165033362.shtml|last=Martin|first=Adam|title=World Title and more|date=December 1, 2006|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref> The following week on an episode of ''SmackDown!'', Batista defeated Finlay by [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]] after Booker interfered on Finlay's behalf.<ref name=\"December8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1165636943.shtml|title=Booker and Finlay unite|date=December 8, 2006|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref> On the December 15 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Cena defeated Finlay after lifting Finlay up on his shoulders and slamming him to the mat, a move that Cena dubbed the [[Professional wrestling throws#Fireman's carry takeover|FU]].<ref name=\"December15\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_11157.shtml|title=12/16 WWE Smackdown review: Giebink's Express v3.0 (Hr. 2)|date=December 15, 2006|publisher=PWTorch.com|last=Giebink|first=Dusty|accessdate=October 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe secondary rivalry was between [[The Undertaker]] and [[Mr. Kennedy]]. On the September 8, 2006 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Kennedy announced that he was looking for a new opponent, one that he had never faced before. Long informed Kennedy that he knew a SmackDown! superstar that had never faced Kennedy, The Undertaker. A match was made between the two for [[No Mercy (2006)|No Mercy]], in which Kennedy defeated Undertaker by disqualification.<ref name=\"NoMercy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/history/2006/matches/322528211/results/|title=Undertaker shows No Mercy on Kennedy|last=Hunt|first=Jen|date=October 8, 2006|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"NoMercy2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1191814054.shtml|title=WWE No Mercy PPV Results|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=October 8, 2006|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906002529/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1191814054.shtml|archivedate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> At Survivor Series, Kennedy once again defeated Undertaker in a [[Professional wrestling match types#First Blood match|First Blood match]].<ref name=\"SurvivorSeries\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/2006/matches/33324801111/results/|title=First blood, last laugh|last=McAvennie|first=Mike|date=November 26, 2006|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=July 12, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821195437/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/2006/matches/33324801111/results/|archivedate=August 21, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"SurvivorSeries2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1164599352.shtml|title=WWE Survivor Series PPV Results|date=November 26, 2006|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919054919/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1164599352.shtml|archivedate=September 19, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the December 1 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Undertaker fought [[Montel Vontavious Porter]] (MVP) in a match where [[Professional wrestling#No contest|neither wrestler won]]. During the match, MVP was scripted to attempt escaping from the ring, but Kennedy caught him during the process and tried to throw him back into the ring. MVP instead threw Kennedy in. Undertaker then kicked Kennedy in the face, and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] attacked MVP at ringside.<ref name=\"December1\"/> The following week as Kennedy was in the ring, the [[hearse]], appearing to have nobody in the driver's seat, drove into the arena; suddenly, The Undertaker appeared from the back of the hearse, as Kennedy sprung from the ring. Later that night, Kane defeated Kennedy by [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]] after MVP interfered on Kennedy's behalf.<ref name=\"December8\"/> On the December 15 episode of ''SmackDown!'', [[The Brothers of Destruction|The Undertaker and Kane]] teamed together to face Kennedy and MVP in a tag team match, which ended in [[Professional wrestling#No contest|neither team winning]]. Kennedy knocked Kane down in the aisle and jumped into the driver's seat of the hearse that had been at ringside for the match, and threatened to run him over with it however the Undertaker appeared in the passenger side seat scaring Kennedy off.<ref name=\"December15\"/>\n\nThe third rivalry was between [[Montel Vontavious Porter]] (MVP) and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]]. After MVP signed with the SmackDown! brand and made his debut, he begged [[Theodore Long]] for more competition. Kane answered the challenge but MVP got himself [[Disqualification (professional wrestling)|disqualified]] when he low blowed Kane to escape Kane's chokeslam. Over the past few months, MVP defeated Kane in a [[Hardcore wrestling|street fight]] with help from [[Mr. Kennedy]] (who was feuding with [[The Undertaker]]) and later defeated Kane in a [[steel cage match]] by escaping the cage. Theodore Long later announced that since MVP and Kane are so evenly matched the two would do battle at Armageddon in an [[Inferno match]]. A match in which a wrestler must be victorious by setting his opponent on fire in a ring surrounded by flames\n\n==Event==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+ '''Other on-screen personnel'''\n!|Role:\n!|Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=2|English [[Sportscaster|commentators]]\n|[[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]]\n|-\n|[[John Layfield|John Bradshaw Layfield]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Spanish commentators\n|[[Carlos Cabrera]]\n|-\n|[[Hugo Savinovich]]\n|-\n|[[Ring announcer]]\n|[[Tony Chimel]]\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Referee (professional wrestling)|Referees]]\n|[[Nick Patrick (referee)|Nick Patrick]]\n|-\n|[[Charles Robinson (referee)|Charles Robinson]]\n|-\n|[[Jim Korderas]]\n|-\n|[[Brian Hebner]]\n|}\n\n===Preliminary matches===\n[[Image:MVP! (2).jpg|thumb|right|[[Montel Vontavious Porter]], who faced Kane in an Inferno match]]\nThe first match to air live was between Kane and MVP in an [[Professional wrestling match types#Inferno match|Inferno match]]. The only way to win an Inferno match is by throwing one's opponent into a fire that surrounds the ring on all four sides. This match was the first time that the Inferno match had been used on pay-per-view in more than [[Unforgiven: In Your House|seven years]].<ref name=\"December22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1166843826.shtml|last=Martin|first=Adam|title=Taker & Kane, more|publisher=WrestleView|date=December 22, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref> At the start of the match, MVP attempted to leave the ring, but was unable to as the flames surrounding the ring prevented him. Kane kicked MVP in the head and threw him into the ring corner. MVP escaped the ring and was unable to go past the fire, so he returned to the ring and was continuously knocked down by Kane. The finish of the match saw Kane grab MVP and force him backwards into the fire. MVP's costume caught on fire as he ran to the entrance ramp. MVP fell to the floor as WWE workers put out the flames with fire extinguishers.<ref name=\"results\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1197864103.shtml|title=WWE Armageddon PPV Results|publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=December 18, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081003064215/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1197864103.shtml|archivedate=October 3, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MVPKane\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729443/results/|title=Back-burner|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=McAvennie|first=Mike|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe following match featured [[Paul London and Brian Kendrick]], [[The Blue Bloods#World Wrestling Entertainment|William Regal and Dave Taylor]], [[MNM (wrestling)|MNM]] ([[Adam Birch|Joey Mercury]], and [[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]), and [[Hardy Boyz|The Hardys]] ([[Matt Hardy|Matt]] and [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Champion]] [[Jeff Hardy|Jeff]]) in a four-team [[ladder match]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]]. In this match, the only way to win and capture the titles was by climbing a ladder and releasing the championship belts that were suspended above the ring. Towards the end of the match, while MNM and The Hardys were out of the ring, Regal and Taylor attempted to climb the ladder, but Kendrick managed to knock the pair off. Kendrick fought off Regal and Taylor as London climbed the ladder and captured the titles to win the match for his team and retain the championships. During the match, Mercury suffered a legitimate nose injury after being hit by a ladder.<ref name=\"WWEMag35\">{{cite journal|date=December 2007|title=This Month on Pay-Per-View|journal=[[WWE Magazine]]|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|issue=December 2007|pages=35}}</ref><ref name=\"WWEMag36\">{{cite journal|date=December 2007|title=Back up the Ladder|journal=[[WWE Magazine]]|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|issue=December 2007|pages=36}}</ref><ref name=\"TagTeamt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729444/results/|title=Climbing the rungs of respect|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Tello|first=Craig|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n{{quote|I happened to be looking up, so it hit me in the throat. But Mercury was looking straight at it and it hit him square in the nose and the orbital bone. It really could have been any one of us. I was just lucky that the ladder hit him first.|[[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]|<ref name=\"WWEMag36\" />}}\n{{quote|I'll always remember [the match] for what we did to Joey Mercury's face. After the seesaw, I remember hearing him yell, \"I'm bleeding,\" and it was like someone went to a sink and turned the faucet on. It was gruesome.|[[Matt Hardy]]|<ref name=\"WWEMag36\" />}}\n\nThe third match was a [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|standard wrestling match]] between [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]] and [[Mike Mizanin|The Miz]]. The Boogeyman controlled the majority of the match and eventually won by [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinfall]] after a [[Powerbomb#Falling powerbomb|Falling]] [[Powerbomb#Chokebomb|Chokebomb]].<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"BoogeymanMiz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/347294441/results/|title=A worm welcome|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Starr|first=Noah|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe next match featured [[Chris Benoit]] defending the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]] against [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]] ([[Manager (professional wrestling)|accompanied]] by [[Vickie Guerrero]]). Before the bell rang to start the match, Chavo tried to attack Benoit, but as the match began, Benoit retaliated by delivering a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Clothesline|clothesline]]. Benoit and Guerrero wrestled inconclusively until Benoit covered Chavo to try to pin him. Chavo managed to place his foot on top of the bottom rope, which forced Benoit to break the pin per official wrestling match rules. While Guerrero was lying on his stomach, Benoit applied the [[sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Sharpshooter]], and made Chavo submit to retain the championship.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"UnitedStates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729441/results/|title=Wolveriene prevails at Armageddon|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821190044/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729441/results/|archivedate=August 21, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe fifth match was the encounter of [[Gregory Helms]] and [[James Yun|Jimmy Wang Yang]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]. Helms performed a [[Neckbreaker#Swinging neckbreaker|swinging neckbreaker]] on Yang. Yang retaliated, but Helms quickly moved back into the power position and pinned Yang to retain the championship.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"Cruiserweight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/347294441/results/|title=Helms still in Cruiserweight control|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=McAvennie|first=Mike|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Main event matches===\n[[Image:Undertaker Milwaukee WI 031008.jpg|thumb|upright|The Undertaker. who faced Mr. Kennedy in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Last Ride match]] at Armageddon]]\nThe following match was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Last Ride match]] between [[The Undertaker]] and [[Mr. Kennedy]], where the only way to win was by throwing one's opponent into a hearse and driving it out of the arena. During the beginning of the match, The Undertaker tossed Kennedy into steel steps on the side of the ring and then onto the commentator's announcing table. The Undertaker then threw Kennedy into the ring apron, which is the apron covering the area under the ring. Kennedy and The Undertaker wrestled inconclusively until The Undertaker tossed Kennedy on top of the roof of the hearse. The Undertaker then delivered a [[Chokeslam]] and a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Tombstone piledriver|Tombstone Piledriver]], both onto the roof of the hearse. As he was still in control of the match, The Undertaker threw Kennedy into the hearse and drove it out of the arena to win the match.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"TakerKennedy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729442/results/|title=Ride to Hell|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Tello|first=Craig|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Last Ride match, [[Jillian Hall]], [[Layla El]], [[Ashley Massaro]], and [[Kristal Marshall]] all took part in a \"Naughty or Nice\" contest, a [[lingerie]] contest, where the [[WWE Diva|Diva]] with the loudest fan reaction would win. The host of the contest was [[Santa Claus]] (portrayed by Big Dick Johnson, otherwise Christopher DeJoseph). Johnson declared all four of the Divas as the winners and proceeded to take off his Santa costume and dance to music being played in the arena.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"DivaContest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/3472944411/results/|title=Secret Santa|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Starr|first=Noah|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe main event was the tag team match between John Cena and Batista versus the team of King Booker and Finlay. Batista wrestled the match with his left arm taped up due to a previous injury. Both teams wrestlers inconclusively until Cena applied the [[Professional wrestling holds#STS|STFU]] on Booker. Finlay broke the submission hold, and [[Hornswoggle|The Little Bastard]] ran into the ring. Little Bastard attempted to kick Cena, but accidentally kicked himself in his head when Cena moved out of the way. Then, Booker tried to [[superkick]] Batista, but Batista moved out of the way, and Booker accidentally hit Finlay. Batista then delivered a [[Powerbomb|Batista Bomb]] and pinned Booker to earn the victory for his team.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"MainEvent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/347294412/results/|title=Champs prevail|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nOn the December 22, 2006 episode of ''SmackDown!'', King Booker and Finlay demanded a rematch against Batista and John Cena. General Manager Theodore Long informed the pair that they would instead be facing Kane and The Undertaker later that night in a match, which Kane and The Undertaker won. At the [[Royal Rumble (2007)|Royal Rumble]], the [[Royal Rumble#Match|Royal Rumble match]] was held, where the winner is the final person left in the ring after the other twenty nine wrestlers are eliminated by being thrown over the top ring rope. The Undertaker won the Royal Rumble match to earn a title shot at [[WrestleMania 23]].<ref name=\"Rumble\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2007/|title=A Phenom-enal Rumble|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Dee|first=Louie|date=January 28, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709054906/http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2007/|archivedate=July 9, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"RoyalRumble\" /> At WrestleMania, he defeated Batista to win the World Heavyweight Championship and maintain his WrestleMania [[The Streak (wrestling)|undefeated streak]].<ref name=\"WrestleMania\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wrestlemania23/matches/3916184/results/|title=The streak lives on for The Deadman|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Hunt|first=Jen|date=April 1, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nChris Benoit continued to feud with Chavo Guerrero over the [[WWE United States Championship]]. On the December 22, 2006 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Benoit defeated Guerrero in a rematch for the title, with Vickie Guerrero accompanying Chavo to ringside. Benoit won the match by disqualification when Vickie hit Benoit in the head with the championship belt.<ref name=\"December22\" /><ref name=\"WWEDecember22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/12222006/|title=Bells will be ringing|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|date=December 22, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref> On the January 12, 2007 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Mr. Kennedy defeated Chris Benoit in a standard match, with help from Chavo Guerrero.<ref name=\"January12\" /><ref name=\"WWEJanuary12\" /> The following week, Benoit defeated Chavo yet again with the championship on the line.<ref name=\"January19\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1169269456.shtml|title=Taker and Kennedy|publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=January 19, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906210109/http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1169269456.shtml|archivedate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe feuds between Kane and Montel Vontavious Porter (MVP), and The Undertaker and Mr. Kennedy did not continue after the event. On the January 5, 2007, episode of ''SmackDown!'', Kennedy set the time to beat in the \"Beat the Clock\" sprint, a tournament based on the time wrestlers win matches, to become the new number one contender for the World Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=\"WWEJanuary5\" /><ref name=\"January5\" /> On the January 12 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Kennedy won the \"Beat the Clock\" sprint by preventing The Undertaker from winning his match and from beating Kennedy's time. At the Royal Rumble, Batista defeated Kennedy to retain the title.<ref name=\"RoyalRumble\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1170044000.shtml|title=Royal Rumble PPV Results|last=Nemner|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|date=January 28, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref> The feuds between Gregory Helms and Jimmy Wang Yang, and The Boogeyman and The Miz also did not continue, as Helms was put into a rivalry with The Boogeyman.<ref name=\"WWEJanuary5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/01052007/|title=Race against time|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|date=January 5, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"January5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1168055099.shtml|title=Beat the Clock sprint|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|date=January 5, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828210853/http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1168055099.shtml|archivedate=August 28, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> Yang was put into a temporary rivalry with [[Chris Chavis|Tatanka]].<ref name=\"January12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1168672396.shtml|title=Beat the Clock winner|publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=January 12, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906140552/http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1168672396.shtml|archivedate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"WWEJanuary12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/01122007/|title=Race against time|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|date=January 12, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe Richmond Coliseum has a maximum capacity of 13,000, but that was reduced for the 2006 Armageddon event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.richmond.va.us/departments/parks/coliseum.aspx|title=Richmond Coliseum|publisher=RichmondGov.com|accessdate=August 23, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822103417/http://www.ci.richmond.va.us/departments/parks/coliseum.aspx|archivedate=August 22, 2008}}</ref> The event grossed over [[United States dollar|$]]423,500 in ticket sales from an attendance of 8,200. ''[[Canadian Online Explorer]]'s'' professional wrestling section rated the WWE Tag Team Championship match a nine out of ten stars, the highest match rating. The United States Championship, Cruiserweight Championship, and Last Ride matches all received seven out of ten stars. The main event match received a five and a half stars out of ten rating.<ref name=\"SLAM!\" />\n\nThe event was released on [[DVD]] on January 16, 2007,<ref name=\"DVD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fye.com/WWE--Armageddon-2006-Front-Page_stcVVproductId8332172VVcatId455366VVviewprod.htm|title=WWE: Armageddon|publisher=[[Trans World Entertainment|For Your Entertainment]]|accessdate=August 23, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925191926/http://www.fye.com/WWE--Armageddon-2006-Front-Page_stcVVproductId8332172VVcatId455366VVviewprod.htm|archivedate=September 25, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> by [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. The DVD reached second on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s'' DVD Sales Chart for recreational sports during the week of February 18, 2007, and it dropped to the tenth spot the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3064430&cdi=8551056&cid=02%2F25%2F2006|title=Video Sales \u2013 Recreational Sports DVD|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].com|accessdate=August 23, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114041045/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3064430&cdi=8551056&cid=02%2F25%2F2006|archivedate=January 14, 2009}}</ref> It remained on the chart's \"top ten\" for two consecutive weeks until the week of March 4, 2007, when it ranked 17th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3064603&cdi=8555487&cid=03%2F04%2F2006|title=Video Sales \u2013 Recreational Sports DVD|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 23, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114031714/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3064603&cdi=8555487&cid=03%2F04%2F2006|archivedate=January 14, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|dark1  = yes\n|match1 = [[Vladimir Kozlov]] defeated [[Scotty 2 Hotty]]\n|stip1  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time1  = 2:01\n|match2 = [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] defeated [[Montel Vontavious Porter]]\n|stip2  = [[Inferno match]]\n|time2  = 08:14\n|match3 = [[Brian Kendrick and Paul London]] (c) defeated  [[Dave Taylor and William Regal]], [[The Hardy Boyz]] ([[Jeff Hardy]] and [[Matt Hardy]]) and  [[MNM (professional wrestling)|MNM]] ([[Joey Mercury]] and [[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]) (with [[Melina Perez|Melina]])\n|stip3  = [[Fatal 4-Way match|Fatal 4-Way]] [[ladder match]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]]\n|time3  = 20:13\n|match4 = [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]] defeated [[The Miz]]\n|stip4  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time4  = 02:51\n|match5 = [[Chris Benoit]] (c) defeated [[Chavo Guerrero]] (with [[Vickie Guerrero]]) by submission\n|stip5  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE United States Championship]]\n|time5  = 12:14\n|match6 = [[Gregory Helms]] (c) defeated [[Jimmy Wang Yang]]\n|stip6  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|time6  = 10:51\n|match7 = [[The Undertaker]] defeated [[Mr. Kennedy]]\n|stip7  = [[Last Ride match]]\n|time7  = 19:49\n|match8 = [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] and [[John Cena]] defeated [[King Booker's Court]] ([[King Booker]] and [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]]) (with [[Queen Sharmell]])\n|stip8  = [[Tag team match]]\n|time8  = 11:29\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006}}\n\n{{2006 WWE pay-per-view events}}\n{{WWEPPV|Armageddon}}\n\n[[Category:WWE Armageddon|2006]]\n[[Category:2006 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Events in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:2006 WWE pay-per-view events]]\n[[Category:December 2006 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2006 World Wrestling Entertainment pay-per-view event}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = Armageddon (2006)\n|image      = WWEarmageddon06.jpg\n|alt        =\n|caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Dave Batista|Batista]]\n|tagline    = The End...Is Only the Beginning\n|theme      =\n|promotion  = [[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]]\n|brand      = [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]]\n|date       = December 17, 2006\n|venue      = [[Richmond Coliseum]]\n|city       = [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n|attendance = 8,200\n|lastevent  = [[December to Dismember (2006)|December to Dismember]]\n|nextevent  = [[New Year's Revolution (2007)|New Year's Revolution]]\n|event      = [[WWE Armageddon|Armageddon]]\n|lastevent2 = [[Armageddon (2005)|2005]]\n|nextevent2 = [[Armageddon (2007)|2007]]\n}}\n'''Armageddon (2006)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of WWE pay-per-view events|event]] produced by [[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE). It took place on December 17, 2006, at the [[Richmond Coliseum]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]]. The event starred [[List of World Wrestling Entertainment employees|wrestlers]] from the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]] [[WWE Brand Extension|brand]].<ref name=\"SLAM!\">{{cite web|first=Brian|last=Elliott|date=December 17, 2006|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2006/12/18/2859158.html|title=Unexpected ladder contest steals Armageddon|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|work=Slam! Sports|accessdate=March 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team match]], in which the team of [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[John Cena]] defeated the team of [[Booker Huffman|King Booker]] and [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]].<ref name=\"Cena & Batista vs Booker & Finlay\">{{cite web|first=Brett|last=Hoffman|date=December 17, 2006|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/347294412/results/|title=Champs prevail|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=March 29, 2008}}</ref> Two featured bouts were scheduled on the undercard, including [[The Undertaker]] versus [[Mr. Kennedy]], in a match where the objective was to [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|place an opponent in a hearse located on the entrance stage and drive them out of the arena]], which Undertaker won.<ref name=\"Last Ride match\">{{cite web|first=Craig|last=Tello|date=December 17, 2006|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729442/results/|title=Ride to Hell|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=March 29, 2006}}</ref> The other match was an [[Professional wrestling match types#Inferno match|Inferno match]] featuring wrestlers attempting to set the opponent on fire with flames surrounding the [[wrestling ring|ring]]. [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] defeated [[Montel Vontavious Porter]].<ref name=\"Inferno match\">{{cite web|first=Mike|last=McAvennie|date=December 17, 2006|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729443/results/|title=Back-burner|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=March 18, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331201448/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729443/results/|archivedate=March 31, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe event grossed over $423,500 in ticket sales from an attendance of 8,200. [[Canadian Online Explorer]]'s professional wrestling section rated the WWE Tag Team Championship match a nine out of ten stars, the highest match rating. The event was released on [[DVD]] on January 16, 2007 by [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. The DVD reached second on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s'' DVD Sales Chart for recreational sports during the week of February 18, 2007, and it dropped to the tenth spot the following week.\n\n==Storylines==\nArmageddon (2006) was the seventh annual [[WWE Armageddon|Armageddon]] event. Eight professional wrestling matches, were featured on the event's [[Card (sports)|card]].\n\n[[Image:Cena With Spinner Belt.jpg|thumb|left|upright|John Cena teamed up with Batista against King Booker and Finlay]]\nThe leading [[Feud (professional wrestling)|staged rivalry]] written into the event was between [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[Booker Huffman|King Booker]]. At [[Survivor Series (2006)|Survivor Series]], WWE's November pay-per-view event, Batista defeated Booker to win the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=\"SurvivorSeries\"/><ref name=\"SurvivorSeries2\"/> On the December 1, 2006 episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'', one of WWE's primary television programs, King Booker and [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]] both demanded a match against Batista for the World Heavyweight Championship. [[Professional wrestling authority figures#General Managers 2|General Manager]] [[Theodore Long]], a portrayed match maker and rules enforcer, announced that Booker and Finlay would instead form a [[tag team]] to compete against Batista and a partner of his choice at Armageddon. Later that night, Batista announced that his partner would be [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]] [[John Cena]], a member of the ''[[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]]'' brand.<ref name=\"December1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1165033362.shtml|last=Martin|first=Adam|title=World Title and more|date=December 1, 2006|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref> The following week on an episode of ''SmackDown!'', Batista defeated Finlay by [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]] after Booker interfered on Finlay's behalf.<ref name=\"December8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1165636943.shtml|title=Booker and Finlay unite|date=December 8, 2006|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref> On the December 15 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Cena defeated Finlay after lifting Finlay up on his shoulders and slamming him to the mat, a move that Cena dubbed the [[Professional wrestling throws#Fireman's carry takeover|FU]].<ref name=\"December15\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_11157.shtml|title=12/16 WWE Smackdown review: Giebink's Express v3.0 (Hr. 2)|date=December 15, 2006|publisher=PWTorch.com|last=Giebink|first=Dusty|accessdate=October 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe secondary rivalry was between [[The Undertaker]] and [[Mr. Kennedy]]. On the September 8, 2006 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Kennedy announced that he was looking for a new opponent, one that he had never faced before. Long informed Kennedy that he knew a SmackDown! superstar that had never faced Kennedy, The Undertaker. A match was made between the two for [[No Mercy (2006)|No Mercy]], in which Kennedy defeated Undertaker by disqualification.<ref name=\"NoMercy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/history/2006/matches/322528211/results/|title=Undertaker shows No Mercy on Kennedy|last=Hunt|first=Jen|date=October 8, 2006|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"NoMercy2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1191814054.shtml|title=WWE No Mercy PPV Results|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=October 8, 2006|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906002529/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1191814054.shtml|archivedate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> At Survivor Series, Kennedy once again defeated Undertaker in a [[Professional wrestling match types#First Blood match|First Blood match]].<ref name=\"SurvivorSeries\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/2006/matches/33324801111/results/|title=First blood, last laugh|last=McAvennie|first=Mike|date=November 26, 2006|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=July 12, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821195437/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/2006/matches/33324801111/results/|archivedate=August 21, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"SurvivorSeries2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1164599352.shtml|title=WWE Survivor Series PPV Results|date=November 26, 2006|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919054919/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1164599352.shtml|archivedate=September 19, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the December 1 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Undertaker fought [[Montel Vontavious Porter]] (MVP) in a match where [[Professional wrestling#No contest|neither wrestler won]]. During the match, MVP was scripted to attempt escaping from the ring, but Kennedy caught him during the process and tried to throw him back into the ring. MVP instead threw Kennedy in. Undertaker then kicked Kennedy in the face, and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] attacked MVP at ringside.<ref name=\"December1\"/> The following week as Kennedy was in the ring, the [[hearse]], appearing to have nobody in the driver's seat, drove into the arena; suddenly, The Undertaker appeared from the back of the hearse, as Kennedy sprung from the ring. Later that night, Kane defeated Kennedy by [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]] after MVP interfered on Kennedy's behalf.<ref name=\"December8\"/> On the December 15 episode of ''SmackDown!'', [[The Brothers of Destruction|The Undertaker and Kane]] teamed together to face Kennedy and MVP in a tag team match, which ended in [[Professional wrestling#No contest|neither team winning]]. Kennedy knocked Kane down in the aisle and jumped into the driver's seat of the hearse that had been at ringside for the match, and threatened to run him over with it however the Undertaker appeared in the passenger side seat scaring Kennedy off.<ref name=\"December15\"/>\n\nThe third rivalry was between [[Montel Vontavious Porter]] (MVP) and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]]. After MVP signed with the SmackDown! brand and made his debut, he begged [[Theodore Long]] for more competition. Kane answered the challenge but MVP got himself [[Disqualification (professional wrestling)|disqualified]] when he low blowed Kane to escape Kane's chokeslam. Over the past few months, MVP defeated Kane in a [[Hardcore wrestling|street fight]] with help from [[Mr. Kennedy]] (who was feuding with [[The Undertaker]]) and later defeated Kane in a [[steel cage match]] by escaping the cage. Theodore Long later announced that since MVP and Kane are so evenly matched the two would do battle at Armageddon in an [[Inferno match]]. A match in which a wrestler must be victorious by setting his opponent on fire in a ring surrounded by flames\n\n==Event==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+ '''Other on-screen personnel'''\n!|Role:\n!|Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=2|English [[Sportscaster|commentators]]\n|[[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]]\n|-\n|[[John Layfield|John Bradshaw Layfield]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Spanish commentators\n|[[Carlos Cabrera]]\n|-\n|[[Hugo Savinovich]]\n|-\n|[[Ring announcer]]\n|[[Tony Chimel]]\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Referee (professional wrestling)|Referees]]\n|[[Nick Patrick (referee)|Nick Patrick]]\n|-\n|[[Charles Robinson (referee)|Charles Robinson]]\n|-\n|[[Jim Korderas]]\n|-\n|[[Brian Hebner]]\n|}\n\n===Preliminary matches===\n[[Image:MVP! (2).jpg|thumb|right|[[Montel Vontavious Porter]], who faced Kane in an Inferno match]]\nThe first match to air live was between Kane and MVP in an [[Professional wrestling match types#Inferno match|Inferno match]]. The only way to win an Inferno match is by throwing one's opponent into a fire that surrounds the ring on all four sides. This match was the first time that the Inferno match had been used on pay-per-view in more than [[Unforgiven: In Your House|seven years]].<ref name=\"December22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1166843826.shtml|last=Martin|first=Adam|title=Taker & Kane, more|publisher=WrestleView|date=December 22, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref> At the start of the match, MVP attempted to leave the ring, but was unable to as the flames surrounding the ring prevented him. Kane kicked MVP in the head and threw him into the ring corner. MVP escaped the ring and was unable to go past the fire, so he returned to the ring and was continuously knocked down by Kane. The finish of the match saw Kane grab MVP and force him backwards into the fire. MVP's costume caught on fire as he ran to the entrance ramp. MVP fell to the floor as WWE workers put out the flames with fire extinguishers.<ref name=\"results\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1197864103.shtml|title=WWE Armageddon PPV Results|publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=December 18, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081003064215/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1197864103.shtml|archivedate=October 3, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MVPKane\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729443/results/|title=Back-burner|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=McAvennie|first=Mike|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe following match featured [[Paul London and Brian Kendrick]], [[The Blue Bloods#World Wrestling Entertainment|William Regal and Dave Taylor]], [[MNM (wrestling)|MNM]] ([[Adam Birch|Joey Mercury]], and [[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]), and [[Hardy Boyz|The Hardys]] ([[Matt Hardy|Matt]] and [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Champion]] [[Jeff Hardy|Jeff]]) in a four-team [[ladder match]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]]. In this match, the only way to win and capture the titles was by climbing a ladder and releasing the championship belts that were suspended above the ring. Towards the end of the match, while MNM and The Hardys were out of the ring, Regal and Taylor attempted to climb the ladder, but Kendrick managed to knock the pair off. Kendrick fought off Regal and Taylor as London climbed the ladder and captured the titles to win the match for his team and retain the championships. During the match, Mercury suffered a legitimate nose injury after being hit by a ladder.<ref name=\"WWEMag35\">{{cite journal|date=December 2007|title=This Month on Pay-Per-View|journal=[[WWE Magazine]]|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|issue=December 2007|pages=35}}</ref><ref name=\"WWEMag36\">{{cite journal|date=December 2007|title=Back up the Ladder|journal=[[WWE Magazine]]|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|issue=December 2007|pages=36}}</ref><ref name=\"TagTeamt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729444/results/|title=Climbing the rungs of respect|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Tello|first=Craig|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n{{quote|I happened to be looking up, so it hit me in the throat. But Mercury was looking straight at it and it hit him square in the nose and the orbital bone. It really could have been any one of us. I was just lucky that the ladder hit him first.|[[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]|<ref name=\"WWEMag36\" />}}\n{{quote|I'll always remember [the match] for what we did to Joey Mercury's face. After the seesaw, I remember hearing him yell, \"I'm bleeding,\" and it was like someone went to a sink and turned the faucet on. It was gruesome.|[[Matt Hardy]]|<ref name=\"WWEMag36\" />}}\n\nThe third match was a [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|standard wrestling match]] between [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]] and [[Mike Mizanin|The Miz]]. The Boogeyman controlled the majority of the match and eventually won by [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinfall]] after a [[Powerbomb#Falling powerbomb|Falling]] [[Powerbomb#Chokebomb|Chokebomb]].<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"BoogeymanMiz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/347294441/results/|title=A worm welcome|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Starr|first=Noah|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe next match featured [[Chris Benoit]] defending the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]] against [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]] ([[Manager (professional wrestling)|accompanied]] by [[Vickie Guerrero]]). Before the bell rang to start the match, Chavo tried to attack Benoit, but as the match began, Benoit retaliated by delivering a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Clothesline|clothesline]]. Benoit and Guerrero wrestled inconclusively until Benoit covered Chavo to try to pin him. Chavo managed to place his foot on top of the bottom rope, which forced Benoit to break the pin per official wrestling match rules. While Guerrero was lying on his stomach, Benoit applied the [[sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Sharpshooter]], and made Chavo submit to retain the championship.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"UnitedStates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729441/results/|title=Wolveriene prevails at Armageddon|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821190044/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729441/results/|archivedate=August 21, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe fifth match was the encounter of [[Gregory Helms]] and [[James Yun|Jimmy Wang Yang]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]. Helms performed a [[Neckbreaker#Swinging neckbreaker|swinging neckbreaker]] on Yang. Yang retaliated, but Helms quickly moved back into the power position and pinned Yang to retain the championship.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"Cruiserweight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/347294441/results/|title=Helms still in Cruiserweight control|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=McAvennie|first=Mike|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Main event matches===\n[[Image:Undertaker Milwaukee WI 031008.jpg|thumb|upright|The Undertaker. who faced Mr. Kennedy in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Last Ride match]] at Armageddon]]\nThe following match was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Last Ride match]] between [[The Undertaker]] and [[Mr. Kennedy]], where the only way to win was by throwing one's opponent into a hearse and driving it out of the arena. During the beginning of the match, The Undertaker tossed Kennedy into steel steps on the side of the ring and then onto the commentator's announcing table. The Undertaker then threw Kennedy into the ring apron, which is the apron covering the area under the ring. Kennedy and The Undertaker wrestled inconclusively until The Undertaker tossed Kennedy on top of the roof of the hearse. The Undertaker then delivered a [[Chokeslam]] and a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Tombstone piledriver|Tombstone Piledriver]], both onto the roof of the hearse. As he was still in control of the match, The Undertaker threw Kennedy into the hearse and drove it out of the arena to win the match.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"TakerKennedy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/34729442/results/|title=Ride to Hell|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Tello|first=Craig|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Last Ride match, [[Jillian Hall]], [[Layla El]], [[Ashley Massaro]], and [[Kristal Marshall]] all took part in a \"Naughty or Nice\" contest, a [[lingerie]] contest, where the [[WWE Diva|Diva]] with the loudest fan reaction would win. The host of the contest was [[Santa Claus]] (portrayed by Big Dick Johnson, otherwise Christopher DeJoseph). Johnson declared all four of the Divas as the winners and proceeded to take off his Santa costume and dance to music being played in the arena.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"DivaContest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/3472944411/results/|title=Secret Santa|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Starr|first=Noah|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe main event was the tag team match between John Cena and Batista versus the team of King Booker and Finlay. Batista wrestled the match with his left arm taped up due to a previous injury. Both teams wrestlers inconclusively until Cena applied the [[Professional wrestling holds#STS|STFU]] on Booker. Finlay broke the submission hold, and [[Hornswoggle|The Little Bastard]] ran into the ring. Little Bastard attempted to kick Cena, but accidentally kicked himself in his head when Cena moved out of the way. Then, Booker tried to [[superkick]] Batista, but Batista moved out of the way, and Booker accidentally hit Finlay. Batista then delivered a [[Powerbomb|Batista Bomb]] and pinned Booker to earn the victory for his team.<ref name=\"results\" /><ref name=\"MainEvent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006/matches/347294412/results/|title=Champs prevail|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Hoffman|first=Brett|date=December 17, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nOn the December 22, 2006 episode of ''SmackDown!'', King Booker and Finlay demanded a rematch against Batista and John Cena. General Manager Theodore Long informed the pair that they would instead be facing Kane and The Undertaker later that night in a match, which Kane and The Undertaker won. At the [[Royal Rumble (2007)|Royal Rumble]], the [[Royal Rumble#Match|Royal Rumble match]] was held, where the winner is the final person left in the ring after the other twenty nine wrestlers are eliminated by being thrown over the top ring rope. The Undertaker won the Royal Rumble match to earn a title shot at [[WrestleMania 23]].<ref name=\"Rumble\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2007/|title=A Phenom-enal Rumble|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Dee|first=Louie|date=January 28, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709054906/http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/2007/|archivedate=July 9, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"RoyalRumble\" /> At WrestleMania, he defeated Batista to win the World Heavyweight Championship and maintain his WrestleMania [[The Streak (wrestling)|undefeated streak]].<ref name=\"WrestleMania\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wrestlemania23/matches/3916184/results/|title=The streak lives on for The Deadman|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=Hunt|first=Jen|date=April 1, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nChris Benoit continued to feud with Chavo Guerrero over the [[WWE United States Championship]]. On the December 22, 2006 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Benoit defeated Guerrero in a rematch for the title, with Vickie Guerrero accompanying Chavo to ringside. Benoit won the match by disqualification when Vickie hit Benoit in the head with the championship belt.<ref name=\"December22\" /><ref name=\"WWEDecember22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/12222006/|title=Bells will be ringing|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|date=December 22, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref> On the January 12, 2007 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Mr. Kennedy defeated Chris Benoit in a standard match, with help from Chavo Guerrero.<ref name=\"January12\" /><ref name=\"WWEJanuary12\" /> The following week, Benoit defeated Chavo yet again with the championship on the line.<ref name=\"January19\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1169269456.shtml|title=Taker and Kennedy|publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=January 19, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906210109/http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1169269456.shtml|archivedate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe feuds between Kane and Montel Vontavious Porter (MVP), and The Undertaker and Mr. Kennedy did not continue after the event. On the January 5, 2007, episode of ''SmackDown!'', Kennedy set the time to beat in the \"Beat the Clock\" sprint, a tournament based on the time wrestlers win matches, to become the new number one contender for the World Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=\"WWEJanuary5\" /><ref name=\"January5\" /> On the January 12 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Kennedy won the \"Beat the Clock\" sprint by preventing The Undertaker from winning his match and from beating Kennedy's time. At the Royal Rumble, Batista defeated Kennedy to retain the title.<ref name=\"RoyalRumble\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1170044000.shtml|title=Royal Rumble PPV Results|last=Nemner|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|date=January 28, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref> The feuds between Gregory Helms and Jimmy Wang Yang, and The Boogeyman and The Miz also did not continue, as Helms was put into a rivalry with The Boogeyman.<ref name=\"WWEJanuary5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/01052007/|title=Race against time|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|date=January 5, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"January5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1168055099.shtml|title=Beat the Clock sprint|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|date=January 5, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828210853/http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1168055099.shtml|archivedate=August 28, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> Yang was put into a temporary rivalry with [[Chris Chavis|Tatanka]].<ref name=\"January12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1168672396.shtml|title=Beat the Clock winner|publisher=WrestleView|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=January 12, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906140552/http://www.wrestleview.com/results/smackdown/smackdown2006/1168672396.shtml|archivedate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"WWEJanuary12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/01122007/|title=Race against time|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|date=January 12, 2006|accessdate=July 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe Richmond Coliseum has a maximum capacity of 13,000, but that was reduced for the 2006 Armageddon event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.richmond.va.us/departments/parks/coliseum.aspx|title=Richmond Coliseum|publisher=RichmondGov.com|accessdate=August 23, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822103417/http://www.ci.richmond.va.us/departments/parks/coliseum.aspx|archivedate=August 22, 2008}}</ref> The event grossed over [[United States dollar|$]]423,500 in ticket sales from an attendance of 8,200. ''[[Canadian Online Explorer]]'s'' professional wrestling section rated the WWE Tag Team Championship match a nine out of ten stars, the highest match rating. The United States Championship, Cruiserweight Championship, and Last Ride matches all received seven out of ten stars. The main event match received a five and a half stars out of ten rating.<ref name=\"SLAM!\" />\n\nThe event was released on [[DVD]] on January 16, 2007,<ref name=\"DVD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fye.com/WWE--Armageddon-2006-Front-Page_stcVVproductId8332172VVcatId455366VVviewprod.htm|title=WWE: Armageddon|publisher=[[Trans World Entertainment|For Your Entertainment]]|accessdate=August 23, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925191926/http://www.fye.com/WWE--Armageddon-2006-Front-Page_stcVVproductId8332172VVcatId455366VVviewprod.htm|archivedate=September 25, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> by [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. The DVD reached second on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s'' DVD Sales Chart for recreational sports during the week of February 18, 2007, and it dropped to the tenth spot the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3064430&cdi=8551056&cid=02%2F25%2F2006|title=Video Sales \u2013 Recreational Sports DVD|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].com|accessdate=August 23, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114041045/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3064430&cdi=8551056&cid=02%2F25%2F2006|archivedate=January 14, 2009}}</ref> It remained on the chart's \"top ten\" for two consecutive weeks until the week of March 4, 2007, when it ranked 17th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3064603&cdi=8555487&cid=03%2F04%2F2006|title=Video Sales \u2013 Recreational Sports DVD|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 23, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114031714/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=394&cfgn=Videos&cfn=Video+Sales+-+Recreational+Sports+DVD&ci=3064603&cdi=8555487&cid=03%2F04%2F2006|archivedate=January 14, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|dark1  = yes\n|match1 = [[Vladimir Kozlov]] defeated [[Scotty 2 Hotty]]\n|stip1  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time1  = 2:01\n|match2 = [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] defeated [[Montel Vontavious Porter]]\n|stip2  = [[Inferno match]]\n|time2  = 08:14\n|match3 = [[Brian Kendrick and Paul London]] (c) defeated  [[Dave Taylor and William Regal]], [[The Hardy Boyz]] ([[Jeff Hardy]] and [[Matt Hardy]]) and  [[MNM (professional wrestling)|MNM]] ([[Joey Mercury]] and [[Johnny Nitro]]) (with [[Melina Perez|Melina]])\n|stip3  = [[Fatal 4-Way match|Fatal 4-Way]] [[ladder match]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Championship]]\n|time3  = 20:13\n|match4 = [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]] defeated [[The Miz]]\n|stip4  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time4  = 02:51\n|match5 = [[Chris Benoit]] (c) defeated [[Chavo Guerrero]] (with [[Vickie Guerrero]]) by submission\n|stip5  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE United States Championship]]\n|time5  = 12:14\n|match6 = [[Gregory Helms]] (c) defeated [[Jimmy Wang Yang]]\n|stip6  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|time6  = 10:51\n|match7 = [[The Undertaker]] defeated [[Mr. Kennedy]]\n|stip7  = [[Last Ride match]]\n|time7  = 19:49\n|match8 = [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] and [[John Cena]] defeated [[King Booker's Court]] ([[King Booker]] and [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]]) (with [[Queen Sharmell]])\n|stip8  = [[Tag team match]]\n|time8  = 11:29\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2006}}\n\n{{2006 WWE pay-per-view events}}\n{{WWEPPV|Armageddon}}\n\n[[Category:WWE Armageddon|2006]]\n[[Category:2006 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Events in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:2006 WWE pay-per-view events]]\n[[Category:December 2006 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohnny Nitro(link changed toJohn Morrison (wrestler)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armageddon_(2006)"}
{"title_page": "Maciej Ceg\u0142owski", "text_new": "[[File:-rp17 - Tag 3 (33731648674).jpg|thumb|Ceg\u0142owski speaking at the [[re:publica]] conference in 2017]]\n'''Maciej Ceg\u0142owski''' is a Polish-American web developer, [[entrepreneur]], speaker, and social critic, based in [[San Francisco]], [[California]]. He is the owner of the bookmarking service [[Pinboard (website)|Pinboard]],<ref name=\"readwriteweb-boring\">{{cite web |url= https://readwrite.com/2011/02/10/pinboard-creator-maciej-ceglow/ |title= Hacker Chat: Pinboard Creator Maciej Ceglowski Talks About Why Boring Architecture is Good, and More |author= Klint Finley |date= February 10, 2011 |work= ReadWriteHack |publisher= [[ReadWriteWeb]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"economist-fame\">{{cite web |url= https://www.economist.com/blogs/babbage/2011/04/price_fame |title= Price of fame: Stick a pin in it |author= G.F. |date= April 4, 2011 |work= Babbage |publisher= [[The Economist]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"Zuckerman\">{{cite web|last1=Zuckerman|first1=Ethan|author-link=Ethan Zuckerman|title=The Internet's Original Sin|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/08/advertising-is-the-internets-original-sin/376041/|website=The Atlantic|quote= The fiasco I want to talk about is the World Wide Web, specifically, the advertising-supported, \"free as in beer\" constellation of social networks, services, and content that represents so much of the present day web industry. I've been thinking of this world, one I've worked in for over 20 years, as a fiasco since reading a lecture by Maciej Ceg\u0142owski, delivered at the Beyond Tellerrand web design conference.  Ceg\u0142owski is an important and influential programmer and an enviably talented writer. His talk is a patient explanation of how we've ended up with surveillance as the default, if not sole, internet business model.|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref> which he calls a social bookmarking site for introverts.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://idlewords.com/about.htm |title=Idle Words - Maciej Ceg\u0142owski |publisher=idlewords.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-06}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCeg\u0142owski was born in Poland and \"accidentally immigrated\" to the United States with his mother at age six, in 1981, but calls himself \"as American as gooseberry pie.\"<ref name=\"about\" /><ref name=\"Web Design: The First 100 Years\"/> He attended [[Middlebury College]], where he studied Russian, French, and studio art,<ref name=\"Middlebury\">{{cite web|title=Middlebury College Students Receive Watson Fellowships|url=http://www.middlebury.edu/newsroom/archive/archive/1997/node/264328|publisher=[[Middlebury College]]|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> graduating with a BA in 1997. He then became a backend software developer and community manager at [[Yahoo!]]'s Brickhouse in [[San Francisco]]. While there, he created a visual search engine for airfares called FareMaps. As an independent contractor, he designed and built an internal data warehouse for [[Twitter]] and an online book reader for Otworz Ksiazke at the University of Warsaw.<ref name=crunchbase /> With [[Joshua Schachter]], founder of [[Delicious (website)|Delicious]], and Peter Gadjokov, Ceg\u0142owski created LOAF (List of All Friends) as a way to share social network information through email without exposing private information.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Livingston|first1=Jessica|title=Founders at work : stories of startups' early days|date=2008|publisher=Apress|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=978-1-4302-1078-8|page=229|edition=Pbk.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ktm885vGIXEC&pg=PT237&lpg=PT237&dq=LOAF+files+are+Bloom+filters&source=bl&ots=vUyJOfRDbh&sig=vvUwFDQY1WZR24Z8bX7R_7ySR8Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjaop_qyJfKAhUP6mMKHTwqDN0Q6AEIMzAE#v=onepage&q=LOAF%20files%20are%20Bloom%20filters&f=false|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe established Pinboard in 2009 after leaving Yahoo. He had been impressed by initial versions of the bookmarking service [[Delicious (website)|Delicious]], which Yahoo had bought.<ref name=\"Entrepreneurs Who Go It Alone \u2014 By Choice\">{{cite web|last1=Dell|first1=Kristina|title=Entrepreneurs Who Go It Alone \u2014 By Choice|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2094921_2094923_2094924-2,00.html|website=Time|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> However, he felt that it had been mismanaged by Yahoo! management and that it would be possible to produce a more successful website with the same concept.<ref name=\"McEwenCassimally2013\">{{cite book|author1=Adrian McEwen|author2=Hakim Cassimally|title=Designing the Internet of Things|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iYkKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT153|date=7 November 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-43065-1|pages=153\u20134}}</ref><ref name=\"An interview with Maciej Ceglowski of Pinboard\">{{cite web|last1=Perrine|first1=Tom|title=An interview with Maciej Ceglowski of Pinboard|url=https://thuktun.wordpress.com/2011/01/03/an-interview-with-maciej-ceglowski-of-pinboard/|website=Thuktun (blog)|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Quick thoughts on Pinboard\">{{cite web|last1=Haughey|first1=Matt|title=Quick thoughts on Pinboard (review)|url=http://a.wholelottanothing.org/2010/12/quick-thoughts-on-pinboard.html|website=Whole Lotta Nothing|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Ovadia2013\">{{cite book|author=Steven Ovadia|title=The Librarian's Guide to Academic Research in the Cloud|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uGNEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124|date=30 September 2013|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-1-78063-381-7|pages=124, 172}}</ref> As of 2016, he remains Pinboard's only full-time employee. The business is a model of a small ad-free pay-for-service that emphasizes privacy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maciej Ceglowski|url=http://www.webstock.org.nz/14/speakers/maciej-ceglowski/|website=Webstock 14|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Ceg\u0142owski announced a project called the Pinboard Investment Co-Prosperity Cloud, offering $37 and promotion for six [[Startup company|startup companies]], to encourage [[Bootstrapping (business)#Financial Bootstrapping|bootstrapping]] technology companies with low costs.<ref name=\"mashable-entrepreneurs\">{{cite web |url= http://mashable.com/2012/12/18/pinboard-startup-fund/ |title= Why Entrepreneurs Are Competing for $37 From This Startup Incubator |author= Seth Fiegerman |date= December 18, 2012 |work= Business |publisher= [[Mashable]] |accessdate=December 30, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"wired-cheapest\">{{cite web |url= https://www.wired.com/business/2012/12/worlds-cheapest-venture-capitalist/ |title= Meet the World's Cheapest Venture Capitalist |author= Ryan Tate |date= December 14, 2012 |work= Business |publisher= [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=December 30, 2012 }}</ref> He awarded winners in January 2013.<ref name=\"wired-spending\">{{cite web |url= https://www.wired.com/business/2013/01/pinboard-spending/ |title= How to Spend a $37 Venture-Capital Infusion |author= Ryan Tate |date= January 21, 2013 |work= Business |publisher= [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=March 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Ceg\u0142owski entered a competition on [[Hacker News]] that would have allowed Pinboard to become a [[Y Combinator (company)|Y Combinator]] Fellow. In light of his frequent criticism of Y Combinator, he humorously described his entry as \"a tremendous, huge opportunity to fund the Bay Area's slowest-growing unicorn.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Apply HN: Pinboard \u2013 Make Y Combinator Great Again|url=https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=11441480|website=Hacker News|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>  Pinboard was not chosen for the fellowship, despite receiving the largest number of votes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tell HN: Winners of Apply HN for YC Fellowship 3|url=https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=11633278|website=Hacker News|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was credited as a technical consultant for the 2018 season of [[HBO]] sitcom [[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Maciej Ceglowski|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9730650/|website=IMDb|accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Speaking and writing ==\nCeg\u0142owski is particularly known for his conference talks on the impacts of technology, and for posting on [[Twitter]], which he uses to joke about the failings and inflated claims of [[Silicon Valley]] companies.<ref name=\"techcrunch-comments\">{{cite news |url= https://techcrunch.com/2016/04/09/dear-facebook-why-are-facebook-comments-so-unremittingly-terrible/ |title= Dear Facebook, why are Facebook Comments so unremittingly terrible?|author= Jon Evans |date= 2016-04-09 |work= [[TechCrunch]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref><ref name=\"techcrunch-money\">{{cite news |url= https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/21/and-realpolitik-for-free/ |title= Money For Nothing For Everyone |author= Jon Evans |date= 2015-11-21 |work= [[TechCrunch]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref><ref name=\"register-ifttt\">{{cite web |url= https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/03/30/love_our_open_api_talk_to_our_lawyers_says_if_this_then_that/ |title= Love our open API? Talk to our lawyers, says If This Then That |author= Richard Chirgwin |date= 2016-03-30|website= [[The Register]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref> He has written and spoken extensively on the problems of advertising-funded services with dubious business models.<ref name=\"Inside Higher Ed\">{{cite web|last1=Fister|first1=Barbara|title=Maciej Ceglowski's Internet Repair Kit|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/blogs/library-babel-fish/maciej-ceglowskis-internet-repair-kit|website=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"The Advertising Bubble\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=The Advertising Bubble|url=http://idlewords.com/2015/11/the_advertising_bubble.htm|website=Idle Words (blog)|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Doctorow\"/> He has described programmatically generated advertising and data mining as a business model that encourages the growth of surveillance.<ref name=\"Doctorow\">{{cite web |last1=Doctorow |first1=Cory |title=Big Data's religious faith denies the reality of failed promises, privacy Chernobyls |url=https://boingboing.net/2015/10/07/big-datas-religious-faith-de.html |website=Boing Boing |date=2015-10-07 |accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpo-crossroads\">{{cite news |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/advertising-week/digital-advertising-at-th_b_8989994.html |title= Digital Advertising at the Crossroads: Will Angry Consumers Block Brands? |author= Zak Pollack |date= 2016-01-15 |work= [[Huffington Post]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref><ref name=\"Doctorow-\">{{cite web |last1=Doctorow |first1=Cory |title=Big Data refusal: the nuclear disarmament movement of the 21st century |url=http://boingboing.net/2015/11/03/big-data-refusal-the-nuclear.html |website=Boing Boing|date=2015-11-03 |accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref> In particular, Ceg\u0142owski has compared large stocks of data on Internet users to the archives of Communist secret police services in his native Central Europe, as a threat to user privacy that may increase as archives remain in existence.<ref name=\"atlantic-sin\">{{cite magazine |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/08/advertising-is-the-internets-original-sin/376041/?single_page=true |title= The Internet's Original Sin |author= [[Ethan Zuckerman]] |date= August 14, 2014 |magazine= [[The Atlantic]] |accessdate= November 13, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"What Happens Next Will Amaze You\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=What Happens Next Will Amaze You|url=http://idlewords.com/talks/what_happens_next_will_amaze_you.htm|website=Idle Words (blog)|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Persuading David Simon Gruber\">{{cite web|last1=Gruber|first1=John|title=Persuading David Simon|url=https://daringfireball.net/linked/2013/06/18/ceglowski-simon|website=Daring Fireball|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"The Internet With a Human Face\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=The Internet With a Human Face|url=http://idlewords.com/talks/internet_with_a_human_face.htm|website=Idle Words (blog)|publisher=Beyond Tellerrand Conference|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Datanami\">{{cite web|last1=Woodie|first1=Alex|title=Big Data Really Freaks This Guy Out|url=http://www.datanami.com/2015/10/01/big-data-really-freaks-this-guy-out/|website=Datanami|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref> He has also argued in favour of simplified, more minimal web design, arguing that immersive web design can be [[Software bloat|bloated]] and unsuitable for consumers with a poor internet connection.<ref name=\"Web Design: The First 100 Years\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=Web Design: The First 100 Years|url=http://idlewords.com/talks/web_design_first_100_years.htm|website=Idle Words|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"The Website Obesity Crisis\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=The Website Obesity Crisis|url=http://idlewords.com/talks/website_obesity.htm|website=Idle Words (blog)|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Is Google's Fight With Facebook Undermining a Web That's Fair to Everyone?\">{{cite web|last1=Dale|first1=Brady|title=Is Google's Fight With Facebook Undermining a Web That's Fair to Everyone?|url=http://observer.com/2016/03/google-accelerated-mobile-pages-facebook-w3c/|website=Observer|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Maciej Ceglowski on why the modern web is so bloated and slow, and why it matters\">{{cite web|last1=Gruber|first1=John|title=Maciej Ceglowski on why the modern web is so bloated and slow, and why it matters|url=https://daringfireball.net/linked/2016/01/02/website-obesity-crisis|website=Daring Fireball|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Doctorow-tools\">{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|author-link=Cory Doctorow |title=Tools, ads, and bad defaults: Web bloat continues unabated |url=http://boingboing.net/2016/01/01/tools-ads-and-bad-defaults.html |website=Boing Boing |date=2016-01-01|accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Doctorow-botwars\">{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|author-link=Cory Doctorow|title=Botwars vs ad-tech: the origin story of universal surveillance on the Internet|url=http://boingboing.net/2015/10/05/botwars-vs-ad-tech-the-origin.html|website=Boing Boing|date=2015-10-05|accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"techcrunch-block\">{{cite news |url= https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/26/i-like-to-block-it-block-it/ |title= I Like To Block It Block It |author= Jon Evans |date= 2015-09-26 |work= [[TechCrunch]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref> [[Cory Doctorow]] has described him as a \"characteristically provocative\" writer of \"barn-burning speeches about the Internet's problems\".<ref name=\"Doctorow-human-face\">{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|author-link=Cory Doctorow|title=The Internet With a Human Face: Maciej Ceg\u0142owski on the things we need to fix|url=http://boingboing.net/2014/05/27/the-internet-with-a-human-face.html|website=Boing Boing|date=2014-05-27|accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Botwars vs ad-tech: the origin story of universal surveillance on the Internet\">{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|title=Botwars vs ad-tech: the origin story of universal surveillance on the Internet|url=https://boingboing.net/2015/10/05/botwars-vs-ad-tech-the-origin.html|website=Boing Boing|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref><ref name='After a rush, aviation stopped \"progressing\" -- the Web might be next'>{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|title=After a rush, aviation stopped \"progressing\" -- the Web might be next|url=https://boingboing.net/2015/07/21/after-a-rush-aviation-stopped.html|website=Boing Boing|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box\n| quote = Tech companies are run by a feckless leadership accountable to no one, creating a toolkit for authoritarianism while hypnotized by science-fiction fantasy.\n| align = right\n| width = 240px\n| quoted = 1\n| author = Maciej Ceglowski, in a public appearance<ref name=\"brokeassstuart\">{{cite web |url=http://brokeassstuart.com/blog/2017/06/08/prankster-tricks-y-combinator-into-supporting-the-homeless/|title=Prankster tricks tech incubator into supporting homeless people|author=Matthew Gering|date=2017-06-08|accessdate= 2017-06-16}}</ref>\n}}\n\nCeg\u0142owski has spoken at conferences including dConstruct, [[Webstock]], [[XOXO (festival)|XOXO Festival]], [[O'Reilly Media]]'s Strata+Hadoop and Emerging Technology Conferences,<ref>{{cite web|title=Speakers - O'Reilly Emerging Technology Conference 2003|url=http://conferences.oreillynet.com/pub/w/22/speakers.html|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> the Canadian University Software Engineering Conference, and beyond tellerrand. He has spoken about his experience of running his own company, including listening to users from the fandom community and \"failing really, really slowly\", working on a project for a long time instead of looking for immediate success.<ref name=\"uk-dconstruct\">{{cite web |url= http://digital.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/2013/09/10/notes-from-dconstruct-2013/ |title= Notes from dConstruct 2013 |author= Matt Sheret |date= September 10, 2013 |work= |publisher= [[Government Digital Service]] |accessdate= December 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"wired-slowly\">{{cite web |url= https://www.wired.com/business/2013/11/the-next-big-thing-you-missed/ |title= Why the Most Ambitious of Tech Startups Should Fail Slowly |author= Ryan Tate |date= November 19, 2013 |work= The Next Big Thing You Missed |publisher= [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate= December 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Elite Daily\">{{cite web|last1=Koziara|first1=Chip|title=Why The Most Important Step In Creating A Startup Is Selling Your Idea|url=http://elitedaily.com/life/why-to-sell-ideas-now/1303877/|website=Elite Daily|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Pinboard explains why you should care about fandom\">{{cite web|title=Pinboard explains why you should care about fandom|url=https://adainitiative.org/2014/04/23/pinboard-explains-why-you-should-care-about-fandom/|publisher=[[Ada Initiative]]|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref> Ceg\u0142owski has discussed prioritising simplicity and stability over using cutting-edge technologies for building Pinboard in order to reduce cost and allow his company to remain simple and practical for a single person to run.<ref name=\"readwriteweb-boring\" /><ref name=\"An interview with Maciej Ceglowski of Pinboard\"/><ref name=\"The Website Obesity Crisis\"/> He also gave a talk about the negative effects of advertising being the economic foundation of the web, as a model that encourages the growth of surveillance.<ref name=\"atlantic-sin\"/>\n\nCeg\u0142owski writes a Pinboard blog on topics including new features, site growth, the benefits of paying for services in general,<ref name=\"guardian-goodbye\">{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/blog/2011/dec/16/goodbye-delicious-hello-pinboard-bookmarking-guardian |title= Goodbye Delicious, hello Pinboard: why we'll pay for internet plumbing |author= Charles Arthur |date= December 16, 2011 |work= Technology Blog |publisher= [[The Guardian]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref> technical aspects of running Pinboard, and critical commentary about social websites like [[Facebook]].<ref name=\"oreilly-graph\">{{cite web |url= http://radar.oreilly.com/2011/11/social-graph-cloudera-kaggle-gps-law.html |title= Strata Week: The social graph that isn't |author= Audrey Watters |date= November 10, 2011 |work= O'Reilly Radar |publisher= [[O'Reilly Media]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref> Ceg\u0142owski has discussed prioritizing speed and stability over using cutting-edge technologies for building Pinboard.<ref name=\"readwriteweb-boring\"/>\n\nHis personal blog, Idlewords, includes blog posts and short essays Ceg\u0142owski has written since 2002, mostly about travel and food, including his 36-day voyage to [[Antarctica]]'s [[Ross Ice Shelf]] in 2016 which he financed through [[Kickstarter]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=An Antarctic Appeal|url=http://idlewords.com/2015/07/an_antarctic_appeal.htm|website=Idlewords|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe has written occasional features for ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''.<ref name=\"How to Hide from the Internet while travelling\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=I'm Going to Antarctica for the Penguins and to Hide From the Internet|url=https://www.wired.com/2016/03/how-to-ditch-the-internet-while-traveling/|website=Wired|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Meet the World's Cheapest Venture Capitalist\">{{cite web|last1=Tate|first1=Ryan|title=Meet the World's Cheapest Venture Capitalist|url=https://www.wired.com/2012/12/worlds-cheapest-venture-capitalist/|website=Wired|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> and opinion pieces for [[The New York Times]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ceglowski|first1=Maciej|title=We Need a More Forgetful Internet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2012/12/11/privacy-and-the-apps-you-download/we-need-a-more-forgetful-internet|accessdate=7 January 2016|work=New York Times|publisher=New York Times|date=2012-12-11}}</ref> His ideas have been quoted in [[Time (magazine)|Time]],<ref name=\"Entrepreneurs Who Go It Alone \u2014 By Choice\" /> [[The Atlantic]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zuckerman|first1=Ethan|title=The Internet's Original Sin|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/08/advertising-is-the-internets-original-sin/376041/|accessdate=7 January 2016|work=The Atlantic|date=August 2014}}</ref> [[The Guardian]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arthur|first1=Charles|title=Goodbye Delicious, hello Pinboard: why we'll pay for internet plumbing|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/blog/2011/dec/16/goodbye-delicious-hello-pinboard-bookmarking-guardian|accessdate=25 August 2016|work=The Guardian|date=16 December 2011}}</ref> [[The Economist]],<ref name=\"economist-fame\"/> [[TechCrunch]], [[Wired (magazine)|Wired News]],<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Thompson|first1=Clive|title=Clive Thompson on the Problem With Online Ads|url=https://www.wired.com/2011/08/st_thompson_onlineads/|magazine=Wired News|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> [[Bloomberg News#Bloomberg View|Bloomberg View]], [[Mashable]] and [[Gigaom]].<ref name=\"crunchbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/person/maciej-ceglowski#/entity |title=Maciej Ceglowski |publisher=crunchbase.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.idlewords.com Idlewords (Personal blog)]\n* {{twitter}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ceglowski, Maciej}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:Middlebury College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American technology company founders]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Yahoo! employees]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American humorists]]\n[[Category:American company founders]]\n[[Category:American software engineers]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:-rp17 - Tag 3 (33731648674).jpg|thumb|Ceg\u0142owski speaking at the [[re:publica]] conference in 2017]]\n'''Maciej Ceg\u0142owski''' is a Polish-American web developer, [[entrepreneur]], speaker, and social critic, based in [[San Francisco]], [[California]]. He is the owner of the bookmarking service [[Pinboard (website)|Pinboard]],<ref name=\"readwriteweb-boring\">{{cite web |url= https://readwrite.com/2011/02/10/pinboard-creator-maciej-ceglow/ |title= Hacker Chat: Pinboard Creator Maciej Ceglowski Talks About Why Boring Architecture is Good, and More |author= Klint Finley |date= February 10, 2011 |work= ReadWriteHack |publisher= [[ReadWriteWeb]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"economist-fame\">{{cite web |url= https://www.economist.com/blogs/babbage/2011/04/price_fame |title= Price of fame: Stick a pin in it |author= G.F. |date= April 4, 2011 |work= Babbage |publisher= [[The Economist]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"Zuckerman\">{{cite web|last1=Zuckerman|first1=Ethan|author-link=Ethan Zuckerman|title=The Internet's Original Sin|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/08/advertising-is-the-internets-original-sin/376041/|website=The Atlantic|quote= The fiasco I want to talk about is the World Wide Web, specifically, the advertising-supported, \"free as in beer\" constellation of social networks, services, and content that represents so much of the present day web industry. I've been thinking of this world, one I've worked in for over 20 years, as a fiasco since reading a lecture by Maciej Ceg\u0142owski, delivered at the Beyond Tellerrand web design conference.  Ceg\u0142owski is an important and influential programmer and an enviably talented writer. His talk is a patient explanation of how we've ended up with surveillance as the default, if not sole, internet business model.|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref> which he calls a social bookmarking site for introverts.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://idlewords.com/about.htm |title=Idle Words - Maciej Ceg\u0142owski |publisher=idlewords.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-06}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCeg\u0142owski was born in Poland and \"accidentally immigrated\" to the United States with his mother at age six, in 1981, but calls himself \"as American as gooseberry pie.\"<ref name=\"about\" /><ref name=\"Web Design: The First 100 Years\"/> He attended [[Middlebury College]], where he studied Russian, French, and studio art,<ref name=\"Middlebury\">{{cite web|title=Middlebury College Students Receive Watson Fellowships|url=http://www.middlebury.edu/newsroom/archive/archive/1997/node/264328|publisher=[[Middlebury College]]|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> graduating with a BA in 1997. He then became a backend software developer and community manager at [[Yahoo!]]'s Brickhouse in [[San Francisco]]. While there, he created a visual search engine for airfares called FareMaps. As an independent contractor, he designed and built an internal data warehouse for [[Twitter]] and an online book reader for Otworz Ksiazke at the University of Warsaw.<ref name=crunchbase /> With [[Joshua Schachter]], founder of [[Delicious (website)|Delicious]], and Peter Gadjokov, Ceg\u0142owski created LOAF (List of All Friends) as a way to share social network information through email without exposing private information.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Livingston|first1=Jessica|title=Founders at work : stories of startups' early days|date=2008|publisher=Apress|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=978-1-4302-1078-8|page=229|edition=Pbk.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ktm885vGIXEC&pg=PT237&lpg=PT237&dq=LOAF+files+are+Bloom+filters&source=bl&ots=vUyJOfRDbh&sig=vvUwFDQY1WZR24Z8bX7R_7ySR8Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjaop_qyJfKAhUP6mMKHTwqDN0Q6AEIMzAE#v=onepage&q=LOAF%20files%20are%20Bloom%20filters&f=false|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe established Pinboard in 2009 after leaving Yahoo. He had been impressed by initial versions of the bookmarking service [[Delicious (website)|Delicious]], which Yahoo had bought.<ref name=\"Entrepreneurs Who Go It Alone \u2014 By Choice\">{{cite web|last1=Dell|first1=Kristina|title=Entrepreneurs Who Go It Alone \u2014 By Choice|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2094921_2094923_2094924-2,00.html|website=Time|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> However, he felt that it had been mismanaged by Yahoo! management and that it would be possible to produce a more successful website with the same concept.<ref name=\"McEwenCassimally2013\">{{cite book|author1=Adrian McEwen|author2=Hakim Cassimally|title=Designing the Internet of Things|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iYkKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT153|date=7 November 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-43065-1|pages=153\u20134}}</ref><ref name=\"An interview with Maciej Ceglowski of Pinboard\">{{cite web|last1=Perrine|first1=Tom|title=An interview with Maciej Ceglowski of Pinboard|url=https://thuktun.wordpress.com/2011/01/03/an-interview-with-maciej-ceglowski-of-pinboard/|website=Thuktun (blog)|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Quick thoughts on Pinboard\">{{cite web|last1=Haughey|first1=Matt|title=Quick thoughts on Pinboard (review)|url=http://a.wholelottanothing.org/2010/12/quick-thoughts-on-pinboard.html|website=Whole Lotta Nothing|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Ovadia2013\">{{cite book|author=Steven Ovadia|title=The Librarian's Guide to Academic Research in the Cloud|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uGNEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124|date=30 September 2013|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-1-78063-381-7|pages=124, 172}}</ref> As of 2016, he remains Pinboard's only full-time employee. The business is a model of a small ad-free pay-for-service that emphasizes privacy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maciej Ceglowski|url=http://www.webstock.org.nz/14/speakers/maciej-ceglowski/|website=Webstock 14|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Ceg\u0142owski announced a project called the Pinboard Investment Co-Prosperity Cloud, offering $37 and promotion for six [[Startup company|startup companies]], to encourage [[Bootstrapping (business)#Financial Bootstrapping|bootstrapping]] technology companies with low costs.<ref name=\"mashable-entrepreneurs\">{{cite web |url= http://mashable.com/2012/12/18/pinboard-startup-fund/ |title= Why Entrepreneurs Are Competing for $37 From This Startup Incubator |author= Seth Fiegerman |date= December 18, 2012 |work= Business |publisher= [[Mashable]] |accessdate=December 30, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"wired-cheapest\">{{cite web |url= https://www.wired.com/business/2012/12/worlds-cheapest-venture-capitalist/ |title= Meet the World's Cheapest Venture Capitalist |author= Ryan Tate |date= December 14, 2012 |work= Business |publisher= [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=December 30, 2012 }}</ref> He awarded winners in January 2013.<ref name=\"wired-spending\">{{cite web |url= https://www.wired.com/business/2013/01/pinboard-spending/ |title= How to Spend a $37 Venture-Capital Infusion |author= Ryan Tate |date= January 21, 2013 |work= Business |publisher= [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=March 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Ceg\u0142owski entered a competition on [[Hacker News]] that would have allowed Pinboard to become a [[Y Combinator (company)|Y Combinator]] Fellow. In light of his frequent criticism of Y Combinator, he humorously described his entry as \"a tremendous, huge opportunity to fund the Bay Area's slowest-growing unicorn.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Apply HN: Pinboard \u2013 Make Y Combinator Great Again|url=https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=11441480|website=Hacker News|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>  Pinboard was not chosen for the fellowship, despite receiving the largest number of votes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tell HN: Winners of Apply HN for YC Fellowship 3|url=https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=11633278|website=Hacker News|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was credited as a technical consultant for the 2018 season of [[HBO]] sitcom [[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Maciej Ceglowski|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9730650/|website=IMDb|accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Speaking and writing ==\nCeg\u0142owski is particularly known for his conference talks on the impacts of technology, and for posting on [[Twitter]], which he uses to joke about the failings and inflated claims of [[Silicon Valley]] companies.<ref name=\"techcrunch-comments\">{{cite news |url= https://techcrunch.com/2016/04/09/dear-facebook-why-are-facebook-comments-so-unremittingly-terrible/ |title= Dear Facebook, why are Facebook Comments so unremittingly terrible?|author= Jon Evans |date= 2016-04-09 |work= [[TechCrunch]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref><ref name=\"techcrunch-money\">{{cite news |url= https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/21/and-realpolitik-for-free/ |title= Money For Nothing For Everyone |author= Jon Evans |date= 2015-11-21 |work= [[TechCrunch]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref><ref name=\"register-ifttt\">{{cite web |url= https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/03/30/love_our_open_api_talk_to_our_lawyers_says_if_this_then_that/ |title= Love our open API? Talk to our lawyers, says If This Then That |author= Richard Chirgwin |date= 2016-03-30|website= [[The Register]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref> He has written and spoken extensively on the problems of advertising-funded services with dubious business models.<ref name=\"Inside Higher Ed\">{{cite web|last1=Fister|first1=Barbara|title=Maciej Ceglowski's Internet Repair Kit|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/blogs/library-babel-fish/maciej-ceglowskis-internet-repair-kit|website=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"The Advertising Bubble\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=The Advertising Bubble|url=http://idlewords.com/2015/11/the_advertising_bubble.htm|website=Idle Words (blog)|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Doctorow\"/> He has described programatically generated advertising and data mining as a business model that encourages the growth of surveillance.<ref name=\"Doctorow\">{{cite web |last1=Doctorow |first1=Cory |title=Big Data's religious faith denies the reality of failed promises, privacy Chernobyls |url=https://boingboing.net/2015/10/07/big-datas-religious-faith-de.html |website=Boing Boing |date=2015-10-07 |accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpo-crossroads\">{{cite news |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/advertising-week/digital-advertising-at-th_b_8989994.html |title= Digital Advertising at the Crossroads: Will Angry Consumers Block Brands? |author= Zak Pollack |date= 2016-01-15 |work= [[Huffington Post]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref><ref name=\"Doctorow-\">{{cite web |last1=Doctorow |first1=Cory |title=Big Data refusal: the nuclear disarmament movement of the 21st century |url=http://boingboing.net/2015/11/03/big-data-refusal-the-nuclear.html |website=Boing Boing|date=2015-11-03 |accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref> In particular, Ceg\u0142owski has compared large stocks of data on Internet users to the archives of Communist secret police services in his native Eastern Europe, as a threat to user privacy that may increase as archives remain in existence.<ref name=\"atlantic-sin\">{{cite magazine |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/08/advertising-is-the-internets-original-sin/376041/?single_page=true |title= The Internet's Original Sin |author= [[Ethan Zuckerman]] |date= August 14, 2014 |magazine= [[The Atlantic]] |accessdate= November 13, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"What Happens Next Will Amaze You\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=What Happens Next Will Amaze You|url=http://idlewords.com/talks/what_happens_next_will_amaze_you.htm|website=Idle Words (blog)|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Persuading David Simon Gruber\">{{cite web|last1=Gruber|first1=John|title=Persuading David Simon|url=https://daringfireball.net/linked/2013/06/18/ceglowski-simon|website=Daring Fireball|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"The Internet With a Human Face\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=The Internet With a Human Face|url=http://idlewords.com/talks/internet_with_a_human_face.htm|website=Idle Words (blog)|publisher=Beyond Tellerrand Conference|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Datanami\">{{cite web|last1=Woodie|first1=Alex|title=Big Data Really Freaks This Guy Out|url=http://www.datanami.com/2015/10/01/big-data-really-freaks-this-guy-out/|website=Datanami|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref> He has also argued in favour of simplified, more minimal web design, arguing that immersive web design can be [[Software bloat|bloated]] and unsuitable for consumers with a poor internet connection.<ref name=\"Web Design: The First 100 Years\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=Web Design: The First 100 Years|url=http://idlewords.com/talks/web_design_first_100_years.htm|website=Idle Words|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"The Website Obesity Crisis\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=The Website Obesity Crisis|url=http://idlewords.com/talks/website_obesity.htm|website=Idle Words (blog)|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Is Google's Fight With Facebook Undermining a Web That's Fair to Everyone?\">{{cite web|last1=Dale|first1=Brady|title=Is Google's Fight With Facebook Undermining a Web That's Fair to Everyone?|url=http://observer.com/2016/03/google-accelerated-mobile-pages-facebook-w3c/|website=Observer|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Maciej Ceglowski on why the modern web is so bloated and slow, and why it matters\">{{cite web|last1=Gruber|first1=John|title=Maciej Ceglowski on why the modern web is so bloated and slow, and why it matters|url=https://daringfireball.net/linked/2016/01/02/website-obesity-crisis|website=Daring Fireball|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Doctorow-tools\">{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|author-link=Cory Doctorow |title=Tools, ads, and bad defaults: Web bloat continues unabated |url=http://boingboing.net/2016/01/01/tools-ads-and-bad-defaults.html |website=Boing Boing |date=2016-01-01|accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Doctorow-botwars\">{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|author-link=Cory Doctorow|title=Botwars vs ad-tech: the origin story of universal surveillance on the Internet|url=http://boingboing.net/2015/10/05/botwars-vs-ad-tech-the-origin.html|website=Boing Boing|date=2015-10-05|accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"techcrunch-block\">{{cite news |url= https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/26/i-like-to-block-it-block-it/ |title= I Like To Block It Block It |author= Jon Evans |date= 2015-09-26 |work= [[TechCrunch]] |accessdate= 2016-06-19 }}</ref> [[Cory Doctorow]] has described him as a \"characteristically provocative\" writer of \"barn-burning speeches about the Internet's problems\".<ref name=\"Doctorow-human-face\">{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|author-link=Cory Doctorow|title=The Internet With a Human Face: Maciej Ceg\u0142owski on the things we need to fix|url=http://boingboing.net/2014/05/27/the-internet-with-a-human-face.html|website=Boing Boing|date=2014-05-27|accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Botwars vs ad-tech: the origin story of universal surveillance on the Internet\">{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|title=Botwars vs ad-tech: the origin story of universal surveillance on the Internet|url=https://boingboing.net/2015/10/05/botwars-vs-ad-tech-the-origin.html|website=Boing Boing|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref><ref name='After a rush, aviation stopped \"progressing\" -- the Web might be next'>{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|title=After a rush, aviation stopped \"progressing\" -- the Web might be next|url=https://boingboing.net/2015/07/21/after-a-rush-aviation-stopped.html|website=Boing Boing|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box\n| quote = Tech companies are run by a feckless leadership accountable to no one, creating a toolkit for authoritarianism while hypnotized by science-fiction fantasy.\n| align = right\n| width = 240px\n| quoted = 1\n| author = Maciej Ceglowski, in a public appearance<ref name=\"brokeassstuart\">{{cite web |url=http://brokeassstuart.com/blog/2017/06/08/prankster-tricks-y-combinator-into-supporting-the-homeless/|title=Prankster tricks tech incubator into supporting homeless people|author=Matthew Gering|date=2017-06-08|accessdate= 2017-06-16}}</ref>\n}}\n\nCeg\u0142owski has spoken at conferences including dConstruct, [[Webstock]], [[XOXO (festival)|XOXO Festival]], [[O'Reilly Media]]'s Strata+Hadoop and Emerging Technology Conferences,<ref>{{cite web|title=Speakers - O'Reilly Emerging Technology Conference 2003|url=http://conferences.oreillynet.com/pub/w/22/speakers.html|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> the Canadian University Software Engineering Conference, and beyond tellerrand. He has spoken about his experience of running his own company, including listening to users from the fandom community and \"failing really, really slowly\", working on a project for a long time instead of looking for immediate success.<ref name=\"uk-dconstruct\">{{cite web |url= http://digital.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/2013/09/10/notes-from-dconstruct-2013/ |title= Notes from dConstruct 2013 |author= Matt Sheret |date= September 10, 2013 |work= |publisher= [[Government Digital Service]] |accessdate= December 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"wired-slowly\">{{cite web |url= https://www.wired.com/business/2013/11/the-next-big-thing-you-missed/ |title= Why the Most Ambitious of Tech Startups Should Fail Slowly |author= Ryan Tate |date= November 19, 2013 |work= The Next Big Thing You Missed |publisher= [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate= December 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Elite Daily\">{{cite web|last1=Koziara|first1=Chip|title=Why The Most Important Step In Creating A Startup Is Selling Your Idea|url=http://elitedaily.com/life/why-to-sell-ideas-now/1303877/|website=Elite Daily|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Pinboard explains why you should care about fandom\">{{cite web|title=Pinboard explains why you should care about fandom|url=https://adainitiative.org/2014/04/23/pinboard-explains-why-you-should-care-about-fandom/|publisher=[[Ada Initiative]]|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref> Ceg\u0142owski has discussed prioritising simplicity and stability over using cutting-edge technologies for building Pinboard in order to reduce cost and allow his company to remain simple and practical for a single person to run.<ref name=\"readwriteweb-boring\" /><ref name=\"An interview with Maciej Ceglowski of Pinboard\"/><ref name=\"The Website Obesity Crisis\"/> He also gave a talk about the negative effects of advertising being the economic foundation of the web, as a model that encourages the growth of surveillance.<ref name=\"atlantic-sin\"/>\n\nCeg\u0142owski writes a Pinboard blog on topics including new features, site growth, the benefits of paying for services in general,<ref name=\"guardian-goodbye\">{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/blog/2011/dec/16/goodbye-delicious-hello-pinboard-bookmarking-guardian |title= Goodbye Delicious, hello Pinboard: why we'll pay for internet plumbing |author= Charles Arthur |date= December 16, 2011 |work= Technology Blog |publisher= [[The Guardian]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref> technical aspects of running Pinboard, and critical commentary about social websites like [[Facebook]].<ref name=\"oreilly-graph\">{{cite web |url= http://radar.oreilly.com/2011/11/social-graph-cloudera-kaggle-gps-law.html |title= Strata Week: The social graph that isn't |author= Audrey Watters |date= November 10, 2011 |work= O'Reilly Radar |publisher= [[O'Reilly Media]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref> Ceg\u0142owski has discussed prioritizing speed and stability over using cutting-edge technologies for building Pinboard.<ref name=\"readwriteweb-boring\"/>\n\nHis personal blog, Idlewords, includes blog posts and short essays Ceglowski has written since 2002, mostly about travel and food, including his 36-day voyage to [[Antarctica]]'s [[Ross Ice Shelf]] in 2016 which he financed through [[Kickstarter]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=An Antarctic Appeal|url=http://idlewords.com/2015/07/an_antarctic_appeal.htm|website=Idlewords|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe has written occasional features for ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''.<ref name=\"How to Hide from the Internet while travelling\">{{cite web|last1=Ceg\u0142owski|first1=Maciej|title=I'm Going to Antarctica for the Penguins and to Hide From the Internet|url=https://www.wired.com/2016/03/how-to-ditch-the-internet-while-traveling/|website=Wired|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Meet the World's Cheapest Venture Capitalist\">{{cite web|last1=Tate|first1=Ryan|title=Meet the World's Cheapest Venture Capitalist|url=https://www.wired.com/2012/12/worlds-cheapest-venture-capitalist/|website=Wired|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> and opinion pieces for [[The New York Times]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ceglowski|first1=Maciej|title=We Need a More Forgetful Internet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2012/12/11/privacy-and-the-apps-you-download/we-need-a-more-forgetful-internet|accessdate=7 January 2016|work=New York Times|publisher=New York Times|date=2012-12-11}}</ref> His ideas have been quoted in [[Time (magazine)|Time]],<ref name=\"Entrepreneurs Who Go It Alone \u2014 By Choice\" /> [[The Atlantic]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zuckerman|first1=Ethan|title=The Internet's Original Sin|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/08/advertising-is-the-internets-original-sin/376041/|accessdate=7 January 2016|work=The Atlantic|date=August 2014}}</ref> [[The Guardian]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arthur|first1=Charles|title=Goodbye Delicious, hello Pinboard: why we'll pay for internet plumbing|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/blog/2011/dec/16/goodbye-delicious-hello-pinboard-bookmarking-guardian|accessdate=25 August 2016|work=The Guardian|date=16 December 2011}}</ref> [[The Economist]],<ref name=\"economist-fame\"/> [[TechCrunch]], [[Wired (magazine)|Wired News]],<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Thompson|first1=Clive|title=Clive Thompson on the Problem With Online Ads|url=https://www.wired.com/2011/08/st_thompson_onlineads/|magazine=Wired News|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> [[Bloomberg News#Bloomberg View|Bloomberg View]], [[Mashable]] and [[Gigaom]].<ref name=\"crunchbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/person/maciej-ceglowski#/entity |title=Maciej Ceglowski |publisher=crunchbase.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.idlewords.com Idlewords (Personal blog)]\n* {{twitter}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ceglowski, Maciej}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:Middlebury College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American technology company founders]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Yahoo! employees]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American humorists]]\n[[Category:American company founders]]\n[[Category:American software engineers]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n", "name_user": "H\u00e9cate MoonLight", "label": "safe", "comment": "1. Replace occurrences of \"Ceglowski\" with \"Ceg\u0142owski\"; 2. Poland is in Central Europe, not Eastern Europe; 3.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maciej_Ceg%C5%82owski"}
{"title_page": "Romany Jones", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{infobox television |\n | show_name = Romany Jones\n | image = \n | caption =  \n | runtime = 25 minutes\n | creator = [[Ronald Chesney]] <br>& [[Ronald Wolfe (screenwriter)|Ronald Wolfe]]\n | starring = [[Arthur Mullard]]<br>[[Queenie Watts]]<br>[[James Beck]]<br>[[Jo Rowbottom]]<br>[[Jonathan Cecil]]<br>Maureen Sweeney<br>[[Kevin Brennan (actor)|Kevin Brennan]]\n | country = United Kingdom\n | network = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] courtesy of [[London Weekend Television]]\n | first_aired = {{Start date|1972|2|15|df=y}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|1975|7|11|df=y}}\n | num_series = 4\n | num_episodes = 27\n }}\n\n'''''Romany Jones''''' is a British sitcom made by [[London Weekend Television]]. It starred [[Arthur Mullard]] and [[Queenie Watts]] as Wally and Lily Briggs and was broadcast between 1973 and 1975. The show was originally designed as a vehicle for [[James Beck]] (Private Walker in ''[[Dad's Army]]''), involving the comic misadventures of two layabout families living on a caravan site.\n\nFollowing Beck's death in August 1973 when he was only 44, Bert and Betty Jones were written out of the series, and Jonathan Cecil and Gay Soper took over the lead roles, playing new neighbours, Jeremy and Susan Crichton-Jones.\n\nThe show's pilot episode had been made by [[Thames Television]] and  broadcast in 1972. It was followed by a spin-off sequel in 1976 entitled ''[[Yus, My Dear]]'', starring Mullard and Watts.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Arthur Mullard]] - Wally Briggs\n*[[Queenie Watts]] - Lily Briggs\n*[[James Beck]] - Bert Jones ''(series 1 and 2)''\n*[[Jo Rowbottom]] - Betty Jones ''(series 1 and 2)''\n*[[Kevin Brennan (actor)|Kevin Brennan]] - Mr Gibson ''(series 1 and 2)''\n*Maureen Sweeney as Val Finch ''(series 2-5)''\n*[[Jonathan Cecil]] - Jeremy Crichton-Jones ''(series 3 and 4)''\n*[[Gay Soper]] - Susan Crichton-Jones ''(series 3 and 4)''\n*[[Alan Ford (actor)|Alan Ford]] as Ken ''(series 3 and 4)''\n\n==Episodes==\n===Pilot (1972)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! No.<br>overall !! No. in<br>series !! Title !! Writer/s !! Original Airdate\n|-\n| <center> 1 </center>|| <center> 1 </center>|| <center> Romany Jones </center>|| <center> [[Ronald Chesney]] & [[Ronald Wolfe (screenwriter)|Ronald Wolfe]]</center> || <center> {{Start date|1972|2|15|df=y}} </center>\n|}\n<br>\n===Series 1 (1973)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! No.<br>overall !! No. in<br>series !! Title !! Writer/s !! Original Airdate\n|-\n| <center> 2 </center>|| <center> 1 </center>|| <center> The More We Are Together </center>|| <center> Jon Watkins </center>|| <center> {{Start date|1973|6|8|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 3 </center>|| <center> 2 </center>|| <center> The Ring </center>|| <center> [[Ronald Chesney]] & [[Ronald Wolfe (screenwriter)|Ronald Wolfe]]</center> || <center> {{Start date|1973|6|15|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 4 </center>|| <center> 3 </center>|| <center> Run Rabbit Run </center>|| <center> [[Chris Boucher]]</center> || <center> {{Start date|1973|6|22|df=y}}\n|-\n| <center> 5 </center>|| <center> 4 </center>|| <center> A Rough Night </center>|| <center> Ronald Chesney & Ronald Wolfe</center> || <center> {{Start date|1973|6|29|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 6 </center>|| <center> 5 </center>|| <center> The Competition </center>|| <center> Geoff Rowley & Andy Baker</center> || <center> {{Start date|1973|7|6|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 7 </center>|| <center> 6 </center>|| <center> An Addition To The Family </center>|| <center> [[Myles Rudge]]</center> || <center> {{Start date|1973|7|13|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 8 </center>|| <center> 7 </center>|| <center> Look After The Pennies </center>|| <center> [[George Layton]] & [[Jonathan Lynn]]</center> || <center> {{Start date|1973|6|22|df=y}}</center>\n|}\n<br>\n===Series 2 (1973)===\n{| class=\"