yles Rudge]] || <center> {{Start date|1974|8|30|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 18 </center>|| <center> 4 </center>|| <center> The Dinner </center>|| <center> Ronald Chesney & Ronald Wolfe</center> || <center> {{Start date|1974|9|6|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 19 </center>|| <center> 5 </center>|| <center> Love Is All </center>|| <center> Henry Charles </center>|| <center> {{Start date|1974|9|13|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 20 </center>|| <center> 6 </center>|| <center> She Loves Me, That Bird </center>|| <center> Jon Watkins </center>|| <center> {{Start date|1974|9|20|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 21 </center>|| <center> 7 </center>|| <center> The Eggs </center>|| <center> Ronald Chesney & Ronald Wolfe</center> || <center> {{Start date|1974|9|27|df=y}}</center>\n|}\n<br>\n===Series 4 (1975)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! No.<br>overall !! No. in<br>series !! Title !! Writer/s !! Original Airdate\n|-\n| <center> 22 </center>|| <center> 1 </center>|| <center> The Dogsbody </center>|| <center> Jon Watkins </center>|| <center> {{Start date|1975|6|6|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 23 </center>|| <center> 2 </center>|| <center> Cold Comfort </center>|| <center> [[Ronald Chesney]] & [[Ronald Wolfe (screenwriter)|Ronald Wolfe]]</center> || <center> {{Start date|1975|6|13|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 24 </center>|| <center> 3 </center>|| <center> The Learner Driver </center>|| <center> Ronald Chesney & Ronald Wolfe</center> || <center> {{Start date|1975|6|20|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 25 </center>|| <center> 4 </center>|| <center> A Good Layer </center>|| <center> Ronald Chesney & Ronald Wolfe</center> || <center> {{Start date|1975|6|27|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 26 </center>|| <center> 5 </center>|| <center> The Washing </center>|| <center> Ronald Chesney & Ronald Wolfe</center> || <center> {{Start date|1975|7|4|df=y}}</center>\n|-\n| <center> 27 </center>|| <center> 6 </center>|| <center> A Night Out </center>|| <center> Ronald Chesney & Ronald Wolfe</center> || <center> {{Start date|1975|7|11|df=y}}</center>\n|}\n==Trivia==\n*[[Chris Boucher]], later to write extensively for science fiction shows including ''[[Doctor Who]]'', ''[[Blake's 7]]'' and ''[[Star Cops]]'', wrote the episode \"Run Rabbit Run\".\n* [[Arthur English]] played Wally Briggs in the pilot episode.\n* Mullard and Watts reprised their roles as Wally and Lily in ''[[Holiday on the Buses]]''.\n\n==DVD Release==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! DVD !! Release date\n|-\n| The Complete Series 1   || 6 June 2011\n|-\n| The Complete Series 2   || 23 January 2012\n|-\n| The Complete Series 3   || 8 April 2013 \n|-\n| The Complete Series 4   || 20 January 2014\n|-\n| The Complete Series 1 to 4 Box Set || 5 February 2018\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/guide/articles/r/romanyjones_1299002680.shtml Romany Jones at BBC Comedy]\n*{{IMDb title|id=0069623|title=Romany Jones}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100105153113/http://www.jamesbeckonline.co.uk/ James Beck Online]\n\n{{Chesney Wolfe}}\n\n[[Category:1972 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1975 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:ITV sitcoms]]\n[[Category:London Weekend Television programmes]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:1970s British comedy television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{infobox television |\n | show_name = Romany Jones\n | image = \n | caption =  \n | runtime = 25 minutes\n | creator = [[Ronald Chesney]] <br>& [[Ronald Wolfe (screenwriter)|Ronald Wolfe]]\n | starring = [[Arthur Mullard]]<br>[[Queenie Watts]]<br>[[James Beck]]<br>[[Jo Rowbottom]]<br>[[Jonathan Cecil]]<br>Maureen Sweeney<br>[[Kevin Brennan (actor)|Kevin Brennan]]\n | country = United Kingdom\n | network = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] courtesy of [[London Weekend Television]]\n | first_aired = {{Start date|1972|2|15|df=y}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|1975|7|11|df=y}}\n | num_series = 4\n | num_episodes = 27\n }}\n\n'''''Romany Jones''''' is a British sitcom made by [[London Weekend Television]]. It starred [[Arthur Mullard]] and [[Queenie Watts]] as Wally and Lily Briggs and was broadcast between 1973 and 1975. The show was originally designed as a vehicle for [[James Beck]] (Private Walker in ''[[Dad's Army]]''), involving the comic misadventures of two layabout families living on a caravan site.\n\nFollowing Beck's death in August 1973 when he was only 44, Bert and Betty Jones were written out of the series, and Jonathan Cecil and Gay Soper took over the lead roles, playing new neighbours, Jeremy and Susan Crichton-Jones.\n\nThe show's pilot episode had been made by [[Thames Television]] and  broadcast in 1972. It was followed by a spin-off sequel in 1976 entitled ''[[Yus, My Dear]]'', starring Mullard and Watts.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Arthur Mullard]] - Wally Briggs\n*[[Queenie Watts]] - Lily Briggs\n*[[James Beck]] - Bert Jones ''(series 1 and 2)''\n*[[Jo Rowbottom]] - Betty Jones ''(series 1 and 2)''\n*[[Kevin Brennan (actor)|Kevin Brennan]] - Mr Gibson ''(series 1 and 2)''\n*Maureen Sweeney as Val Finch ''(series 2-5)''\n*[[Jonathan Cecil]] - Jeremy Crichton-Jones ''(series 3 and 4)''\n*[[Gay Soper]] - Susan Crichton-Jones ''(series 3 and 4)''\n*[[Alan Ford (actor)|Alan Ford]] as Ken ''(series 3 and 4)''\n\n==Episodes==\n===Pilot (1972)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! No.<br>overall !! No. in<br>series !! Title !! Writer/s !! Original Airdate\n|-\n| <center> 1 </center>|| <center> 1 </center>|| <center> Romany Jones </center>|| <center> [[Ronald Chesney]] & [[Ronald Wolfe (screenwriter)|Ronald Wolfe]]</center> || <center> {{Start date|1972|2|15|df=y}} </center>\n|}\n<br>\n===Series 1 (1973)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! No.<br>overall !! No. in<br>series !! Title !! Writer/s 