{"title_page": "Armageddon (2005)", "text_new": "{{short description|2005 World Wrestling Entertainment pay-per-view event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = Armageddon (2005)\n|image      = Armageddon 2005.jpg\n|alt        =\n|caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Dave Batista|Batista]]\n|promotion  = [[World Wrestling Entertainment]]\n|brand      = [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]]\n|date       = December 18, 2005\n|venue      = [[Dunkin' Donuts Center]]\n|city       = [[Providence, Rhode Island]]\n|attendance = 8,000<ref name=\"PWH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/armageddon.html#2005|title= Armageddon 2005 results|publisher=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref>\n|lastevent  = [[Survivor Series (2005)|Survivor Series]]\n|nextevent  = [[New Year's Revolution (2006)|New Year's Revolution]]\n|event      = [[WWE Armageddon|Armageddon]]\n|lastevent2 = [[Armageddon (2004)|2004]]\n|nextevent2 = [[Armageddon (2006)|2006]]\n}}\n'''Armageddon (2005)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of WWE pay-per-view events|event]] produced by [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE). It took place on December 18, 2005 at the [[Dunkin' Donuts Center]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. It was the sixth annual [[WWE Armageddon|Armageddon]] chronology and was a [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]] [[WWE Brand Extension|brand]]-exclusive event.<ref name=\"SLAM!\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Sokol|date=2005-12-18|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2005/12/19/1359742.html|title=Taker-Orton rises above Armageddon|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|work=SLAM! Sports|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was a [[Hell in a Cell]] match between [[Randy Orton]] and [[The Undertaker]], which Undertaker won by [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinfall]] after performing a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Tombstone piledriver|Tombstone piledriver]].<ref name=\"Taker vs Orton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/mainevent/|title=Undertaker vs. Randy Orton in a Hell in a Cell Match|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2008-04-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080329063430/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/mainevent/| archivedate= 29 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> One of the predominant matches on the [[Card (sports)|card]] was an Interpromotional [[Professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team match]] between [[WWE Tag Team Championship (2002\u20132010)|WWE Tag Team Champions]] [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] and [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Champions]] [[Big Show and Kane]]. Big Show and Kane won the match after Kane pinned Mysterio following a [[chokeslam]].<ref name=\"WWE results\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/results/|title=Armageddon 2005 results|publisher=WWE|accessdate= 2008-04-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080331220630/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/results/| archivedate= 31 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Another primary match on the undercard was [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]] versus [[Chris Benoit]] in the fourth match of their \"[[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|Best of 7]]\" series for the vacant [[WWE United States Championship]]. Benoit won the match after forcing Booker to [[Professional wrestling#Submission|submit]] with the [[Professional wrestling holds#Crossface|Crippler Crossface]], thus earning his first victory in the series.<ref name=\"WWE results\"/>\n\n==Storylines==\nThe event featured six [[Mock combat|professional wrestling matches]] with different wrestlers involved in pre-existing [[Screenplay|script]]ed feuds, [[plot (narrative)|plot]]s and [[Narrative thread|storyline]]s. Wrestlers were portrayed as either [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]] or [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorites]] as they followed a series of tension-building events, which culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches. All wrestlers (aside from the one interpromotional match) belonged to the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]] brand&nbsp;\u2013 a [[WWE Brand Extension|storyline division]] in which WWE assigned its employees to a different program, the other being [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]].\n\nThe main event at Armageddon was fought in a [[Hell in a Cell]] match stipulation between [[The Undertaker]] and [[Randy Orton]]. The buildup to the match began at [[WrestleMania 21]], where The Undertaker defeated Orton, a [[WWE Raw|Raw]] superstar at the time, in an [[WWE Brand Extension|Interpromotional]] match.<ref>{{cite web| author=Dale Plummer and Nick Tylwalk|date=2005-04-03|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Wrestlemania21/2005/04/03/981982.html| title=Main events weak at WrestleMania 21|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|work=SLAM! Sports|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Adam|last=Martin|date=2005-04-03|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1112583710.shtml|title=WWE WrestleMania 21 PPV Results - 4/3/05 - Los Angeles, CA|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-04-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080504024106/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1112583710.shtml| archivedate= 4 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On the June 16 episode of ''SmackDown!'', during the third annual [[2005 WWE Draft Lottery|WWE Draft]], a mock sports draft lottery in which wrestlers switched programs, Orton was drafted to the SmackDown! brand. At the August pay-per-view event, [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]], Orton defeated The Undertaker, where he [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinned]] him after performing an [[Cutter (professional wrestling)#Jumping cutter|RKO]] following interference from his father, [[Bob Orton, Jr.|\"Cowboy\" Bob Orton]]. This led to a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|Handicap]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Casket match]] between Undertaker and Orton and his father at [[No Mercy (2005)|No Mercy]]. At the event, Orton and his father defeated Undertaker, and set the casket, which Orton locked Undertaker in, which was scripted to be on fire. The proceeding month, at [[Survivor Series (2005)|Survivor Series]], the Undertaker returned and attacked several SmackDown! superstars following a 5-on-5 [[Survivor Series match]] between Raw and SmackDown!. Orton, who won the match for SmackDown!, was able to escape the attack. Then, on the December 2 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Undertaker called Orton to face him inside Hell in a Cell at Armageddon, which was made official.\n\nThe pay-per-view event featured the buildup of a rivalry among two [[tag team]]s, a group of at least two wrestlers. The two groups were [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] versus [[Big Show and Kane]]. On the November 11 episode of ''SmackDown!'', an Interpromotional [[Professional wrestling match types#Hardcore-based variations|Street Fight]] match was scheduled between Batista and [[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]].<ref name=\"November 11\">{{cite news|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1131775217.shtml|title=Raw ambushes SmackDown|date=2005-11-11|work=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-12-29|publisher=wrestleview.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081122063307/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1131775217.shtml| archivedate= 22 November 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Edge, who earlier in the night, pleaded to Batista not go through the match. Batista, however, declined to cancel the match.<ref name=\"November 11\"/> Outside the arena, General Manager [[Theodore Long]] was outside talking to Raw General Manager [[Eric Bischoff]], who had just arrived to the show. As Long and Bischoff were talking, [[Chris Masters]] showed up and grabbed Long from behind and placed him in a [[Professional wrestling holds#Full nelson|full nelson]] [[Professional wrestling#Submission|submission]] hold, which he calls the Master Lock.<ref name=\"November 11\"/> After the assault on Long, Bischoff and Masters got into a limousine and drove away from the arena. Rey Mysterio, [[Matt Hardy]], and [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (JBL) got into JBL's limousine and followed Bishoff and Masters. Inside the arena, Kane and the Big Show showed up and [[Chokeslam#Double chokeslam|chokeslammed]] Batista.<ref name=\"November 11\"/> The chokeslam resulted in Batista [[Legit (professional wrestling)|legitimately]] injuring his back.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/051111.html|title=SmackDown! results - November 11, 2005|date=2005-11-11|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate= 2008-12-31| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081220200537/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/051111.html| archivedate= 20 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On the November 21 episode of ''Raw'', one of WWE's primary television programs, SmackDown! superstars, Batista, Randy Orton, JBL, Rey Mysterio, and [[Bobby Lashley]], arrived to the show's arena. The Raw superstars met the SmackDown! superstars and a brawl broke out between both rosters. The fight led to Kane and the Big Show to double chokeslam Batista on top of a car, which was scripted so that Batista could attend to his injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/051121.html|title=Raw results - November 21, 2005|date=2005-11-21|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=2008-12-31| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081220092822/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/051121.html| archivedate= 20 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On the November 25 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Batista was scheduled to defend his [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] against Orton in a [[Professional wrestling match types#No Disqualification match|No Holds Barred match]]. Batista retained his title after the Raw roster showed up to the arena and began a fight with the SmackDown! roster. Kane and the Big Show double chokeslammed Batista into the announcer's table.\n\n==Event==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+ '''Other on-screen personnel'''\n!|Role:\n!|Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=2|English [[Sports commentator|commentators]]\n|[[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]]\n|-\n|[[Tazz]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Spanish commentators\n|[[Carlos Cabrera]]\n|-\n|[[Hugo Savinovich]]\n|-\n|[[Ring announcer]]\n|[[Tony Chimel]]\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Referee (professional wrestling)|Referees]]\n|[[Nick Patrick (referee)|Nick Patrick]]\n|-\n|[[Charles Robinson (referee)|Charles Robinson]]\n|-\n|[[Jim Korderas]]\n|-\n|[[Brian Hebner]]\n|}\n\n===Pre-show===\nPrior to the [[pay-per-view]], [[Jamie Noble]] defeated [[Shoichi Funaki|Funaki]] on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]''.<ref name=\"Warned\">{{cite web|url=http://warned.net/WWEArmageddon2005.html|accessdate=2008-04-30|title=WWE Armageddon 2005 Results|publisher=Warned.net| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080503182507/http://warned.net/WWEArmageddon2005.html| archivedate= 3 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"Facts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hoffco-inc.com/wwe/ppv/ppv/arm05.html|accessdate=2008-04-30|title=WWE Armageddon 2005 Results|publisher= Hoff Co| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080504011617/http://www.hoffco-inc.com/wwe/ppv/ppv/arm05.html| archivedate= 4 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===Main card===\nThe first match was a match between [[Matt Hardy]] and [[John Layfield|JBL]] (with [[Jillian Hall]]). JBL would have most of the offense for the entire match, since at the beginning of the match, Hardy got caught up, neck first, between the top and middle rope, and stayed there for a little while as JBL proceeded to choke, punch and kick his head in. After attacking Hardy for a few minutes, JBL illegally ripped off a turnbuckle pad, sent Hardy into it and executed a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Lariat|Clothesline From Hell]] for the win.\n\nIn the second match, The Mexicools (Super Crazy and Psicosis) faced MNM ([[Adam Birch|Joey Mercury]] and [[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]) (with Melina). Psichosis and Crazy performed many high-flying moves, landing a corkscrew as well as a tope con hilo over the referee's back. Melina got involved, tripping up Psichosis and taking away his momentum. MNM used their double teaming tactics to wear down Psichosis, keeping him isolated from making the tag. Once the tag was made, Crazy controlled most of the offense for the rest of the match. Melina tried to get involved again, but was sent down for her troubles. Crazy executed a moonsault on Joey Mercury, but Johnny Nitro broke the pinfall, leading to [[Professional wrestling double-team maneuvers#Flapjack DDT|the Snapshot]] for the win.\n\nIn the third match, [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (with [[Sharmell Sullivan-Huffman|Sharmell]]) faced [[Chris Benoit]] in match four of a best of seven series match for the vacant [[WWE United States Championship]]. There were multiple chops and suplexes from both wrestlers. They seemed to be a little off their game however, floundering a bit at times. Several Crossface attempts, as well as a low blow/scissor kick combination from Sharmell and Booker all failed to win the match for both wrestlers. With Booker down, Benoit executed a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Diving headbutt|Diving headbutt]], only for a near-fall. Benoit once again went for the [[crossface]], but this time Booker rolled through and hit referee [[Jim Korderas]]. Benoit was quick to apply the [[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Sharpshooter]], forcing Booker to submit but the referee was out. Sharmell came in and hit Benoit with the broom, but that did not affect him. As he was distracted, Booker attacked Benoit, setting up for the Book End, which was reversed into a DDT and Benoit forced Booker to submit with a Crossface for the victory.\n\nIn the fourth match, [[Bobby Lashley]] faced [[William Regal]] and [[Paul Burchill]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|2-on-1 Handicap Match]]. Lashley was in control for most of the match. He used the [[Powerbomb#Inverted powerbomb|Dominator]] on Burchill to win the match.\n\nIn the fifth match, [[Juventud Guerrera|Juventud]] faced [[Kid Kash]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]. In the end, Kash went for a springboard moonsault, but caught a pair of knees to the midsection. Juventud then executed a huricanrana off the top rope, and executed a Juvi Driver for the two count. Kash countered a front flip leg drop with a [[Brainbuster#Jumping brainbuster|Dead Level]] to win the title.\n\nIn the sixth match, [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Champions]] [[Rey Mysterio]] and [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Champion]] [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] faced [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Champions]] [[Big Show]] and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] in an Interpromotional Tag Team Champions vs Champions match. Each team demonstrated their strength, with Mysterio being the only man out of place. The match evolved into a brawl, with Batista and Big Show wrestling over the broadcast table, as Mysterio executed [[Tiger Feint kick|619]] to Kane. He went for the [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Springboard hurricanrana|West Coast Pop]], but Kane caught him in midair, [[chokeslamming]] him for the win.\n\n===Main event===\nIn the main event, [[The Undertaker]] faced [[Randy Orton]] (with [[Bob Orton, Jr.|Bob Orton]]) inside [[Hell in a Cell]]. During the match, Undertaker hit Orton with a steel chair, bloodying Orton. Orton hit Undertaker with the steel steps, bloodying Undertaker also. \"Cowboy\" Bob Orton tried intervening, but Undertaker executed a Big Boot, causing the Cell and Bob to collide, causing a laceration. Orton executed a Diving Splash through a table on Undertaker for a near-fall. Orton ducked a punch from Undertaker that caught referee [[Nick Hamilton|Nick Patrick]], bloodying him as well. As referees and EMTs came down, Bob entered the Cell. Orton executed an [[cutter (professional wrestling)#jumping cutter|RKO]], but there was no referee to make the count. [[Charles Robinson (referee)|Charles Robinson]] made the count, but Undertaker kicked out at two. The Undertaker executed a [[Powerbomb#Elevated powerbomb|Last Ride]] on Orton but Bob broke up the pinfall, leading Undertaker to attack Bob. Undertaker attempted a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Kneeling reverse piledriver|Tombstone Piledriver]] on Orton but Orton reversed into a Tombstone on Undertaker for a near-fall. Bob tried to get involved again but Undertaker attacked Bob. Undertaker hit Bob and Orton with an Urn and executed a Tombstone on Bob. Undertaker executed a Tombstone Piledriver on Orton to win the match.\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn the \"Best of Seven\" series, [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]] ended up winning the vacant [[WWE United States Championship]] on the January 13, 2006 edition of [[WWE Friday Night SmackDown|SmackDown]] in [[Philadelphia]], with the help of [[Randy Orton]]. The feud between [[Randy Orton]] and [[The Undertaker]] ended in the [[Hell in a Cell]] match after the feud ran for about nine months. [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]], who were the [[WWE Tag Team Championship (2002\u20132010)|WWE Tag Team Championship]] holders at the time, lost the title to the team of [[MNM (wrestling)|MNM]] after Batista suffered a legitimate injury in early 2006, sidelining him for up to seven months. [[Big Show]] and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] continued to reign as World Tag Team Champions until April 2006.\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results = <ref name=\"WWE results\"/>\n|times = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=5062|title=WWE Armageddon 2005 \u00ab Events Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=www.cagematch.net|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n|heat1  = yes\n|match1 = [[Jamie Noble]] defeated [[Shoichi Funaki|Funaki]]<ref name=\"PWH\"/><ref name=\"OWW\">{{cite web|date=2005-12-18|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/armageddon05.html|title=Armageddon 2005 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=2008-04-22| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506022257/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/armageddon05.html|archivedate=6 May 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|stip1  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time1  = 03:30\n|match2 = [[John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (with [[Jillian Hall]]) defeated [[Matt Hardy]]\n|stip2  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time2  = 6:20\n|match3 = [[MNM (professional wrestling)|MNM]] ([[Joey Mercury]] and [[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]) (with [[Melina Perez|Melina]]) defeated [[The Mexicools]] ([[Psicosis]] and [[Super Crazy]])\n|stip3  = [[Tag team match]]\n|time3  = 8:50\n|match4 = [[Chris Benoit]] defeated [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (with [[Sharmell]]) by submission\n|stip4  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the vacant [[WWE United States Championship]]<br />Fourth in the best of seven series\n|time4  = 20:11\n|match5 = [[Bobby Lashley]] defeated [[Paul Burchill]] and [[William Regal]]\n|stip5  = 2-on-1 [[Handicap match]]\n|time5  = 3:30\n|match6 = [[Kid Kash]] defeated [[Juventud Guerrera|Juventud]] (c)\n|stip6  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|time6  = 9:00\n|match7 = [[Big Show and Kane]] defeated [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] and [[Rey Mysterio]]\n|stip7  = [[Tag team match]]\n|time7  = 8:33\n|match8 = [[The Undertaker]] defeated [[Randy Orton]] (with [[Bob Orton Jr.|Bob Orton]])<ref name=\"Taker vs Orton\"/>\n|stip8  = [[Hell in a Cell match]]\n|time8  = 30:29\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080309231549/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/ Official Armageddon 2005 website]\n\n{{WWEPPV|Armageddon}}\n{{2005 WWE pay-per-view events}}\n\n[[Category:WWE Armageddon|2006]]\n[[Category:2005 in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Events in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:2005 WWE pay-per-view events]]\n[[Category:December 2005 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2005 World Wrestling Entertainment pay-per-view event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = Armageddon (2005)\n|image      = Armageddon 2005.jpg\n|alt        =\n|caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Dave Batista|Batista]]\n|promotion  = [[World Wrestling Entertainment]]\n|brand      = [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]]\n|date       = December 18, 2005\n|venue      = [[Dunkin' Donuts Center]]\n|city       = [[Providence, Rhode Island]]\n|attendance = 8,000<ref name=\"PWH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/armageddon.html#2005|title= Armageddon 2005 results|publisher=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref>\n|lastevent  = [[Survivor Series (2005)|Survivor Series]]\n|nextevent  = [[New Year's Revolution (2006)|New Year's Revolution]]\n|event      = [[WWE Armageddon|Armageddon]]\n|lastevent2 = [[Armageddon (2004)|2004]]\n|nextevent2 = [[Armageddon (2006)|2006]]\n}}\n'''Armageddon (2005)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of WWE pay-per-view events|event]] produced by [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE). It took place on December 18, 2005 at the [[Dunkin' Donuts Center]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. It was the sixth annual [[WWE Armageddon|Armageddon]] chronology and was a [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]] [[WWE Brand Extension|brand]]-exclusive event.<ref name=\"SLAM!\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Sokol|date=2005-12-18|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2005/12/19/1359742.html|title=Taker-Orton rises above Armageddon|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|work=SLAM! Sports|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was a [[Hell in a Cell]] match between [[Randy Orton]] and [[The Undertaker]], which Undertaker won by [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinfall]] after performing a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Tombstone piledriver|Tombstone piledriver]].<ref name=\"Taker vs Orton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/mainevent/|title=Undertaker vs. Randy Orton in a Hell in a Cell Match|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2008-04-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080329063430/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/mainevent/| archivedate= 29 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> One of the predominant matches on the [[Card (sports)|card]] was an Interpromotional [[Professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team match]] between [[WWE Tag Team Championship (2002\u20132010)|WWE Tag Team Champions]] [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] and [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Champions]] [[Big Show and Kane]]. Big Show and Kane won the match after Kane pinned Mysterio following a [[chokeslam]].<ref name=\"WWE results\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/results/|title=Armageddon 2005 results|publisher=WWE|accessdate= 2008-04-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080331220630/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/results/| archivedate= 31 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Another primary match on the undercard was [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]] versus [[Chris Benoit]] in the fourth match of their \"[[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|Best of 7]]\" series for the vacant [[WWE United States Championship]]. Benoit won the match after forcing Booker to [[Professional wrestling#Submission|submit]] with the [[Professional wrestling holds#Crossface|Crippler Crossface]], thus earning his first victory in the series.<ref name=\"WWE results\"/>\n\n==Storylines==\nThe event featured six [[Mock combat|professional wrestling matches]] with different wrestlers involved in pre-existing [[Screenplay|script]]ed feuds, [[plot (narrative)|plot]]s and [[Narrative thread|storyline]]s. Wrestlers were portrayed as either [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]] or [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorites]] as they followed a series of tension-building events, which culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches. All wrestlers (aside from the one interpromotional match) belonged to the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown!]] brand&nbsp;\u2013 a [[WWE Brand Extension|storyline division]] in which WWE assigned its employees to a different program, the other being [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]].\n\nThe main event at Armageddon was fought in a [[Hell in a Cell]] match stipulation between [[The Undertaker]] and [[Randy Orton]]. The buildup to the match began at [[WrestleMania 21]], where The Undertaker defeated Orton, a [[WWE Raw|Raw]] superstar at the time, in an [[WWE Brand Extension|Interpromotional]] match.<ref>{{cite web| author=Dale Plummer and Nick Tylwalk|date=2005-04-03|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Wrestlemania21/2005/04/03/981982.html| title=Main events weak at WrestleMania 21|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|work=SLAM! Sports|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Adam|last=Martin|date=2005-04-03|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1112583710.shtml|title=WWE WrestleMania 21 PPV Results - 4/3/05 - Los Angeles, CA|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2008-04-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080504024106/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1112583710.shtml| archivedate= 4 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On the June 16 episode of ''SmackDown!'', during the third annual [[2005 WWE Draft Lottery|WWE Draft]], a mock sports draft lottery in which wrestlers switched programs, Orton was drafted to the SmackDown! brand. At the August pay-per-view event, [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]], Orton defeated The Undertaker, where he [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinned]] him after performing an [[Cutter (professional wrestling)#Jumping cutter|RKO]] following interference from his father, [[Bob Orton, Jr.|\"Cowboy\" Bob Orton]]. This led to a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|Handicap]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Casket match]] between Undertaker and Orton and his father at [[No Mercy (2005)|No Mercy]]. At the event, Orton and his father defeated Undertaker, and set the casket, which Orton locked Undertaker in, which was scripted to be on fire. The proceeding month, at [[Survivor Series (2005)|Survivor Series]], the Undertaker returned and attacked several SmackDown! superstars following a 5-on-5 [[Survivor Series match]] between Raw and SmackDown!. Orton, who won the match for SmackDown!, was able to escape the attack. Then, on the December 2 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Undertaker called Orton to face him inside Hell in a Cell at Armageddon, which was made official.\n\nThe pay-per-view event featured the buildup of a rivalry among two [[tag team]]s, a group of at least two wrestlers. The two groups were [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]] versus [[Big Show and Kane]]. On the November 11 episode of ''SmackDown!'', an Interpromotional [[Professional wrestling match types#Hardcore-based variations|Street Fight]] match was scheduled between Batista and [[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]].<ref name=\"November 11\">{{cite news|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1131775217.shtml|title=Raw ambushes SmackDown|date=2005-11-11|work=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-12-29|publisher=wrestleview.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081122063307/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2005/1131775217.shtml| archivedate= 22 November 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Edge, who earlier in the night, pleaded to Batista not go through the match. Batista, however, declined to cancel the match.<ref name=\"November 11\"/> Outside the arena, General Manager [[Theodore Long]] was outside talking to Raw General Manager [[Eric Bischoff]], who had just arrived to the show. As Long and Bischoff were talking, [[Chris Masters]] showed up and grabbed Long from behind and placed him in a [[Professional wrestling holds#Full nelson|full nelson]] [[Professional wrestling#Submission|submission]] hold, which he calls the Master Lock.<ref name=\"November 11\"/> After the assault on Long, Bischoff and Masters got into a limousine and drove away from the arena. Rey Mysterio, [[Matt Hardy]], and [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (JBL) got into JBL's limousine and followed Bishoff and Masters. Inside the arena, Kane and the Big Show showed up and [[Chokeslam#Double chokeslam|chokeslammed]] Batista.<ref name=\"November 11\"/> The chokeslam resulted in Batista [[Legit (professional wrestling)|legitimately]] injuring his back.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/051111.html|title=SmackDown! results - November 11, 2005|date=2005-11-11|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate= 2008-12-31| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081220200537/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/051111.html| archivedate= 20 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On the November 21 episode of ''Raw'', one of WWE's primary television programs, SmackDown! superstars, Batista, Randy Orton, JBL, Rey Mysterio, and [[Bobby Lashley]], arrived to the show's arena. The Raw superstars met the SmackDown! superstars and a brawl broke out between both rosters. The fight led to Kane and the Big Show to double chokeslam Batista on top of a car, which was scripted so that Batista could attend to his injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/051121.html|title=Raw results - November 21, 2005|date=2005-11-21|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=2008-12-31| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081220092822/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/051121.html| archivedate= 20 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On the November 25 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Batista was scheduled to defend his [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] against Orton in a [[Professional wrestling match types#No Disqualification match|No Holds Barred match]]. Batista retained his title after the Raw roster showed up to the arena and began a fight with the SmackDown! roster. Kane and the Big Show double chokeslammed Batista into the announcer's table.\n\n==Event==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+ '''Other on-screen personnel'''\n!|Role:\n!|Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=2|English [[Sports commentator|commentators]]\n|[[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]]\n|-\n|[[Tazz]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Spanish commentators\n|[[Carlos Cabrera]]\n|-\n|[[Hugo Savinovich]]\n|-\n|[[Ring announcer]]\n|[[Tony Chimel]]\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Referee (professional wrestling)|Referees]]\n|[[Nick Patrick (referee)|Nick Patrick]]\n|-\n|[[Charles Robinson (referee)|Charles Robinson]]\n|-\n|[[Jim Korderas]]\n|-\n|[[Brian Hebner]]\n|}\n\n===Pre-show===\nPrior to the [[pay-per-view]], [[Jamie Noble]] defeated [[Shoichi Funaki|Funaki]] on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]''.<ref name=\"Warned\">{{cite web|url=http://warned.net/WWEArmageddon2005.html|accessdate=2008-04-30|title=WWE Armageddon 2005 Results|publisher=Warned.net| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080503182507/http://warned.net/WWEArmageddon2005.html| archivedate= 3 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"Facts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hoffco-inc.com/wwe/ppv/ppv/arm05.html|accessdate=2008-04-30|title=WWE Armageddon 2005 Results|publisher= Hoff Co| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080504011617/http://www.hoffco-inc.com/wwe/ppv/ppv/arm05.html| archivedate= 4 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===Main card===\nThe first match was a match between [[Matt Hardy]] and [[John Layfield|JBL]] (with [[Jillian Hall]]). JBL would have most of the offense for the entire match, since at the beginning of the match, Hardy got caught up, neck first, between the top and middle rope, and stayed there for a little while as JBL proceeded to choke, punch and kick his head in. After attacking Hardy for a few minutes, JBL illegally ripped off a turnbuckle pad, sent Hardy into it and executed a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Lariat|Clothesline From Hell]] for the win.\n\nIn the second match, The Mexicools (Super Crazy and Psicosis) faced MNM ([[Adam Birch|Joey Mercury]] and [[John Morrison (wrestler)|Johnny Nitro]]) (with Melina). Psichosis and Crazy performed many high-flying moves, landing a corkscrew as well as a tope con hilo over the referee's back. Melina got involved, tripping up Psichosis and taking away his momentum. MNM used their double teaming tactics to wear down Psichosis, keeping him isolated from making the tag. Once the tag was made, Crazy controlled most of the offense for the rest of the match. Melina tried to get involved again, but was sent down for her troubles. Crazy executed a moonsault on Joey Mercury, but Johnny Nitro broke the pinfall, leading to [[Professional wrestling double-team maneuvers#Flapjack DDT|the Snapshot]] for the win.\n\nIn the third match, [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (with [[Sharmell Sullivan-Huffman|Sharmell]]) faced [[Chris Benoit]] in match four of a best of seven series match for the vacant [[WWE United States Championship]]. There were multiple chops and suplexes from both wrestlers. They seemed to be a little off their game however, floundering a bit at times. Several Crossface attempts, as well as a low blow/scissor kick combination from Sharmell and Booker all failed to win the match for both wrestlers. With Booker down, Benoit executed a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Diving headbutt|Diving headbutt]], only for a near-fall. Benoit once again went for the [[crossface]], but this time Booker rolled through and hit referee [[Jim Korderas]]. Benoit was quick to apply the [[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Sharpshooter]], forcing Booker to submit but the referee was out. Sharmell came in and hit Benoit with the broom, but that did not affect him. As he was distracted, Booker attacked Benoit, setting up for the Book End, which was reversed into a DDT and Benoit forced Booker to submit with a Crossface for the victory.\n\nIn the fourth match, [[Bobby Lashley]] faced [[William Regal]] and [[Paul Burchill]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|2-on-1 Handicap Match]]. Lashley was in control for most of the match. He used the [[Powerbomb#Inverted powerbomb|Dominator]] on Burchill to win the match.\n\nIn the fifth match, [[Juventud Guerrera|Juventud]] faced [[Kid Kash]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]. In the end, Kash went for a springboard moonsault, but caught a pair of knees to the midsection. Juventud then executed a huricanrana off the top rope, and executed a Juvi Driver for the two count. Kash countered a front flip leg drop with a [[Brainbuster#Jumping brainbuster|Dead Level]] to win the title.\n\nIn the sixth match, [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Champions]] [[Rey Mysterio]] and [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Champion]] [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] faced [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Champions]] [[Big Show]] and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] in an Interpromotional Tag Team Champions vs Champions match. Each team demonstrated their strength, with Mysterio being the only man out of place. The match evolved into a brawl, with Batista and Big Show wrestling over the broadcast table, as Mysterio executed [[Tiger Feint kick|619]] to Kane. He went for the [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Springboard hurricanrana|West Coast Pop]], but Kane caught him in midair, [[chokeslamming]] him for the win.\n\n===Main event===\nIn the main event, [[The Undertaker]] faced [[Randy Orton]] (with [[Bob Orton, Jr.|Bob Orton]]) inside [[Hell in a Cell]]. During the match, Undertaker hit Orton with a steel chair, bloodying Orton. Orton hit Undertaker with the steel steps, bloodying Undertaker also. \"Cowboy\" Bob Orton tried intervening, but Undertaker executed a Big Boot, causing the Cell and Bob to collide, causing a laceration. Orton executed a Diving Splash through a table on Undertaker for a near-fall. Orton ducked a punch from Undertaker that caught referee [[Nick Hamilton|Nick Patrick]], bloodying him as well. As referees and EMTs came down, Bob entered the Cell. Orton executed an [[cutter (professional wrestling)#jumping cutter|RKO]], but there was no referee to make the count. [[Charles Robinson (referee)|Charles Robinson]] made the count, but Undertaker kicked out at two. The Undertaker executed a [[Powerbomb#Elevated powerbomb|Last Ride]] on Orton but Bob broke up the pinfall, leading Undertaker to attack Bob. Undertaker attempted a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Kneeling reverse piledriver|Tombstone Piledriver]] on Orton but Orton reversed into a Tombstone on Undertaker for a near-fall. Bob tried to get involved again but Undertaker attacked Bob. Undertaker hit Bob and Orton with an Urn and executed a Tombstone on Bob. Undertaker executed a Tombstone Piledriver on Orton to win the match.\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn the \"Best of Seven\" series, [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]] ended up winning the vacant [[WWE United States Championship]] on the January 13, 2006 edition of [[WWE Friday Night SmackDown|SmackDown]] in [[Philadelphia]], with the help of [[Randy Orton]]. The feud between [[Randy Orton]] and [[The Undertaker]] ended in the [[Hell in a Cell]] match after the feud ran for about nine months. [[Dave Batista|Batista]] and [[Rey Mysterio, Jr.|Rey Mysterio]], who were the [[WWE Tag Team Championship (2002\u20132010)|WWE Tag Team Championship]] holders at the time, lost the title to the team of [[MNM (wrestling)|MNM]] after Batista suffered a legitimate injury in early 2006, sidelining him for up to seven months. [[Big Show]] and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] continued to reign as World Tag Team Champions until April 2006.\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results = <ref name=\"WWE results\"/>\n|times = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=5062|title=WWE Armageddon 2005 \u00ab Events Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=www.cagematch.net|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n|heat1  = yes\n|match1 = [[Jamie Noble]] defeated [[Shoichi Funaki|Funaki]]<ref name=\"PWH\"/><ref name=\"OWW\">{{cite web|date=2005-12-18|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/armageddon05.html|title=Armageddon 2005 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=2008-04-22| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506022257/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/armageddon05.html|archivedate=6 May 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|stip1  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time1  = 03:30\n|match2 = [[John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] (with [[Jillian Hall]]) defeated [[Matt Hardy]]\n|stip2  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time2  = 6:20\n|match3 = [[MNM (professional wrestling)|MNM]] ([[Joey Mercury]] and [[Johnny Nitro]]) (with [[Melina Perez|Melina]]) defeated [[The Mexicools]] ([[Psicosis]] and [[Super Crazy]])\n|stip3  = [[Tag team match]]\n|time3  = 8:50\n|match4 = [[Chris Benoit]] defeated [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (with [[Sharmell]]) by submission\n|stip4  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the vacant [[WWE United States Championship]]<br />Fourth in the best of seven series\n|time4  = 20:11\n|match5 = [[Bobby Lashley]] defeated [[Paul Burchill]] and [[William Regal]]\n|stip5  = 2-on-1 [[Handicap match]]\n|time5  = 3:30\n|match6 = [[Kid Kash]] defeated [[Juventud Guerrera|Juventud]] (c)\n|stip6  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991\u20132007)|WWE Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|time6  = 9:00\n|match7 = [[Big Show and Kane]] defeated [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] and [[Rey Mysterio]]\n|stip7  = [[Tag team match]]\n|time7  = 8:33\n|match8 = [[The Undertaker]] defeated [[Randy Orton]] (with [[Bob Orton Jr.|Bob Orton]])<ref name=\"Taker vs Orton\"/>\n|stip8  = [[Hell in a Cell match]]\n|time8  = 30:29\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080309231549/http://www.wwe.com/shows/armageddon/history/2005/ Official Armageddon 2005 website]\n\n{{WWEPPV|Armageddon}}\n{{2005 WWE pay-per-view events}}\n\n[[Category:WWE Armageddon|2006]]\n[[Category:2005 in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Events in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:2005 WWE pay-per-view events]]\n[[Category:December 2005 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohnny Nitro(link changed toJohn Morrison (wrestler)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armageddon_(2005)"}
{"title_page": "Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n\n| image          = Juan Sebastian Veron 2017.jpg\n| caption        = Ver\u00f3n with Estudiantes in 2017\n| fullname       = Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1975|3|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[La Plata]], Argentina\n| height         = 1.86m<ref>{{cite web |title=Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n profile |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/player/18910/juan-sebastian-veron |publisher=Sky Sports }}</ref>\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1    = 1993\u20131994 |youthclubs1 = [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes]]\n| years1         = 1994\u20131996 |clubs1  = [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes]]                |caps1  = 60  |goals1  = 7\n| years2         = 1996      |clubs2  = [[Boca Juniors]]                                       |caps2  = 17  |goals2  = 4\n| years3         = 1996\u20131998 |clubs3  = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]                           |caps3  = 61  |goals3  = 7\n| years4         = 1998\u20131999 |clubs4  = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]                                   |caps4  = 26  |goals4  = 1\n| years5         = 1999\u20132001 |clubs5  = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]                                   |caps5  = 53  |goals5  = 11\n| years6         = 2001\u20132003 |clubs6  = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]           |caps6  = 51  |goals6  = 7\n| years7         = 2003\u20132007 |clubs7  = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]                               |caps7  = 7   |goals7  = 1\n| years8         = 2004\u20132006 |clubs8  = \u2192 [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] (loan) |caps8  = 49  |goals8  = 3\n| years9         = 2006\u20132007 |clubs9  = \u2192 [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes]] (loan)       |caps9  = 30  |goals9  = 2\n| years10        = 2007\u20132012 |clubs10 = [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes]]                |caps10 = 107 |goals10 = 18\n| years11        = 2012      |clubs11 = [[Asociaci\u00f3n Coronel Brandsen|Brandsen]]               |caps11 = 28  |goals11 = 7\n| years12        = 2013\u20132014 |clubs12 = [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes]]                |caps12 = 21  |goals12 = 0\n| totalcaps = 515 |totalgoals = 68\n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20132010 |nationalteam1 = [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] |nationalcaps1 = 73 |nationalgoals1 = 9\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|ARG}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2007 Venezuela]]|}}\n}}\n'''Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8xwan se\u03b2as\u02c8tjam be\u02c8\u027eon}};{{efn-ua|In isolation, ''Sebasti\u00e1n'' is pronounced {{IPA-es|se\u03b2as\u02c8tjan|}}.}} born 9 March 1975) is a retired Argentine [[Association football|football]]er and current chairman of [[Estudiantes de La Plata]],<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/deportes/Juan_Sebastian_Veron-Estudiantes_0_1223878157.html \"Ver\u00f3n arras\u00f3 y se convirti\u00f3 en el nuevo presidente\"], ''Clar\u00edn'', 4 October 2014</ref> where he had served as Director of Sports.<ref name=director/> A former [[midfielder]], Ver\u00f3n's career started in Estudiantes, continued in Argentina's [[Boca Juniors]], and included stints in several clubs in the Italian [[Serie A]] (where he won the ''[[List of Italian football champions|Scudetto]]'' with [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] and with [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]], and a [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] with [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]), and England's [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. In 2006, Ver\u00f3n returned to Estudiantes, where he remained until his retirement in 2014, aside from a brief spell with [[Asociaci\u00f3n Coronel Brandsen|Brandsen]]. He announced his short return to first team football would occur in the [[2017 Copa Libertadores]].\n\nAt international level, Ver\u00f3n obtained 73 caps for [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] between 1996 and 2010, scoring 9 goals. He represented his nation at three [[FIFA World Cup]]s, and at the [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica]], where he won a runners-up medal.\n\nIn 2004, he was included in the [[FIFA 100]] centenary list of the 125 greatest living footballers, selected by [[Pel\u00e9]] as part of FIFA's centenary celebrations. Ver\u00f3n has both Argentine and [[Italian nationality law|Italian citizenship]]. His nickname is ''La Brujita'' {{IPA-es|la \u03b2\u027eu\u02c8xita|}} (''The Little Witch''), a nod to his father [[Juan Ram\u00f3n Ver\u00f3n|Juan Ram\u00f3n]] who was known as ''La Bruja'' (''The Witch'') and was also a championship winning player with Estudiantes.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/2003/10/04/d-05801.htm La Brujita naci\u00f3 en un cl\u00e1sico] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Estudiantes===\nIn 1993, Ver\u00f3n signed for [[Estudiantes de La Plata]] and in 1995 helped the team to return to the [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]. In 1996, he joined [[Boca Juniors]], playing 17 games and scoring three goals, alongside [[Diego Maradona]]. He made his international debut for [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] in the same year. [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] signed him for [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] shortly afterwards.\n\n===Italian triumphs and passport controversy===\n<!--copyedit-->\nIn 1998, after playing for Argentina in the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]], he signed for [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] in a [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]15-million deal. The following year, Parma won the [[1998\u201399 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] and the [[1999 UEFA Cup Final|UEFA Cup]]. Eriksson then signed him again, this time for [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] in an \u00a318.1-million deal, with Ver\u00f3n reportedly netting a weekly wage of \u00a348,000. He made his debut for Lazio in the Italian side's 1\u20130 victory over Manchester United in the [[1999 UEFA Super Cup|European Super Cup]], in [[Monaco]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nIn 2000, Ver\u00f3n was the driving force for Lazio as they captured the ''[[1999\u20132000 Serie A|Scudetto]]'', the [[1999\u20132000 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] and the [[2000 Supercoppa Italiana|Italian Super Cup]], as he scored 8 goals.<ref name=\"magician\"/>\n\nBut in February 2000 he was under investigation by Italian police for a possible fake Italian passport in order to avoid the non-EU quota. However, the charge was cleared by FIGC in June 2001, because his passport really had been issued by Italian officials, and he avoided a ban.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/internationals/players-banned-over-false-passport-scandal-675847.html|title=Players banned over false passport scandal|date=28 June 2001|accessdate=9 March 2010|work=[[The Independent]] |location=London |first=Frances |last=Kennedy }}</ref> However, a new controversy was exposed that Ver\u00f3n and his agent may have used fake documents submitted to the Italian government in order to allege to the government that Ver\u00f3n had Italian descent and granted him an [[Italian nationality law|Italian passport]], which claimed an Italian, Giuseppe Antonio Porcella was Ver\u00f3n's great grandfather Ireneo Portela.<ref name=\"show pony\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/jul/15/sport.comment |title=The \u00a328m show pony |date=15 July 2001 |accessdate=9 March 2010 |work=The Guardian |location=London |first=Simon |last=Kuper }}</ref> Manchester United even inserted a clause in the transfer document for a possible ban.<ref>{{cite news |title=Football Focus: United's `safety-net' clause in Veron deal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/leagues/premierleague/manutd/3014691/Football-Focus-Uniteds-safety-net-clause-in-Veron-deal.html |date=13 October 2001 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |location=London |first=Kevin |last=Buckley }}</ref> In July 2002, he was called to appear before Italy's state prosecutor to answer allegations he illegally acquired an Italian passport.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/2085420.stm |title=Veron faces passport charges |date=2 July 2002 |accessdate=9 March 2010 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref> Elena Tedaldi, the agent who helped Ver\u00f3n to get the passport, was jailed for 15 months,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1222732/DAN-KING-So-got-Alonso-millions-Liverpool.html |title=DAN KING: So who got the Alonso millions at Liverpool? |date=24 October 2009 |accessdate=9 March 2010 |work=Daily Mail |location=London |first=Dan |last=King }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/newcastle-sports/football-news/2008/07/14/raids-linked-to-italian-passport-probe-61634-21334569/ |title=Raids linked to Italian passport probe |date=14 July 2008 |accessdate=9 March 2010 |work=journallive }}</ref> but Ver\u00f3n and [[Sergio Cragnotti]], former Lazio chairman were acquitted in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/detalle/detallenoticias.asp?idnoticia=246917 |title=Ver\u00f3n y ex presidente de la Lazio absueltos por pasaportes falsos |date=23 February 2007 |accessdate=9 March 2010 |work=EMOL |language=Spanish }}</ref> It is because Ver\u00f3n also had Italian descent through another great-grand parent, and it was Tedaldi who used the fake documents.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ju29ro.com/altri-scandali/82-lazio-la-vera-storia-del-passaporto-di-veron.html |title=Lazio: La vera storia del passaporto di Veron |date=10 May 2007 |accessdate=9 March 2010 |publisher=ju29ro.com |language=Italian }}</ref>\n\n===Spell in England===\nAfter the 2000\u201301 season, he moved from Lazio to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 12 July for a fee of \u00a328.1 million on a five-year deal, [[Progression of the British football transfer fee record|the most expensive transfer in English football]] at that time<ref>{{cite news |title=Veron seals \u00a328.1m Man Utd move |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/1423604.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=12 July 2001 |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref> and becoming the first Non-UEFA player to break the English transfer record. On signing for Manchester United, he was quoted as saying that he had no fear of the [[Premier League|Premiership]].\n\nVer\u00f3n's first season at [[Old Trafford]] started well. In September 2001 he found the back of the net in three of Manchester United's four outings, ultimately being awarded the [[Premier League Player of the Month]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061209120649/http://www.premierleague.com/fapl.rac?command=setSelectedId&nextPage=enNewsLatest&id=466978&type=com.fapl.website.news.NewsItem&categoryCode=NewsSpecialFeatures&breadcrumb=sfsub_breadcrumb |title=Barclaycard Premiership Player of the Month 2001/02 |archivedate=9 December 2006 |url=http://www.premierleague.com/fapl.rac?command=setSelectedId&nextPage=enNewsLatest&id=466978&type=com.fapl.website.news.NewsItem&categoryCode=NewsSpecialFeatures&breadcrumb=sfsub_breadcrumb |accessdate=3 October 2009 |work=premierleague.com |publisher=[[Premier League]] |url-status=dead }}</ref> But as the season progressed and fatigue settled in, his performances declined. He would have trouble adapting to the relentlessly faster pace of the [[Premier League|Premiership]], where he was not allowed the same space and time on the ball.\n\nThere was plenty of pressure on him at the start of his second season at Old Trafford and his performances did improve considerably, especially in the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], where he excelled due to the slower tempo of the matches, scoring four goals, and was at the heart of United's successes in the group stages.<ref name=\"magician\"/> However, injury meant that he missed much of the end of the season. Questions over his performance led to an expletive-laden tirade against the media by manager [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] in support of Ver\u00f3n: \"[Ver\u00f3n] is a fucking great player\" were his parting words. \"And you're all fucking idiots.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/may/07/newsstory.sport3|title=Ferguson rages at Ver\u00f3n critics |accessdate=31 January 2009 |publisher=guardian.co.uk |location=London |first=Daniel |last=Taylor |date=7 May 2002 }}</ref> However, fans and pundits alike agreed that the signing was an expensive flop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manutdtalk.com/sir-alex-ferguson-5-worst-signings/296/|title=Sir Alex Ferguson 5 Worst Signings! - Manchester United Forum - manutdtalk.com|publisher=}}</ref> Ver\u00f3n later commented that the reason for his fitness problems and struggles with injuries at Manchester United were due to the less intense summer pre-season training in England.<ref name=\"magician\"/>\n\nWhen [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] paid \u00a315 million for him two years on, following the arrival of [[Roman Abramovich]], Ver\u00f3n claimed that he wanted to stay and fight for his place at Old Trafford but Ferguson was willing to let Chelsea talk to him and he was eventually convinced by then Chelsea manager [[Claudio Ranieri]] that his future lay at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], where he had much to prove. His transfer fee to Chelsea was about half that of his record-breaking transfer of just two years before.\n\nVer\u00f3n made an excellent start to his Chelsea career by scoring the opening goal in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Anfield]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3140907.stm|title=Hasselbaink sinks Liverpool|publisher=BBC|date=17 August 2003 |accessdate=4 November 2009}}</ref> but he fell away with injury problems as the [[2003\u201304 Chelsea F.C. season|2003\u201304 season]] progressed and made only 15 appearances for Chelsea.\n\n''[[The Times]]'' listed Ver\u00f3n's transfers to Manchester United and Chelsea among the 50 worst transfers ever in Premiership history.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article2096584.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727003744/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article2096584.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 July 2008 |work=The Times |location=London |title=The 50 worst transfers |first=Bill |last=Edgar |date=18 July 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2010 }}</ref> His several big-money transfers made Ver\u00f3n, at the time, the most expensive footballer in history, with a cumulative total of \u00a377 million.\n\n===Return to Italy===\n[[File:Juan seba veron.JPG|thumb|upright|Ver\u00f3n in training for [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]]]]\nWhen [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]] took over as Chelsea manager the following season, Ver\u00f3n was loaned out to [[Internazionale Milano F.C.|Internazionale]] initially for [[2004\u201305 Serie A|2004\u201305]], but he subsequently returned to Inter on loan for a further season. With Inter, he was part of the squad that won the [[2005 Coppa Italia Final|2005 Coppa Italia]], [[2006 Coppa Italia Final|2006 Coppa Italia]], and also by default the [[2005\u201306 Serie A|2006 Serie A]] title after [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] were stripped of the title for a [[2006 Italian football scandal|match fixing scandal]].\n\n===Returning home===\nIn mid-2006, Ver\u00f3n made it known that he wished to return to his native Argentina for the 2006\u201307 season. He received offers from [[Boca Juniors]] and [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]], but chose his boyhood club [[Estudiantes de La Plata]], of whom he is a declared fan and has made significant donations in the past to upgrade the club training facilities. Chelsea agreed to loan Ver\u00f3n to Estudiantes for a season, until the end of his contract with the English club. On 13 December 2006, he helped Estudiantes win the [[2006\u201307 in Argentine football|Apertura 2006]] tournament, its first in 23 years, in a final play-off match final over Boca Juniors. Some rival fans booed him, arguably dating back to his sub-par performances during the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], but Ver\u00f3n was ranked among the top three players in the 2006 Argentine League by sports newspaper ''Ol\u00e9''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nunca pens\u00e9 en renunciar a la Selecci\u00f3n|url=http://www.ole.clarin.com/jsp/v4/pagina.jsp?pagId=01302317&fecha=20061103|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316153904/http://www.ole.clarin.com/jsp/v4/pagina.jsp?pagId=01302317&fecha=20061103|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 March 2009|publisher=[[Diario Ol\u00e9|Ol\u00e9]]|date=3 November 2006|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his donations to the club's training grounds, Ver\u00f3n was a decisive factor in the agreement with La Plata city hall to update Estudiantes' historic stadium to modern standards. Ver\u00f3n personally engaged then Argentine president [[N\u00e9stor Kirchner]] to kick-start the negotiations, which had been stalled by La Plata mayor [[Julio Alak]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/deportiva/nota.asp?nota_id=860532 |title=La radiograf\u00eda del peor momento del f\u00fatbol argentino |work=Lanacion.com |date= |accessdate=21 July 2007 }}</ref> Ver\u00f3n indicated that he may run for Estudiantes president in the future.\n\n[[Image:Juan Sebastian Veron & Roberto Rosetti 2009 FIFA CWC.JPG|thumb|left|Ver\u00f3n & [[Roberto Rosetti]] ''(right)'' during the [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup]].]]\nIn July 2007, [[Kevin Payne (soccer)|Kevin Payne]], president of [[Major League Soccer]] club [[D.C. United]], met with Ver\u00f3n in [[Buenos Aires]] to discuss a possible transfer, but Ver\u00f3n decided to stay in Estudiantes.<ref>[http://www.ole.clarin.com/notas/2007/12/14/01564181.html Ole] {{in lang|es}}</ref> Ver\u00f3n suffered from a string of minor injuries after his return from the [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica]], and missed a number of important games during the 2007\u201308 season. In early 2008, several football personalities chose Ver\u00f3n as the best player in the Argentine league.<ref>[http://www.ole.clarin.com/notas/2008/02/21/futbollocal/01611909.html Ole] {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ole.clarin.com/notas/2008/02/19/futbollocal/01610777.html Ole] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nVeron's fitness improved in time for the 2008\u201309 season, in which Estudiantes reached the finals of the [[2008 Copa Sudamericana Finals|Copa Sudamericana]] and secured a place in the 2009 [[2009 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]].\nIn 2009, he played in the [[2009 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]] for the second time, having seen Estudiantes eliminated in the [[2008 Copa Libertadores|round of 16]] in the previous year by eventual champions [[Liga de Quito]]. After displaying his usual excellent level of play throughout the tournament, he found himself leading Estudiantes into the [[2009 Copa Libertadores Finals|final]] for the first time since 1971. The Copa Libertadores has long been a special competition for Estudiantes and its fans, ever since the team won three consecutive titles from 1968\u20131970 with Ver\u00f3n's father playing a key role on the left wing. Ver\u00f3n certainly shared this affinity for the most prestigious title in the American continent, as evidenced by his declaration before the final: \"I would trade everything I've won for this title.\"<ref>[http://www.ole.clarin.com/notas/2009/07/08/copalibertadores/01954645.html Ole] {{in lang|es}}</ref> His dream came true as Estudiantes won the final, after an aggregate of 2\u20131. A 0\u20130 tie in La Plata and a dramatic 2\u20131 win away in Belo Horizonte against [[Brazil]]'s [[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube|Cruzeiro]] sealed ''el pincha's'' triumph.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=261095&cc=5739|title=Cruzeiro 1 \u2013 2 Estudiantes La Plata|date=16 July 2009|work=ESPN|accessdate=22 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jul/16/estudiantes-veron-cruzeiro-copa-libertadores|title=Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n leads Estudiantes to Copa Libertadores triumph|date=16 July 2009|work=The Guardian|accessdate=22 September 2009 |location=London }}</ref> Ver\u00f3n was chosen by visitors to ''fifa.com'' as the best player of the 2009 Copa Libertadores.<ref>[http://es.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/newsid=1084468.html fifa.com] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nVer\u00f3n was twice elected [[South American Footballer of the Year]] (2008 and 2009) by [[Uruguay]]an newspaper ''[[El Pa\u00eds (Uruguay)|El Pa\u00eds]]'', a title that is cited worldwide.<ref>[http://www.corrieredellosport.it/Notizie/Calcio/53586/Sudamerica,+Veron+miglior+giocatore+2008 corrieredellosport.it]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/news/2008/December/31/juan-veron-wins-south-american-footballer-of-the-year-award/ |title=soccerway |publisher=soccerway |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ovaciondigital.com.uy/091230/futinter-462775/futbolinternacional/veron-fue-reelecto-como-el-rey-de-america |title=Ver\u00f3n fue reelecto como el Rey de Am\u00e9rica \u2013 Diario EL PAIS \u2013 Montevideo \u2013 Uruguay |publisher=Ovaciondigital.com.uy |date=30 December 2009 |accessdate=26 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Argentina |url=http://goal.com/en/news/585/argentina/2009/12/31/1718492/estudiantes-star-juan-sebastian-veron-named-south-american |title=Estudiantes Star Juan Sebastian Veron Named South American Player of 2009 |publisher=Goal.com |date=31 December 2009 |accessdate=26 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Returning from retirement===\nIn December 2016, Ver\u00f3n returned to professional football, signing an 18-month contract to play for Estudiantes in the [[2017 Copa Libertadores]]. Ver\u00f3n had vowed to return if fans bought 65% of the boxes at the club's new stadium, and fulfilled that promise by signing an 18-month contract; he will be given a minimum salary that will go directly back to the club for everyday operations.<ref>{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Mewis |title=Former Man United midfielder Juan Sebastian Veron comes out of retirement aged 41 to sign for Estudiantes |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/former-manchester-united-midfielder-juan-9462951 |website=Mirror.co.uk |publisher=MGN |date=15 December 2016 |accessdate=28 December 2016 }}</ref> He made his first appearance for the club since coming out of retirement in a 1\u20130 friendly victory over Bahia in the [[2017 Florida Cup|Florida Cup]], in Orlando, on 15 January 2017, playing the first half, before being substituted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/01/16/juan-sebastian-veron-comes-retirement-boyhood-club-age-41/|title=Juan Sebastian Veron comes out of retirement for boyhood club at the age of 41|publisher=The Telegraph|author1=Callum Davis|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nVer\u00f3n was called up for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] in France, where Argentina was eliminated by the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in the quarter-finals following a 2\u20131 defeat; during the match, Veron set-up [[Claudio L\u00f3pez (footballer)|Claudio L\u00f3pez]]'s goal.<ref name=\"The 10 best players of France 98\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/best-players-world-cup-france-98-zidane-ronaldo-thuram-bergkamp-suker |title=Ranked! The 10 best players of France 98 |publisher=FourFourTwo |last1=Wilson |first1=Jonathan |date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020 }}</ref> A rumour (never confirmed) that Ver\u00f3n had failed an internal doping test, and allegations of laziness hampered his relationship with the media and fans. He was called up again for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]] in [[South Korea]]/[[Japan]], where Ver\u00f3n was regarded as a key player and [[Captain (association football)|captained]] the side in place of the injured [[Roberto Ayala]]. Some fans{{who|date=May 2015}} held him personally responsible for Argentina's dismal performance, which included a loss to [[England national football team|England]] and elimination in the group phase.\n\nAfter then-national coach [[Jos\u00e9 Pekerman]] omitted him from the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] squad, his replacement, [[Alfio Basile]] recalled Ver\u00f3n to the national squad in February 2007, based on his performance in Estudiantes's 2006 championship team. Ver\u00f3n was a starter in the Argentine team that reached the final of [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica]]. Due to injuries and Estudiantes's busy schedule, Ver\u00f3n did not feature in the immediate plans of national coach [[Diego Maradona]], but was recalled to the Argentine squad as a second-half substitute in the 4\u20130 win over [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] on 28 March 2009, Maradona's first competitive game in charge of the national team. He also played in the starting XI in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualifying|2010 FIFA World Cup qualifier]] against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] on 6 June 2009 and was selected by manager [[Diego Maradona]] in the final [[2010 FIFA World Cup squads#Argentina|23-man squad]] for the finals of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].\n\nVer\u00f3n started Argentina's first [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group B#Argentina vs Nigeria|group match]] against Nigeria, and provided the assist for [[Gabriel Heinze]]'s goal. After missing the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group B#Argentina vs South Korea|match]] against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] due to injury, Ver\u00f3n returned to the starting line-up [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group B#Argentina vs Greece|against]] [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and played the full 90 minutes as Argentina won 2\u20130. He came on as a substitute for Carlos T\u00e9vez in the 69th minute in Argentina's 3\u20131 victory over [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the Round of 16, but did not feature during the quarterfinal loss to [[Germany national football team|Germany]].\n\nOn 26 August 2010, Ver\u00f3n retired from international football.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/444132-estudiantes-legend-juan-sebastin-vern-retires-from-argentina |title=Legend Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n Retires From Argentina |date=26 August 2010 |accessdate=26 August 2010 |publisher=Bleacher Report }}</ref> Nevertheless, Ver\u00f3n appeared again for Argentina in the 2011 [[Supercl\u00e1sico de las Am\u00e9ricas]], a two legged, non-[[FIFA]] sanctioned [[Exhibition game|exhibition]], between Argentina and [[Brazil national football team|Brazil's]] domestically-based players.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/945590/juan-sebastian-veron-and-juan-riquelme-given-argentina-recall?cc=4716|title=Veron and Riquelme given recall|date=18 August 2011|accessdate=18 August 2011|work=[[ESPN Soccernet]]}}</ref>\n\n==Post-playing career==\nIn December 2012, Ver\u00f3n returned to Estudiantes to work as Director of Sports of the institution. In a press conference, the president of the club, Enrique Lombardi, stated that Ver\u00f3n will not receive any remuneration for his work at the club.<ref name=director>[http://www.clarin.com/deportes/Veron-volvio-Estudiantes_0_826117544.html \"Ver\u00f3n volvi\u00f3 a Estudiantes\"], ''Clar\u00edn'', 10 December 2012</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJuan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n is the eldest son of former Argentina striker [[Juan Ram\u00f3n Ver\u00f3n]], who scored against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] for Estudiantes at [[Old Trafford]] in the [[1968 Intercontinental Cup]].<ref name=\"stayed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/juan-sebastian-veron-admits-he-should-have-stayed-at-manchester-united-and-not-joined-chelsea-a6991276.html|title=Juan Sebastian Veron admits he 'should have stayed' at Manchester United and not joined Chelsea|publisher=The Independent|author=Jack de Menezes|date=19 April 2016|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> He was born the day his father played a derby for Estudiantes against cross-town rivals [[Club de Gimnasia y Esgrima La Plata|Gimnasia y Esgrima]]. As a boy, Ver\u00f3n dreamed of playing for English club [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], as his uncle, [[Pedro Verde]], played for the club at the time. When his son started to play professionally, his father tried to persuade one of his former clubs [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]] to sign him. However, after a short trial with them, they finally decided that he was not good enough for their team. After his transfer to Manchester United, Ver\u00f3n said, \"So there I was hoping to play for Sheffield United and here I am at Manchester United!\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2003/mar/02/football.features1 'My uncle played for Sheffield United'] ''[[The Guardian]]''. 2 March 2003.</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\n[[File:Jerseys of Zanetti, Zamorano, Figo & Veron.jpg|thumb|Ver\u00f3n's Inter jersey (number 14) next to [[Iv\u00e1n Zamorano|Zamorano]] (one plus eight) and [[Lu\u00eds Figo|Figo]] (seven) in the [[San Siro]] museum]]\nVer\u00f3n was a talented, complete, influential, and versatile midfielder, who usually functioned as a [[playmaker]]; he was capable of playing both as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], and in the [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|centre]], or even [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|just in front of the defensive line]], as a [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker|deep-lying playmaker]], due to his ability to read the game, tackle, and dictate the tempo of his team's play or orchestrate his team's attacking moves from deeper positions with his passing after winning back the ball, in addition to providing assists and creating goalscoring opportunities for teammates. He could also get forward and score goals, and often functioned in a free role in midfield. A strong, athletic, tenacious, hardworking, and physical player, in his prime, he was gifted with pace, good footwork, and excellent technical ability, as well as outstanding vision, creativity, and passing range, also possessing a powerful shot from distance with either foot.<ref name=\"magician\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/features/a-magician-mistreated-fergie-and-keano-reassessing-juan-sebastian-veron-manchester-united|title=A magician mistreated by Fergie and Keano: reassessing Juan Sebastian Veron at Manchester United|publisher=FourFourTwo|author1=Emmet Gates|date=2 August 2016|accessdate=28 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804234938/http://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/features/a-magician-mistreated-fergie-and-keano-reassessing-juan-sebastian-veron-manchester-united|archive-date=4 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"The 10 best players of France 98\"/><ref name=\"magic man\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/veron-the-magic-man-of-lazio-9220346.html|title=Veron the magic man of Lazio|publisher=The Indepdendent|author1=Phil Shaw|date=15 June 2001|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fantagazzetta.com/rubriche/memento-juan-sebastian-veron-la-bruja-del-pallone-185467|title=MEMENTO - Juan Sebastian Veron, la \"Bruja\" del pallone|website=fantagazzetta.com|language=Italian|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.espn.com/soccer/blogs/blogpost?id=2950349&wjb=|title=Man United continue to struggle with fitting playmakers into their system|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Michael Cox|date=14 September 2016|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsoccer.com/uncategorized/the-hidden-depths-of-the-defensive-midfielder-333362|title=The hidden depths of the defensive midfielder|publisher=World Soccer|author1=Jamie Rainbow|date=14 January 2012|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2009/07/seba_veron_an_heir_to_cerezo.html |title=Seba Veron, an heir to Cerezo |publisher=BBC Sport |author1=Tim Vickery |date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=3 November 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2019/aug/14/the-joy-of-six-football-and-the-outside-of-the-boot |title=The Joy of Six: football and the outside of the boot |work=The Guardian |last1=Smyth |first1=Rob |date=14 August 2019 |accessdate=25 October 2019 }}</ref> He was also an accurate corner kick and [[Direct free kick|set piece]] taker, known for his powerful, [[Curl (football)|bending]] free-kicks with his right foot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/2215072/veron-the-new-free-kick-don|title=VERON - THE NEW FREE-KICK DON?|publisher=Sky Sports|author1=Matt Pomroy|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3010139/Veron-free-kick-fires-up-Ferguson.html|title=Veron free-kick fires up Ferguson|publisher=The Telegraph|author1=Steve Thomson|date=4 August 2001|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/ilcuoio/2019/03/09-54314842/juan_sebastian_veron_la_brujita_argentina_dal_piede_fatato/ |title=Juan Sebastian Veron: la \"Brujita\" argentina dal piede fatato |work=Il Corriere dello Sport |language=Italian |date=9 March 2019 |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n:Sources:<ref>{{FootballDatabase.eu|1259}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerway|10376}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerbase|13876}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-